00:16:55.080 --> 00:17:01.440
[Guest]: on a Kindle. So I will always do a lot of highlighting, and then export those highlights

00:17:01.440 --> 00:17:06.640
[Guest]: and I'll go over the highlights after I have read the book, and then try to come up with

00:17:06.640 --> 00:17:12.680
[Guest]: my own summary. So that is the process which actually it takes because finally, in a from

00:17:12.680 --> 00:17:18.000
[Guest]: a book, you can hardly take away, you know, four or five sentences that you will actually

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:24.440
[Guest]: remember after a year or so. So I want to get to that main idea in rather than the entire

00:17:24.440 --> 00:17:29.800
[Guest]: story, you know, because I find a lot of books are just historical retellings of some things,

00:17:29.800 --> 00:17:34.840
[Guest]: which you would have come across in other books as well. So finally, you want to get

00:17:34.840 --> 00:17:42.000
[Guest]: to the crux. So I'm looking for that key idea, which the aha moment which made me think Oh,

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:47.080
[Guest]: this book, I had never thought of it that way, right. So I'm always trying to pick those

00:17:47.080 --> 00:17:54.040
[Guest]: kinds of insights and visual map making or something really helps. So even now, the books

00:17:54.040 --> 00:17:59.120
[Guest]: that sort of have impacted me a lot, I've always created some mind map or some visual

00:17:59.120 --> 00:18:05.720
[Guest]: aid. Because once I put that in the mind map, you know, that just I'm able to retain that

00:18:05.720 --> 00:18:11.080
[Guest]: for longer for some reason, the other you know, and then even after a year or so, I

00:18:11.080 --> 00:18:16.080
[Guest]: at least know where in the mind map will be that idea which I was looking for. Whereas

00:18:16.080 --> 00:18:22.120
[Guest]: if I do that in notes where I type that that somehow doesn't happen. So maybe visually

00:18:22.120 --> 00:18:25.000
[Guest]: that connect works better.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:26.680
[Guest]: And what do you use to make these mind maps?

00:18:26.680 --> 00:18:33.160
[Guest]: So I use a bunch of online software available. Currently, I'm using Koggle. C O G G L E.

00:18:33.160 --> 00:18:36.360
[Guest]: It's freely available. So just I use that one.

00:18:36.360 --> 00:18:40.720
[Amit Varma]: Cool. And if you have an example of such a mind map, can I link it for my listeners?

00:18:40.720 --> 00:18:43.560
[Guest]: Or I mean, I can even post an image of such a mind map.

00:18:43.560 --> 00:18:51.640
[Guest]: Sure. Yeah, I made one for the lessons of history by Will Durant. So that's that's there.

00:18:51.640 --> 00:18:56.400
[Amit Varma]: Wonderful, wonderful. So that will be linked from the show notes in some way or form. So

00:18:56.400 --> 00:19:00.600
[Amit Varma]: getting back to your childhood, you've grown up in Goa. And at this moment, as we are piecing

00:19:00.600 --> 00:19:05.720
[Amit Varma]: together bits of your life and trying to forensically figure out what happens next, it seems likely

00:19:05.720 --> 00:19:10.360
[Amit Varma]: that you are going to end up in some form as Rahul Ravid's teammate, perhaps when he's

00:19:10.360 --> 00:19:14.640
[Amit Varma]: about to retire, and you're coming in and he hands over the baton or the bat as it were.

00:19:14.640 --> 00:19:20.040
[Amit Varma]: But that's not what happens next. So tell me a little bit about sort of how your journey

00:19:20.040 --> 00:19:21.200
[Amit Varma]: proceeds from there.

00:19:21.200 --> 00:19:27.920
[Guest]: Yeah, so I mean, yeah, I used to love cricket, but I was never good at it. So I used to be

00:19:27.920 --> 00:19:31.960
[Guest]: one of those kids. I mean, you see on the streets, we'll do this bowling action and

00:19:31.960 --> 00:19:37.440
[Guest]: then batting action and then fielding also oblivious to all the people around them. So

00:19:37.440 --> 00:19:44.680
[Guest]: I was that kind of a person, but never really good at it. So 99% hard work, 1% talent, that

00:19:44.680 --> 00:19:52.000
[Guest]: kind of person. So yeah, so I did play some cricket, but was more interested in studies

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:59.760
[Guest]: and all that. So reading wise, yeah, a lot of it was generally reading. In the earlier

00:19:59.760 --> 00:20:07.720
[Guest]: lives, it was Tinkles and a lot of Sportstar. I used to like Sportstar magazine. And I remember

00:20:07.720 --> 00:20:13.080
[Guest]: this child craft encyclopedia from the past somehow that those were the books that I used

00:20:13.080 --> 00:20:19.640
[Guest]: to like, enjoy reading, you know, something new I hadn't known. Back then, again, no internet,

00:20:19.640 --> 00:20:24.880
[Guest]: right. So and we didn't have a great library, like our school had a really small library

00:20:24.880 --> 00:20:30.800
[Guest]: and distances in Goa were huge. So no concept of a library around my house, at least for

00:20:30.800 --> 00:20:37.120
[Guest]: seven, eight kilometers. So there was one small library of our sort of the entire factory

00:20:37.120 --> 00:20:43.360
[Guest]: residing people. So I used to just pick up some books there. But I remember one thing

00:20:43.360 --> 00:20:48.880
[Guest]: earlier as to read this, when I was to go to Indore for the summer holidays, we used

00:20:48.880 --> 00:20:54.640
[Guest]: to always read these Raj comics books. Those are all not great reading, I wouldn't recommend

00:20:54.640 --> 00:21:00.880
[Guest]: to anyone, but I spent a lot of time reading those. So there was this weird mix of a grocery

00:21:00.880 --> 00:21:06.920
[Guest]: store and a library in many North Indian cities, right. So you will have people buying sugar

00:21:06.920 --> 00:21:11.720
[Guest]: and also books laying down and you can pick them up for 50 paisa for a day and give them

00:21:11.720 --> 00:21:16.640
[Guest]: back and things like that. So these were comic books, right in Hindi. So I used to read a

00:21:16.640 --> 00:21:23.480
[Guest]: lot of like that really junk reading, but that was like in the summer holidays. In our

00:21:23.480 --> 00:21:31.640
[Guest]: home we used to get Hindi newspaper daily. So read a lot of Hindi newspaper in the evenings.

00:21:31.640 --> 00:21:37.840
[Guest]: Hindi newspaper is to reach in at 4pm in the evening. So used to read that. So that was

00:21:37.840 --> 00:21:48.000
[Guest]: pretty much my like reading diet. And a lot of it was studying etc. Did 10th in Goa, did

00:21:48.000 --> 00:21:53.360
[Guest]: reasonably well I was I think, I think I was the first in the state or something like that.

00:21:53.360 --> 00:22:00.680
[Guest]: And then then went to 11th, 12th. I was always, I was fascinated by engineering, wanted to

00:22:00.680 --> 00:22:10.080
[Guest]: learn what that is. So took up the whatever science stream, 12th and etc. Then got into

00:22:10.080 --> 00:22:15.880
[Guest]: Yeah, by the way, I should also talk a lot about the failures. So like all people who

00:22:15.880 --> 00:22:22.080
[Guest]: wanted to do engineering, I started my IIT preparations at home itself, there were no

00:22:22.080 --> 00:22:28.080
[Guest]: concept of tuitions, I've never been to a tuition. So used to just read what a brilliant

00:22:28.080 --> 00:22:34.480
[Guest]: tutorials many people will relate to it. So bought those books was never it wasn't good

00:22:34.480 --> 00:22:40.400
[Guest]: enough for that. So didn't get through that. But I got to a really nice college, which

00:22:40.400 --> 00:22:46.840
[Guest]: is NIT Suratkal. It's in Karnataka. And luckily it has a beach of its own. So that was like

00:22:46.840 --> 00:22:54.000
[Guest]: some connect. And yeah, so spent four years there doing electronics engineering, again,

00:22:54.000 --> 00:23:01.040
[Guest]: something that really fascinated me. So I was really enjoying learning that. So that

00:23:01.040 --> 00:23:08.680
[Guest]: was about my engineering days. Yeah, one thing why semiconductors and things that sort of

00:23:08.680 --> 00:23:15.640
[Guest]: fascinated me was just because I even then I believe that, you know, the entire world

00:23:15.640 --> 00:23:21.160
[Guest]: that we see the change that we see is because of these chips, right? Like the way they have

00:23:21.160 --> 00:23:27.280
[Guest]: given us a new life, a lot of what we do are because of the advancements in semiconductors

00:23:27.280 --> 00:23:33.760
[Guest]: and chip making, right? So just like people say how every inkjet printer today will have

00:23:33.760 --> 00:23:39.040
[Guest]: more computing power than you know, NASA had its disposal for taking people to the moon.

00:23:39.040 --> 00:23:43.840
[Guest]: That's so fascinating, right? Like, which other technology has advanced by that way.

00:23:43.840 --> 00:23:49.400
[Guest]: So there are lots of like Moore's law and all it's just a heuristic. All those things

00:23:49.400 --> 00:23:56.360
[Guest]: sort of were fascinating. So did that work for a while? And yeah, that was my engineering

00:23:56.360 --> 00:24:02.000
[Guest]: days and then sort of wanted to continue in that field for some time. But one thing I

00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:07.200
[Guest]: knew I didn't want to go out of India like somehow I had I still have this feeling that

00:24:07.200 --> 00:24:13.560
[Guest]: I want to do something here in this country for some weird reason. But anyway, so I again

00:24:13.560 --> 00:24:21.040
[Guest]: took this GATE exam, which is there for people who want to do masters in Indian colleges

00:24:21.040 --> 00:24:26.160
[Guest]: and all. Again, I failed at that so couldn't get through that. But I got a really good

00:24:26.160 --> 00:24:32.040
[Guest]: job which was in one of the best semiconductor companies in the world. So I sort of took

00:24:32.040 --> 00:24:38.960
[Guest]: that job up in Bangalore, worked for six, seven years, enjoyed that. But then I thought

00:24:38.960 --> 00:24:44.520
[Guest]: six, seven years is a lot to be doing the same thing. In between in 2008, 9, I also

00:24:44.520 --> 00:24:50.040
[Guest]: thought, okay, let me try UPSC. Why not? You know, governance, government interested me.

00:24:50.040 --> 00:24:55.320
[Guest]: So I thought, while I'm working, let me try it. So I tried that also, and I failed there

00:24:55.320 --> 00:25:01.680
[Guest]: also. So basically, competitive exams are not my forte. And that happened. But I continued

00:25:01.680 --> 00:25:09.360
[Guest]: working there. In between continued playing cricket. So captain, my captain, my school

00:25:09.360 --> 00:25:15.320
[Guest]: team, then college team, I didn't captain but company team I captained again. So that

00:25:15.320 --> 00:25:21.480
[Guest]: was sort of one thing that I enjoyed. And after that, so the reason I mentioned cricket

00:25:21.480 --> 00:25:25.280
[Guest]: is because there is a connect to public policy there. So while I was playing cricket, one

00:25:25.280 --> 00:25:29.400
[Guest]: of the interns who was there in our team, he told me something that there is something

00:25:29.400 --> 00:25:34.360
[Guest]: called public policy. And there is something called a course at Takshashila that people

00:25:34.360 --> 00:25:41.560
[Guest]: do. And by that time, I had not heard about this word at all, right? This is 2012 or 2013.

00:25:41.560 --> 00:25:48.440
[Guest]: I have not heard about public policy. I've read blogs, I and all of Nitin and others,

00:25:48.440 --> 00:25:54.680
[Guest]: your blog, etc. I'd read that but nothing beyond that. I said, Okay, maybe I didn't

00:25:54.680 --> 00:25:59.120
[Guest]: get into the government. But there is something now to learn about the government without

00:25:59.120 --> 00:26:05.360
[Guest]: being in the government. So isn't that fascinating? So let me try that. So I took up the course

00:26:05.360 --> 00:26:11.360
[Guest]: which is GCPP graduate certificate in public policy course while I was working in a semiconductor

00:26:11.360 --> 00:26:18.920
[Guest]: company and I quite enjoyed what I learned sort of opened a completely new way of thinking

00:26:18.920 --> 00:26:24.840
[Guest]: for me. It gave me a framework to see the world and see the news in a new way. So was

00:26:24.840 --> 00:26:29.640
[Guest]: quite inspired by that. And then I thought, Okay, I have done seven years in a particular

00:26:29.640 --> 00:26:34.040
[Guest]: field. Seven years is too long to be doing the same thing. Why not try something else?

00:26:34.040 --> 00:26:38.720
[Guest]: And that's when Yeah, a lot of people in our company was like, what the hell? You can't

00:26:38.720 --> 00:26:43.920
[Guest]: even explain what you're going to do. And you're going to do that, leaving a good job.

00:26:43.920 --> 00:26:48.360
[Guest]: You know, they said, you know, see, this is the salary you might earn. And this is the

00:26:48.360 --> 00:26:53.360
[Guest]: opportunity cost of losing it. They didn't use that word. But yeah, opportunity cost

00:26:53.360 --> 00:26:58.240
[Guest]: of losing it. Do you really want to do it? So I said, like, I will try it, you know,

00:26:58.240 --> 00:27:05.320
[Guest]: let me try something for a year, which is, which I want to just because I'm really interested

00:27:05.320 --> 00:27:10.000
[Guest]: in it. If it doesn't work out, probably, I will come back, you know, so that was my

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:15.600
[Guest]: attitude. And yeah, that was 2013. So now seven years, I've been doing various things

00:27:15.600 --> 00:27:22.560
[Guest]: related to public policy. And it's been really great fun, you know, so that's how it's been.

00:27:22.560 --> 00:27:30.760
[Guest]: So a lot of failures, some luck, some privilege, and that's how where I am.

00:27:30.760 --> 00:27:33.960
[Amit Varma]: This is really scary. Now that you mentioned that you've done seven years, and I'm wondering

00:27:33.960 --> 00:27:37.840
[Amit Varma]: abhi yeh kya karega, scary and also exciting, because who knows, maybe, you know, like your

00:27:37.840 --> 00:27:41.600
[Amit Varma]: colleague Manoj failed to do, you might get into Bollywood and become a star or whatever,

00:27:41.600 --> 00:27:45.760
[Amit Varma]: one never knows. The fact that you couldn't get into government. So you decided to learn

00:27:45.760 --> 00:27:50.200
[Amit Varma]: about government from the outside. It reminds me of this great quote by Lyndon Johnson,

00:27:50.200 --> 00:27:55.360
[Amit Varma]: when Lyndon Johnson had made J. Edgar Hoover, the FBI director, and he was asked that, hey,

00:27:55.360 --> 00:27:59.560
[Amit Varma]: come on, the guy's a scumbag, you know, he's a scumbag. Why have you hired him? And Johnson

00:27:59.560 --> 00:28:04.120
[Amit Varma]: said, quote, it's probably better to have him inside the tent pissing out than outside

00:28:04.120 --> 00:28:08.680
[Amit Varma]: the tent pissing in, stop quote. So had the IAS people knew that you were going to be

00:28:08.680 --> 00:28:13.160
[Amit Varma]: outside the tent pissing in, they might well have made you an IAS officer. Let's move on

00:28:13.160 --> 00:28:17.960
[Amit Varma]: to our next question from the Twitter feed. And I really should not be reading Twitter

00:28:17.960 --> 00:28:22.920
[Amit Varma]: during a recording. This is absolutely a first, but it's justified. And this is from a Sambit

00:28:22.920 --> 00:28:27.520
[Amit Varma]: Das, who asked, how were his Surat Kal days?

00:28:27.520 --> 00:28:34.320
[Guest]: Surat Kal was great fun. Again, the entire idea is a college or a place like that is

00:28:34.320 --> 00:28:39.560
[Guest]: made by the connections that you make, right by the people who are around you rather than

00:28:39.560 --> 00:28:45.200
[Guest]: the teaching or the learning that you get from teachers per se, right. And that again

00:28:45.200 --> 00:28:50.920
[Guest]: was really fascinating at Surat Kal, just because you met people from all over India.

00:28:50.920 --> 00:28:58.200
[Guest]: So that was an NIT. I mean, it was the first year when it became an NIT. What it essentially

00:28:58.200 --> 00:29:04.880
[Guest]: meant was that you had people from all over India. So unlike IITs, in NITs there are state

00:29:04.880 --> 00:29:12.560
[Guest]: quotas. So every NIT will have, you know, one seat, probably one seat, at least from

00:29:12.560 --> 00:29:18.640
[Guest]: most states in India, you know, so you had a kind of variety that you will not have even

00:29:18.640 --> 00:29:24.360
[Guest]: in an IIT, right. So probably every state of India had a representation. So that was

00:29:24.360 --> 00:29:32.280
[Guest]: really fun, you know, so just meeting people from so many different places was really mind

00:29:32.280 --> 00:29:36.080
[Guest]: opening, you know, so I learned so much from that experience itself.

00:29:36.080 --> 00:29:40.400
[Amit Varma]: Okay, so I'm not going to distract myself with any more Twitter, we'll go to the questions

00:29:40.400 --> 00:29:44.320
[Amit Varma]: that towards the end of this episode, I'm just going to focus on the things that I'm

00:29:44.320 --> 00:29:48.400
[Amit Varma]: curious about. And the next thing I'm curious about is your engineering training in the

00:29:48.400 --> 00:29:52.400
[Amit Varma]: sense that you know, there is a term that I often use pejoratively, the engineering

00:29:52.400 --> 00:29:57.520
[Amit Varma]: mindset. And the engineering mindset is that kind of mindset where because you're so used

00:29:57.520 --> 00:30:02.320
[Amit Varma]: to doing intricate designs of things, whether it's machines or whatever, you imagine that

00:30:02.320 --> 00:30:07.920
[Amit Varma]: that same mindset can be transplanted onto public policy or economics or running a country

00:30:07.920 --> 00:30:11.840
[Amit Varma]: or governance or whatever. And obviously, we know that that's not the way the world

00:30:11.840 --> 00:30:17.480
[Amit Varma]: works that you cannot control or design anything that is too large from the top down, whether

00:30:17.480 --> 00:30:23.760
[Amit Varma]: it is society or language or markets or whatever. And it requires, you know, a great deal of

00:30:23.760 --> 00:30:29.120
[Amit Varma]: humility for someone to accept that when they have been trained their entire career, that

00:30:29.120 --> 00:30:33.400
[Amit Varma]: they have the skills and they have the intellect to design something in a perfect way, that

00:30:33.400 --> 00:30:37.760
[Amit Varma]: if they cannot do that, it's only a question of figuring out why and learning how to do

00:30:37.760 --> 00:30:44.920
[Amit Varma]: it, but it can be done. Now, one of the qualities I really like about you is this constant intellectual

00:30:44.920 --> 00:30:50.560
[Amit Varma]: humility and curiosity, where one, you know, the limits of your knowledge, you also understand

00:30:50.560 --> 00:30:55.200
[Amit Varma]: spontaneous order really well. And, you know, I also want to spend a bit of time later in

00:30:55.200 --> 00:31:00.320
[Amit Varma]: this episode discussing state market society, all of that with you, where we'll discuss

00:31:00.320 --> 00:31:04.800
[Amit Varma]: these questions in detail. But first, this question about sort of the engineering mindset

00:31:04.800 --> 00:31:08.600
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that was this something that you were plagued with? I mean, were there

00:31:08.600 --> 00:31:14.440
[Amit Varma]: aspects of the training which you felt shaped you in positive ways? And were there aspects

00:31:14.440 --> 00:31:17.600
[Amit Varma]: which you had to thrust aside or fight?

00:31:17.600 --> 00:31:24.600
[Guest]: Yeah, yeah, that's a really good question. But I think engineering actually held me in

00:31:24.600 --> 00:31:31.760
[Guest]: good stead while coming into public policy. The reason being, I think engineering is essentially

00:31:31.760 --> 00:31:37.480
[Guest]: about concerned with getting things done, right? Finally, it's about a problem solving

00:31:37.480 --> 00:31:42.640
[Guest]: mindset, you know, so you have to solve a problem. I think that is really the core of

00:31:42.640 --> 00:31:48.480
[Guest]: public policy as well. There is a goal, you need some policy to be made towards achieving

00:31:48.480 --> 00:31:53.240
[Guest]: that goal. And it will have its imperfections, it will have its trade offs, but you need

00:31:53.240 --> 00:32:00.380
[Guest]: to get that thing done, you know. So that's where I think academia and very good training

00:32:00.380 --> 00:32:05.320
[Guest]: in say, a non-engineering discipline will get you into, you know, understanding that

00:32:05.320 --> 00:32:09.400
[Guest]: problem really well. But when you have to confront the trade offs, when you have to

00:32:09.400 --> 00:32:15.120
[Guest]: make that cost benefit trade off, right? For that, I think an engineering training helps.

00:32:15.120 --> 00:32:21.660
[Guest]: So that really helped me, right? Because when we are, say, talking or proposing solutions

00:32:21.660 --> 00:32:27.360
[Guest]: to the government, or just we want to solve a particular issue, or the way we see it,

00:32:27.360 --> 00:32:33.520
[Guest]: we have to confront those trade offs. We can't say things are complex, the world is complex.

00:32:33.520 --> 00:32:37.640
[Guest]: Even this can happen, that can happen, and you can't leave it there. Finally, you have

00:32:37.640 --> 00:32:43.320
[Guest]: to bite the bullet, you have to take that stance. So I think engineering helps in that,

00:32:43.320 --> 00:32:49.480
[Guest]: you know, and like, you become comfortable with imperfections, you become comfortable

00:32:49.480 --> 00:32:54.440
[Guest]: with imperfect solutions, and yet, you want to make the world slightly better off from

00:32:54.440 --> 00:32:59.680
[Guest]: where you started with, right? So that sort of helped me from the engineering mindset.

00:32:59.680 --> 00:33:05.120
[Guest]: And we often teach this in our courses as well that public policy, like engineering

00:33:05.120 --> 00:33:10.280
[Guest]: is an applied discipline, you know, so think of biology as the science and medicine as

00:33:10.280 --> 00:33:15.720
[Guest]: a applied discipline, or physics as a science and engineering as a discipline. Similarly,

00:33:15.720 --> 00:33:20.440
[Guest]: you know, economic reasoning is the science and public policy is the applied discipline.

00:33:20.440 --> 00:33:26.880
[Guest]: So in that way, public policy is quite similar to engineering, it's about getting things

00:33:26.880 --> 00:33:33.080
[Guest]: done about solving issues, being comfortable with imperfections, you will always realize

00:33:33.080 --> 00:33:38.760
[Guest]: that you have insufficient data, insufficient time, and yet, you want to propose a way that

00:33:38.760 --> 00:33:43.440
[Guest]: might make things better off than they are now, right? So that engineering training helps.

00:33:43.440 --> 00:33:48.800
[Guest]: Yeah, where it doesn't help, like you said, right, you might have this tendency that you

00:33:48.800 --> 00:33:55.360
[Guest]: know, technocratic mindset that just do these few things, and you can control all variables,

00:33:55.360 --> 00:33:59.720
[Guest]: and the system will respond as you want to, right? But you know, even there, engineering

00:33:59.720 --> 00:34:05.000
[Guest]: has a lot to teach. It's not as if even in engineering, you have leakage currents, you

00:34:05.000 --> 00:34:09.720
[Guest]: want to do some things, but you will end up the circuit won't work the way you'd want

00:34:09.720 --> 00:34:14.760
[Guest]: it to because of some weird thing you hadn't thought about. So you try to relate those

00:34:14.760 --> 00:34:21.080
[Guest]: things as well and try to understand that, you know, perfect solutions don't exist. You

00:34:21.080 --> 00:34:28.600
[Guest]: try to make things work. So that helped. But I totally agree that that mindset is there

00:34:28.600 --> 00:34:35.360
[Guest]: and I try to keep away from it that one, I don't know enough. So that is always something

00:34:35.360 --> 00:34:40.480
[Guest]: to begin with. And the idea that you need to know so many more disciplines to even understand

00:34:40.480 --> 00:34:49.320
[Guest]: a tiny bit of society, right? infinitely complex system than a circuit, right? Human society,

00:34:49.320 --> 00:34:55.160
[Guest]: there are so many variables for any issue. Everything is multi causal. So you can't attribute

00:34:55.160 --> 00:35:00.880
[Guest]: to a particular issue very easily. So that though all those problems exist, and I think

00:35:00.880 --> 00:35:06.960
[Guest]: that humility comes for anyone who's just looking at the world as it is, you know, once

00:35:06.960 --> 00:35:13.800
[Guest]: you look at the world as it is, you will just be dumbfounded by its complexity. So you will

00:35:13.800 --> 00:35:19.920
[Guest]: try to maybe model it some way you will maybe have a system loop to try and explain, okay,

00:35:19.920 --> 00:35:26.000
[Guest]: maybe this causes this and that causes so, but then once you try putting that system

00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:31.720
[Guest]: map, so very soon it gets so complex, that you realize that, you know, it's not a system

00:35:31.720 --> 00:35:37.320
[Guest]: which can be managed like a circuit can be you know, and that that black box which society

00:35:37.320 --> 00:35:43.880
[Guest]: is itself is so complex that modeling its output is not not very easy. So I guess, yeah,

00:35:43.880 --> 00:35:49.680
[Guest]: though, there are benefits, and you also realize your limitations pretty soon, once you start

00:35:49.680 --> 00:35:50.680
[Amit Varma]: it.

00:35:50.680 --> 00:35:54.280
[Amit Varma]: I love the analogies, you draw theory and practice in the sense that, you know, physics

00:35:54.280 --> 00:35:58.560
[Amit Varma]: is a theory and engineering is a practical application, economic reasoning is a theory

00:35:58.560 --> 00:36:03.280
[Amit Varma]: and public policy is a practical application. But there is a sort of a difference in these

00:36:03.280 --> 00:36:07.560
[Amit Varma]: practical applications vis-a-vis each other. And I'm reminded of this quote, like we have

00:36:07.560 --> 00:36:12.600
[Amit Varma]: a WhatsApp group for the writing class that I had on all the writing students of the past.

00:36:12.600 --> 00:36:17.440
[Amit Varma]: So one of them, Sahil Khanwala of the Indian dream podcast, by the way, a podcast that

00:36:17.440 --> 00:36:23.080
[Amit Varma]: I once appeared on as a guest, and the first line of the show notes was something to the

00:36:23.080 --> 00:36:27.760
[Amit Varma]: effect of we will now speak to India's most famous podcaster. And I said, What is this

00:36:27.760 --> 00:36:32.960
[Amit Varma]: stuff that they've got Narendra Modi on? But no, it wasn't the brains behind monkey bath.

00:36:32.960 --> 00:36:36.880
[Amit Varma]: But anyway, so Sahil Khanwala of the Indian dream podcast said in this message that he

00:36:36.880 --> 00:36:42.160
[Amit Varma]: sent out of context, so it's, it was in a different context, but it fits this very well.

00:36:42.160 --> 00:36:45.760
[Amit Varma]: And what he said was, quote, a friend of mine once said, you know what the problem is with

00:36:45.760 --> 00:36:51.280
[Amit Varma]: being an economist, everyone has an opinion about the economy. No one goes up to a geologist

00:36:51.280 --> 00:36:57.120
[Amit Varma]: and says igneous rocks are fucking bullshit. Stop quote. And you know, igneous rocks, you

00:36:57.120 --> 00:37:01.000
[Amit Varma]: cannot argue with igneous rocks, they are there. But all these things that economists

00:37:01.000 --> 00:37:05.800
[Amit Varma]: talk about seem so counterintuitive, everyone has an opinion, everyone argues on the basis

00:37:05.800 --> 00:37:11.880
[Amit Varma]: of whatever and in the social sciences, it becomes hard to actually prove things in a

00:37:11.880 --> 00:37:16.720
[Amit Varma]: way that is convincing for everyone. So all these ideologies can flourish. So tell me

00:37:16.720 --> 00:37:20.680
[Amit Varma]: a little bit about you know, while learning public policy, what are the sort of mental

00:37:20.680 --> 00:37:24.960
[Amit Varma]: shifts that you made while learning about economics and public policy? Because I remember

00:37:24.960 --> 00:37:30.960
[Amit Varma]: when I kind of grew up as a kid in the 80s, and even hit adulthood in the 90s, such as

00:37:30.960 --> 00:37:34.720
[Amit Varma]: it is, I mean, I don't know if anyone is ever fully an adult at a certain point in your

00:37:34.720 --> 00:37:39.920
[Amit Varma]: middle age, you realize everyone is winging it. But as I gradually got older, initially,

00:37:39.920 --> 00:37:44.240
[Amit Varma]: you had this vague leftist kind of mindset that hey, the state will solve everything

00:37:44.240 --> 00:37:49.240
[Amit Varma]: and things can be planned. And you don't really understand how market works in the same exploitative

00:37:49.240 --> 00:37:52.960
[Amit Varma]: because you're looking at the world in zero some ways. And then gradually, at some point,

00:37:52.960 --> 00:37:57.800
[Amit Varma]: a light bulb goes off, hopefully, and you begin to understand how that works. And for

00:37:57.800 --> 00:38:03.040
[Amit Varma]: me, the two big light bulbs in my mind was understanding how society slash markets work

00:38:03.040 --> 00:38:07.920
[Amit Varma]: in terms of positive sumness, spontaneous order, all of those things, which changed

00:38:07.920 --> 00:38:12.600
[Amit Varma]: the way I look at the world. And the other big one was just learning about natural selection,

00:38:12.600 --> 00:38:17.400
[Amit Varma]: what it was that human beings were, you know, once you understand natural selection, and

00:38:17.400 --> 00:38:21.960
[Amit Varma]: the role of evolution and shaping us, you get so much closer to understanding human

00:38:21.960 --> 00:38:29.080
[Amit Varma]: nature and sort of also closer to rejecting false narratives like religion and so on.

00:38:29.080 --> 00:38:34.640
[Amit Varma]: So those were my kind of two light bulb moments, as it were, were there any light bulb moments

00:38:34.640 --> 00:38:39.640
[Amit Varma]: for you that you can kind of identify that suddenly, you know, once the switch comes

00:38:39.640 --> 00:38:45.880
[Guest]: on, everything kind of looks different? Yeah, I think so many concepts in basic economics

00:38:45.880 --> 00:38:52.640
[Guest]: microeconomics are like that, no, just like you said, positive some thing, right. So voluntary

00:38:52.640 --> 00:38:59.600
[Guest]: exchange being positive for both sides who are taking part in it is such a mind blowing

00:38:59.600 --> 00:39:05.000
[Guest]: concept, right. And yet, a lot of us will still not appreciate it, right. We always

00:39:05.000 --> 00:39:12.040
[Guest]: think one side is exploited, and one side is the exploiter. One person, I mean, very

00:39:12.040 --> 00:39:16.560
[Guest]: in a conference that I did, I don't know the name is so apologies for that. They use

00:39:16.560 --> 00:39:21.680
[Guest]: this word, they said, don't use the phrase haves versus have nots, but use haves versus

00:39:21.680 --> 00:39:27.680
[Guest]: want to haves. It's not haves and want to have. So it was so fascinating, right? It's

00:39:27.680 --> 00:39:32.480
[Guest]: haves versus have nots always puts you in this mindset of, there is a confrontation,

00:39:32.480 --> 00:39:37.640
[Guest]: there's never a competition or a cooperation, it's always one against the other. But reality

00:39:37.640 --> 00:39:42.400
[Guest]: is you have, everyone wants the same thing, whether it's the haves or the want to haves,

00:39:42.400 --> 00:39:48.400
[Guest]: it's just that some people already are ahead, some people are not and you know, it's,

00:39:48.400 --> 00:39:54.480
[Guest]: and it opens up the possibility of cooperation, exchange, even competition. So I think that

00:39:54.480 --> 00:40:00.880
[Guest]: was really something which I still think of. So that that is one idea. The other thing

00:40:00.880 --> 00:40:09.240
[Guest]: just the simple concept of opportunity cost is so mind blowing. And it has so many implications

00:40:09.240 --> 00:40:14.120
[Guest]: on public policy as well, especially when a state like ours, which is doing so many

00:40:14.120 --> 00:40:20.360
[Guest]: things with so less resources. For that, this idea of opportunity cost becomes so important,

00:40:20.360 --> 00:40:26.280
[Guest]: right? So there's a really nice paper, Amit, and I am saying this because I know you talk

00:40:26.280 --> 00:40:32.240
[Guest]: about this and discuss this a lot about how people think very differently when they are

00:40:32.240 --> 00:40:36.880
[Guest]: talking about what should be done with their own money, versus what should be done with

00:40:36.880 --> 00:40:42.320
[Guest]: government money, right? And the essential idea behind that is that people, we intuitively

00:40:42.320 --> 00:40:48.500
[Guest]: don't get opportunity cost. So there is opportunity cost, neglect is far more common when it comes

00:40:48.500 --> 00:40:53.640
[Guest]: to public policy, rather than when it is when it comes to personal decisions. So this is

00:40:53.640 --> 00:40:59.520
[Guest]: empirically proven. There's a paper we can link. People did an experiment, asked people

00:40:59.520 --> 00:41:03.960
[Guest]: about their decisions. And they found that when they were talking about their own decisions,

00:41:03.960 --> 00:41:09.560
[Guest]: they were always conscious of their own time, their own money, how is it being utilized,

00:41:09.560 --> 00:41:13.520
[Guest]: it won't be utilized for something else if I put into this cause. But when they were

00:41:13.520 --> 00:41:18.720
[Guest]: talking about government and public health, that was a topic they picked up. They were

00:41:18.720 --> 00:41:23.880
[Guest]: just not thinking of opportunity cost. Their belief was that the government can do everything.

00:41:23.880 --> 00:41:28.240
[Guest]: The government has infinite resources, and the government should do this. We've elected

00:41:28.240 --> 00:41:33.480
[Guest]: them. So why can't the government just make things, a utopian world come alive? Why can't

00:41:33.480 --> 00:41:39.640
[Guest]: the government do that? So that is the mindset which a lot of us start with, even I started

00:41:39.640 --> 00:41:45.360
[Guest]: with. But once you learn opportunity cost, you just know, you know that, no, that's not

00:41:45.360 --> 00:41:52.240
[Guest]: possible. To get something, you have to lose something. So there is some, you do some things

00:41:52.240 --> 00:41:56.320
[Guest]: and the government will not have time, money for other things. So why not concentrate your

00:41:56.320 --> 00:42:01.280
[Guest]: efforts on the things that governments are supposed to do, rather than what you wish

00:42:01.280 --> 00:42:09.240
[Guest]: them to do. So that was one really important idea. And then several other ideas, just generally

00:42:09.240 --> 00:42:14.680
[Guest]: about public policy. I would also begin by saying that economic reasoning is the science

00:42:14.680 --> 00:42:20.040
[Guest]: behind public policy, but it's not the only science as such. So it is, forms the core,

00:42:20.040 --> 00:42:25.320
[Guest]: but you also need, because it's an applied discipline, public policy, you will also need

00:42:25.320 --> 00:42:31.760
[Guest]: knowledge from say, social psychology, knowledge from a whole bunch of other disciplines, sociology

00:42:31.760 --> 00:42:37.560
[Guest]: and history, so many other things you need to know in order to make sense of the real

00:42:37.560 --> 00:42:41.360
[Guest]: world, right, which will be infinitely more complex than what even economic reasoning

00:42:41.360 --> 00:42:49.800
[Guest]: can tell us, you know, so that is also to be added. Going beyond that, any other idea,

00:42:49.800 --> 00:42:57.200
[Guest]: just learning about, I had written this about what people should unlearn before learning

00:42:57.200 --> 00:43:02.640
[Guest]: public policy, you know, so I just wanted to tell those things, because they were what

00:43:02.640 --> 00:43:05.240
[Guest]: hit me when I started in this discipline first.

00:43:05.240 --> 00:43:09.480
[Amit Varma]: We'll come to that next, you had made a video on it also, 8 things, which we'll link from

00:43:09.480 --> 00:43:13.840
[Amit Varma]: the show notes. And in fact, we can come to it right now. But before that, you know, just

00:43:13.840 --> 00:43:18.480
[Amit Varma]: a couple of asides. One is, as you point out, and I had mentioned earlier that, you know,

00:43:18.480 --> 00:43:23.640
[Amit Varma]: people don't go out and express their views on geology, or say how to design a rocket

00:43:23.640 --> 00:43:28.320
[Amit Varma]: to experts. But they do that in economics, because it just seems that, you know, everyone

00:43:28.320 --> 00:43:32.520
[Amit Varma]: can have a theory that can fit in different opposite theories appear to fit. And why is

00:43:32.520 --> 00:43:38.600
[Amit Varma]: that and a one reason for that is that in the social sciences, it's very hard to get

00:43:38.600 --> 00:43:42.800
[Amit Varma]: at the truth because it is so multifactorial, like a great illustration of this, which our

00:43:42.800 --> 00:43:47.640
[Amit Varma]: mutual friend Shruti Rajgopalan had once given me is that, you know, imagine you want to

00:43:47.640 --> 00:43:53.440
[Amit Varma]: find out if dropping a coin in water raises the level of the water, right? And obviously

00:43:53.440 --> 00:43:56.800
[Amit Varma]: it does, because you know, the coin is part of it. Now, it's very easy to do this in a

00:43:56.800 --> 00:44:00.320
[Amit Varma]: lab because you can take two beakers with the same amount of water and put a coin in

00:44:00.320 --> 00:44:04.000
[Amit Varma]: one and you can measure and everything is controlled. But imagine trying to do this

00:44:04.000 --> 00:44:07.840
[Amit Varma]: in a swimming pool, that you drop a coin in a swimming pool where people are splashing

00:44:07.840 --> 00:44:11.380
[Amit Varma]: around all over the place and you're trying to measure the level. And it is simply not

00:44:11.380 --> 00:44:15.640
[Amit Varma]: useful because there are so many other factors that you can't prove it one way or the other

00:44:15.640 --> 00:44:20.720
[Amit Varma]: and you will have all kinds of differing theories on it and then it just becomes an ideological

00:44:20.720 --> 00:44:26.320
[Amit Varma]: battle. So this is one way in which economics which is a study of human behaviour is kind

00:44:26.320 --> 00:44:31.160
[Amit Varma]: of different from say the study of metals or whatever, because human behaviour is so

00:44:31.160 --> 00:44:35.640
[Amit Varma]: complex and so many other things go into it, especially when you kind of zoom out of what

00:44:35.640 --> 00:44:40.320
[Amit Varma]: one individual may be thinking or doing and look at a different level. As far as positive

00:44:40.320 --> 00:44:44.520
[Amit Varma]: someness is concerned, my favourite metaphor for that is what John Stossel called the double

00:44:44.520 --> 00:44:49.840
[Amit Varma]: thank you moment. And, you know, old listeners of the show will perhaps find that I'm repeating

00:44:49.840 --> 00:44:54.660
[Amit Varma]: myself. But I love this as a metaphor, where Stossel invokes someone who goes into buy

00:44:54.660 --> 00:44:59.520
[Amit Varma]: a coffee at a Starbucks. And I mean, he didn't say Starbucks, I'm saying Starbucks, but goes

00:44:59.520 --> 00:45:03.960
[Amit Varma]: into buy coffee at a Starbucks and he pays for the coffee. And as the person hands him

00:45:03.960 --> 00:45:08.280
[Amit Varma]: the coffee, he says thank you and the person handing him the coffee says thank you. So

00:45:08.280 --> 00:45:12.040
[Amit Varma]: it's a double thank you. And what happened here is that he values a coffee more than

00:45:12.040 --> 00:45:15.800
[Amit Varma]: the money he paid for it. And the Starbucks values the money more than the coffee they're

00:45:15.800 --> 00:45:21.400
[Amit Varma]: giving out. It's a positive sum game and through such voluntary exchanges is how we all get

00:45:21.400 --> 00:45:26.000
[Amit Varma]: better off. So it's not a zero sum game. It's not that to get richer, the poor must get

00:45:26.000 --> 00:45:31.960
[Amit Varma]: poorer, which would be terrible and exploitative and dystopian. But that's actually not how

00:45:31.960 --> 00:45:35.480
[Amit Varma]: the world works. And you also mentioned this paper, which of course, I linked from the

00:45:35.480 --> 00:45:40.480
[Amit Varma]: show notes, but it reminds me of, you know, Friedman had this beautiful two by two matrix

00:45:40.480 --> 00:45:45.920
[Amit Varma]: of spending money, he pointed out that, you know, if you spend your own money on yourself,

00:45:45.920 --> 00:45:50.080
[Amit Varma]: you economize and you seek the highest value. Whereas if you spend your own money on someone

00:45:50.080 --> 00:45:53.160
[Amit Varma]: else you economize, but you don't care so much about the value because you're not the

00:45:53.160 --> 00:45:58.120
[Amit Varma]: beneficiary. If you spend someone else's money on yourself, you don't economize because it's

00:45:58.120 --> 00:46:01.680
[Amit Varma]: not your money, but you seek the highest value because you're benefiting. And if you spend

00:46:01.680 --> 00:46:07.280
[Amit Varma]: someone else's money on someone else, you don't economize and you don't seek value either.

00:46:07.280 --> 00:46:10.960
[Amit Varma]: You behave as if money falls from the sky and whatever, whatever. And that's basically

00:46:10.960 --> 00:46:14.500
[Amit Varma]: government spending, right? I want to ask you about these eight things to unlearn before

00:46:14.500 --> 00:46:19.280
[Amit Varma]: you learn about public policy. But before we go there, let's talk a little bit more

00:46:19.280 --> 00:46:23.880
[Amit Varma]: about economic reasoning. Like when I heard the phrase for the first time, I can't remember

00:46:23.880 --> 00:46:27.280
[Amit Varma]: what I thought, obviously, where were you when so and so died? Or where were you when

00:46:27.280 --> 00:46:31.000
[Amit Varma]: India won the World Cup? Where were you when you first heard the phrase economic reasoning?

00:46:31.000 --> 00:46:34.360
[Amit Varma]: I don't remember, but economic reasoning must have seemed to me very dull and boring as

00:46:34.360 --> 00:46:39.880
[Amit Varma]: if it is something to do with numbers and charts and tables and all of that. But economic

00:46:39.880 --> 00:46:45.120
[Amit Varma]: reasoning, I find is fundamental to how we make every decision we make in our lives,

00:46:45.120 --> 00:46:49.600
[Amit Varma]: at least as a good lens to look at all of that and to in fact, make better decision

00:46:49.600 --> 00:46:53.240
[Amit Varma]: and live one's life better or look back on one's mistakes. So tell me a little bit more

00:46:53.240 --> 00:46:57.440
[Amit Varma]: about what you understand by the term economic reasoning and how your process of learning

00:46:57.440 --> 00:47:04.800
[Guest]: it and teaching it was. Yeah, so just adding to what you just mentioned before, Amit, about

00:47:04.800 --> 00:47:10.120
[Guest]: the comparison of throwing a coin in a lake and seeing the water rise. Yeah, the difference

00:47:10.120 --> 00:47:16.400
[Guest]: is that the respondents on of anything that the government does have agency of their own,

00:47:16.400 --> 00:47:23.520
[Guest]: right. So and the way they work, their motivations will be so vastly different, that even economic

00:47:23.520 --> 00:47:28.880
[Guest]: reasoning by itself cannot capture all those, right. So there's a great book by Tyler Cowen,

00:47:28.880 --> 00:47:33.600
[Guest]: right, Discovering Your Inner Economist. And he also writes about, you know, economists

00:47:33.600 --> 00:47:38.120
[Guest]: also often make a caricature of themselves by saying that, you know, just you know how

00:47:38.120 --> 00:47:42.680
[Guest]: incentives work, and then you can say how the world works. That's not how it is, you

00:47:42.680 --> 00:47:48.360
[Guest]: know, even incentives are so complex, the cultural context varies, the incentive of

00:47:48.360 --> 00:47:54.920
[Guest]: a person in India might be very different from the incentive of a similarly placed person

00:47:54.920 --> 00:48:01.160
[Guest]: in the US. So understanding that cultural context, understanding why people think the

00:48:01.160 --> 00:48:07.320
[Guest]: way they do is so important to understanding, even making some sense of the world. So that's

00:48:07.320 --> 00:48:12.200
[Guest]: why along with economic reasoning, you would need so many other disciplines to just make

00:48:12.200 --> 00:48:17.480
[Guest]: some sense of these motivations, right. Be that as it may, now when we think of economic

00:48:17.480 --> 00:48:23.960
[Guest]: reasoning itself, one really powerful insight that economic reasoning sort of gives me is,

00:48:23.960 --> 00:48:30.000
[Guest]: it helps you to anticipate the unintended, right. So one great thing that I had learned,

00:48:30.000 --> 00:48:36.800
[Guest]: and this was by a lecture by Pratap Bhanumetha himself, he mentioned in a class that not

00:48:36.800 --> 00:48:43.600
[Guest]: everything that is unintended is unanticipated, right. So you generally when people have this

00:48:43.600 --> 00:48:49.960
[Guest]: conception of something going wrong by the government, we often say that was unintended

00:48:49.960 --> 00:48:55.120
[Guest]: effects, right, like, whatever, demonetization happened, but yeah, unintended effects, some

00:48:55.120 --> 00:48:59.880
[Guest]: good happened, but how can the government have predicted what can happen? So it was

00:48:59.880 --> 00:49:04.600
[Guest]: unintended, right. But the key insight is that no, that's not the way it is, you know,

00:49:04.600 --> 00:49:10.480
[Guest]: you can anticipate some things which are unintended, even before a policy is done. So you don't

00:49:10.480 --> 00:49:15.440
[Guest]: need to actually experiment on millions of citizens and then figure out that, you know,

00:49:15.440 --> 00:49:21.480
[Guest]: when you put a price cap, that item will just stop selling or quality will degrade. You

00:49:21.480 --> 00:49:26.240
[Guest]: absolutely don't need to do that and learn, but we still do that, right, the government

00:49:26.240 --> 00:49:31.040
[Guest]: will still price stents and then figure out, oh, stents have disappeared, why have that

00:49:31.040 --> 00:49:36.240
[Guest]: happened? So economic reasoning is what gives you that lens, right, you are able to, a key

00:49:36.240 --> 00:49:41.040
[Guest]: component of anticipating the unintended, if you know basic economic reasoning, right.

00:49:41.040 --> 00:49:45.560
[Guest]: So if you know what will happen when you put a price floor, if you know what happens when

00:49:45.560 --> 00:49:50.360
[Guest]: price cap is put, when a tax is put, there will be deadweight losses, you know, so such

00:49:50.360 --> 00:49:56.560
[Guest]: things if you have in mind, you are really able to make better public policies, right.

00:49:56.560 --> 00:50:01.040
[Guest]: So that's why even in our teaching, we always tell people, however uncomfortable you are

00:50:01.040 --> 00:50:06.040
[Guest]: with this word economics, there's no way around it when you are in public policy, irrespective

00:50:06.040 --> 00:50:10.680
[Guest]: of the discipline that you are, you know, you might be doing things in environment policy

00:50:10.680 --> 00:50:18.120
[Guest]: or climate change policy, or even local government related policy, you will still need economic

00:50:18.120 --> 00:50:23.440
[Guest]: reasoning, which is, many times people don't start with that prior, right, they think like

00:50:23.440 --> 00:50:28.600
[Guest]: economics is just one subject, which you have to learn, you have to get credits for, but

00:50:28.600 --> 00:50:35.000
[Guest]: it's not that way, you know, it is a discipline that runs across all domains of public policy.

00:50:35.000 --> 00:50:41.440
[Guest]: So being armed with certain tools from that particular discipline is really key.

00:50:41.440 --> 00:50:47.680
[Guest]: And it will help you anticipate the unintended and stop and it won't allow you to make stupid

00:50:47.680 --> 00:50:52.440
[Guest]: policies, right, you will be able to at least say that, yeah, this sounds great, everyone

00:50:52.440 --> 00:50:57.120
[Guest]: benefits, there's a great policy, but then you will be able to say, okay, there are things

00:50:57.120 --> 00:51:00.220
[Guest]: that might go wrong if you apply the economic reasoning.

00:51:00.220 --> 00:51:04.160
[Guest]: So that is like one big idea that economic reasoning helps in.

00:51:04.160 --> 00:51:09.320
[Guest]: The second thing is about just this idea of marginal cost and marginal benefit, right.

00:51:09.320 --> 00:51:15.600
[Guest]: So economic reasoning is very consequentialist in its approach, right, so it is always thinking

00:51:15.600 --> 00:51:19.320
[Guest]: of consequences, not intentions and things like that.

00:51:19.320 --> 00:51:26.720
[Guest]: So in policy that matters a lot, right, you have interested people to do something, you

00:51:26.720 --> 00:51:32.120
[Guest]: are electing them, there is a huge amount of money that is at their disposal, force

00:51:32.120 --> 00:51:33.240
[Guest]: at their disposal.

00:51:33.240 --> 00:51:36.720
[Guest]: So you want them to be judged by consequences, right.

00:51:36.720 --> 00:51:42.680
[Guest]: So that's why what happens is having marginal cost and marginal benefit and comparing whether

00:51:42.680 --> 00:51:47.960
[Guest]: a policy should be done based on benefits exceeding cost is important.

00:51:47.960 --> 00:51:53.240
[Guest]: Often you will notice, Amit, people will justify a policy based on just the good that it can

00:51:53.240 --> 00:51:54.240
[Guest]: bring, right.

00:51:54.240 --> 00:51:59.960
[Guest]: So we'll just say, oh, CSR policy is so great, corporate social responsibility, because I

00:51:59.960 --> 00:52:04.280
[Guest]: saw a lake near my house, which is so well done.

00:52:04.280 --> 00:52:06.760
[Guest]: And that's why CSR policy should be implemented.

00:52:06.760 --> 00:52:09.840
[Guest]: So you're just looking at a small benefit of that policy.

00:52:09.840 --> 00:52:14.900
[Guest]: But what were the costs of that, you know, what could that money have been better utilized

00:52:14.900 --> 00:52:22.440
[Guest]: by the company itself, instead of you having it to submit to the government or your government

00:52:22.440 --> 00:52:24.680
[Guest]: forcing you to do that particular thing, right.

00:52:24.680 --> 00:52:31.040
[Guest]: So those costs need to be kept in mind, and that is a key idea, I think economic reasoning

00:52:31.040 --> 00:52:32.600
[Guest]: again can teach.

00:52:32.600 --> 00:52:38.040
[Guest]: The next like really mind blowing insight is just market failures, right, that codification

00:52:38.040 --> 00:52:44.320
[Guest]: of four or five kinds of market failures gives you such a real, really important lens to

00:52:44.320 --> 00:52:45.360
[Guest]: look at the world, right.

00:52:45.360 --> 00:52:49.400
[Guest]: So when you see pollution happens, right, you try to think of, okay, what is the market

00:52:49.400 --> 00:52:50.400
[Guest]: failure?

00:52:50.400 --> 00:52:55.880
[Guest]: And then once you think of, okay, once this is the particular type of market failure,

00:52:55.880 --> 00:53:00.520
[Guest]: then you can map a government solution to that particular market failure.

00:53:00.520 --> 00:53:05.960
[Guest]: So I think you had Ajay Shah on the podcast a couple of times, and his book does this

00:53:05.960 --> 00:53:08.200
[Guest]: really well.

00:53:08.200 --> 00:53:13.520
[Guest]: But I'll still repeat it just for people who might be interested, that the fact that we

00:53:13.520 --> 00:53:15.720
[Guest]: know there are four or five market failures, right.

00:53:15.720 --> 00:53:22.720
[Guest]: So you have a negative externalities, positive externalities, market power, information asymmetry

00:53:22.720 --> 00:53:23.720
[Guest]: and public goods.

00:53:23.720 --> 00:53:25.140
[Guest]: So broadly five.

00:53:25.140 --> 00:53:29.680
[Guest]: So once you are able to classify a failure, let's look at vaccines, right.

00:53:29.680 --> 00:53:33.440
[Guest]: So first question you ask is, okay, what should government do about vaccines?

00:53:33.440 --> 00:53:35.800
[Guest]: So then you ask, what is the market failure, right?

00:53:35.800 --> 00:53:37.920
[Guest]: So is it a public good?

00:53:37.920 --> 00:53:41.760
[Guest]: Is it a negative externality, positive externality, whatever, right.

00:53:41.760 --> 00:53:45.400
[Guest]: And a lot of people would think vaccines are public goods, which they are not, right.

00:53:45.400 --> 00:53:49.080
[Guest]: So they are private goods with positive externalities, right.

00:53:49.080 --> 00:53:53.600
[Guest]: So you taking a vaccine benefits me, even though I'm not involved in that transaction.

00:53:53.600 --> 00:53:56.000
[Guest]: So that is what a positive externality is.

00:53:56.000 --> 00:54:02.880
[Guest]: So now once you know what a market failure is, you can map which government action is

00:54:02.880 --> 00:54:06.400
[Guest]: best suited for that kind of market failure, right.

00:54:06.400 --> 00:54:11.120
[Guest]: And in the Shah and Kelkar book, they had these three ideas, right.

00:54:11.120 --> 00:54:12.680
[Guest]: Produce, finance, regulate.

00:54:12.680 --> 00:54:17.760
[Guest]: And you know that once you have something which is positive externalities, that's a

00:54:17.760 --> 00:54:23.080
[Guest]: market failure, the best government intervention would be to finance the recipients, right.

00:54:23.080 --> 00:54:28.240
[Guest]: So in this case, it would be you give vaccines for free, right, or you subsidize it or whatever.

00:54:28.240 --> 00:54:33.160
[Guest]: So it gives you a solution just by thinking in a structured way, right.

00:54:33.160 --> 00:54:37.120
[Guest]: Think of the market failure, think of what are the possible solutions.

00:54:37.120 --> 00:54:42.600
[Guest]: But instead, people might often think that, oh, vaccines are public goods, so government

00:54:42.600 --> 00:54:44.040
[Guest]: should even produce it.

00:54:44.040 --> 00:54:50.920
[Guest]: And then you enter into a whole different idea of governments trying to build its capacity

00:54:50.920 --> 00:54:56.240
[Guest]: to make vaccines, to produce vaccines, and we know how that would work out, right.

00:54:56.240 --> 00:55:00.800
[Guest]: So just this idea of having market failures and thinking that, you know, if there's a

00:55:00.800 --> 00:55:05.400
[Guest]: positive externality, financing may be a best solution.

00:55:05.400 --> 00:55:09.760
[Guest]: If it's a public good market failure, then maybe government production is justified to

00:55:09.760 --> 00:55:10.760
[Guest]: a sense.

00:55:10.760 --> 00:55:15.160
[Guest]: And if there are the other market failures, negative externalities, market power or information

00:55:15.160 --> 00:55:20.960
[Guest]: asymmetry, best ways for regulation, one way or the other, governments come in to stop

00:55:20.960 --> 00:55:25.720
[Guest]: the excesses of people who are deviating from the law, right.

00:55:25.720 --> 00:55:32.320
[Guest]: And this is such an important framework, right, if we just learn this, maybe we'll demand

00:55:32.320 --> 00:55:37.960
[Guest]: better policies and understand when governments take other routes, right.

00:55:37.960 --> 00:55:44.200
[Guest]: So yeah, this was like, the main ideas that I think are really core from economic reasoning,

00:55:44.200 --> 00:55:48.960
[Guest]: and we should learn making better policies and even making sense of the news.

00:55:48.960 --> 00:55:51.520
[Guest]: Forget about whether you want to be in the government or not.

00:55:51.520 --> 00:55:56.200
[Guest]: But just if you want to parse the news, these ideas can help.

00:55:56.200 --> 00:55:57.200
[Amit Varma]: Fascinating.

00:55:57.200 --> 00:56:01.280
[Amit Varma]: And I'll kind of add to that by talking a little bit more about economic reasoning in

00:56:01.280 --> 00:56:04.960
[Amit Varma]: the sense that even though it's called economic reasoning, it's really reasoning.

00:56:04.960 --> 00:56:07.520
[Amit Varma]: You know, economics is after all, the study of human behavior.

00:56:07.520 --> 00:56:12.320
[Amit Varma]: So when I teach my writing course, for example, and over 1200 students have suffered through

00:56:12.320 --> 00:56:14.080
[Amit Varma]: it over the last 15 months.

00:56:14.080 --> 00:56:18.120
[Amit Varma]: When I teach my writing course, I often talk about, you know, I bring up economic reasoning

00:56:18.120 --> 00:56:21.040
[Amit Varma]: without calling it that, so it doesn't seem so intimidating.

00:56:21.040 --> 00:56:25.000
[Amit Varma]: For example, one of the points I want to I make right at the start of the course is that

00:56:25.000 --> 00:56:28.960
[Amit Varma]: we have to keep the reader at the forefront of our consideration, you know, too often,

00:56:28.960 --> 00:56:32.800
[Amit Varma]: when people sit down to write, they imagine that the act of writing is something that

00:56:32.800 --> 00:56:36.240
[Amit Varma]: is happening between them and their laptop, like I have thoughts in my head, I put it

00:56:36.240 --> 00:56:39.680
[Amit Varma]: out on the laptop or write it on a piece of paper and the writing is done.

00:56:39.680 --> 00:56:44.120
[Amit Varma]: But the writing only becomes meaningful when it has an intended effect on the intended

00:56:44.120 --> 00:56:45.120
[Amit Varma]: reader.

00:56:45.120 --> 00:56:46.700
[Amit Varma]: So you have to keep the reader at the heart of it.

00:56:46.700 --> 00:56:50.640
[Amit Varma]: And the way I kind of try to get this through is talking about opportunity cost is that

00:56:50.640 --> 00:56:54.760
[Amit Varma]: what could you be doing instead of attending this webinar, as it were, you know, you could

00:56:54.760 --> 00:56:57.760
[Amit Varma]: be reading a book, you could be watching Netflix, you could be watching YouTube, you could be

00:56:57.760 --> 00:57:00.220
[Amit Varma]: sleeping, all those opportunity cost.

00:57:00.220 --> 00:57:05.120
[Amit Varma]: So whenever someone reads anything by you, they are paying a huge price in terms of time

00:57:05.120 --> 00:57:09.320
[Amit Varma]: and time is money, so they are paying time and money, and also attention and energy,

00:57:09.320 --> 00:57:11.960
[Amit Varma]: which are separate points, reading something you have written.

00:57:11.960 --> 00:57:16.980
[Amit Varma]: So it is such an enormous privilege, and you should feel so grateful that someone is reading

00:57:16.980 --> 00:57:18.280
[Amit Varma]: anything by you.

00:57:18.280 --> 00:57:23.140
[Amit Varma]: And instead, so many writers seem to feel entitled to readers, they take it for granted,

00:57:23.140 --> 00:57:24.640
[Amit Varma]: and we actually need to work hard.

00:57:24.640 --> 00:57:28.480
[Amit Varma]: And which is why I say that, you know, bad writing is equal to bad behavior.

00:57:28.480 --> 00:57:33.560
[Amit Varma]: Because bad writing, I define as writing that wastes a reader's time, and it's absolutely

00:57:33.560 --> 00:57:34.560
[Amit Varma]: bad behavior.

00:57:34.560 --> 00:57:38.240
[Amit Varma]: And you can use the economic lens to look at other aspects of writing.

00:57:38.240 --> 00:57:42.720
[Amit Varma]: For example, you know, there are situations in which you don't want to write long sentences.

00:57:42.720 --> 00:57:46.860
[Amit Varma]: And there are situations in which you do because you're building that kind of longer rhythm.

00:57:46.860 --> 00:57:51.960
[Amit Varma]: So you'll often face what an economist would call a trade off that, you know, longer sentences

00:57:51.960 --> 00:57:55.280
[Amit Varma]: are harder to process, which is a negative side of the trade off.

00:57:55.280 --> 00:57:58.620
[Amit Varma]: But the positive side of the trade off is that maybe they are creating an immersive

00:57:58.620 --> 00:58:03.860
[Amit Varma]: effect and a slow rhythm that you want to for that particular essay or story you might

00:58:03.860 --> 00:58:04.880
[Amit Varma]: be writing.

00:58:04.880 --> 00:58:10.160
[Amit Varma]: So writers face choices at every moment, when they are writing, kahan pe full stop dalna

00:58:10.160 --> 00:58:11.920
[Amit Varma]: hai, kahan pe para break karna hai.

00:58:11.920 --> 00:58:15.960
[Amit Varma]: Every choice involves trade offs, because there are no definitive answers of this is

00:58:15.960 --> 00:58:17.280
[Amit Varma]: good and this is bad.

00:58:17.280 --> 00:58:19.120
[Guest]: So economic reasoning can help.

00:58:19.120 --> 00:58:22.080
[Guest]: Maybe you can add even transaction costs to this, right?

00:58:22.080 --> 00:58:27.800
[Guest]: Just the fact that you if you use complicated words, if you're trying to show off your literary

00:58:27.800 --> 00:58:33.400
[Guest]: flair, then you're actually increasing transaction costs of a person who's reading it, right?

00:58:33.400 --> 00:58:35.160
[Amit Varma]: So you would want to minimize that.

00:58:35.160 --> 00:58:36.160
[Amit Varma]: Harder for them to process.

00:58:36.160 --> 00:58:39.940
[Amit Varma]: This is what I keep saying that, you know, don't say when you can say stop, why would

00:58:39.940 --> 00:58:43.600
[Amit Varma]: you use a phrase like put an end to all those words where one is enough, you're just being

00:58:43.600 --> 00:58:47.440
[Amit Varma]: rude to the reader, which is not to say you dumb it down, you what you want to say is

00:58:47.440 --> 00:58:50.860
[Amit Varma]: what you want to say, you never compromise, you never dumb it down, but find the most

00:58:50.860 --> 00:58:56.320
[Amit Varma]: efficient way of saying it that is courteous to the reader and respects the time.

00:58:56.320 --> 00:58:59.920
[Amit Varma]: And you sort of mentioned stance and you know, when that decision happened, and basically

00:58:59.920 --> 00:59:03.920
[Amit Varma]: for listeners who may not be aware, I think three or four years ago, this government put

00:59:03.920 --> 00:59:07.400
[Amit Varma]: a price cap on stance and they said, Oh, people can't afford stance, so we'll put a price

00:59:07.400 --> 00:59:08.560
[Amit Varma]: cap and all that.

00:59:08.560 --> 00:59:12.280
[Amit Varma]: And I remember tweeting at that time, or maybe I wrote in an article, I don't remember, but

00:59:12.280 --> 00:59:16.760
[Amit Varma]: I remember putting it out there in the public, that this will lead to shortages, price gaps

00:59:16.760 --> 00:59:19.140
[Amit Varma]: always lead to shortages, period.

00:59:19.140 --> 00:59:22.440
[Amit Varma]: This is economics 101 economic reasoning.

00:59:22.440 --> 00:59:24.400
[Amit Varma]: And and that's exactly what happened.

00:59:24.400 --> 00:59:27.400
[Amit Varma]: And I don't even remember you and I might even have discussed it on one of my Bangalore

00:59:27.400 --> 00:59:30.480
[Amit Varma]: trips, but it was just so obvious that this is going to happen.

00:59:30.480 --> 00:59:36.220
[Amit Varma]: And that's also a profound point you made about how something that is unintended can

00:59:36.220 --> 00:59:38.240
[Amit Varma]: nevertheless be anticipated.

00:59:38.240 --> 00:59:43.880
[Amit Varma]: And an example of that, if I might do a humble brag is both Demon and GST, like Demon from

00:59:43.880 --> 00:59:48.600
[Amit Varma]: day one, I started writing columns and did episodes and why it would be a disaster and

00:59:48.600 --> 00:59:54.540
[Amit Varma]: it was and before GST was announced, I did an episode with Devanshu Dutta, breaking down

00:59:54.540 --> 00:59:59.080
[Amit Varma]: why even though it was well intentioned, all the different things that would go wrong,

00:59:59.080 --> 01:00:03.080
[Amit Varma]: and they all did, right, we were kind of completely spot on there.

01:00:03.080 --> 01:00:06.960
[Amit Varma]: And the interesting thing is, one core fallacy is in fact, the first one you talk about when

01:00:06.960 --> 01:00:12.240
[Amit Varma]: you want people to unlearn certain things, you know, before you think about public policy,

01:00:12.240 --> 01:00:16.920
[Amit Varma]: the first of those was that good intentions matter, that if something is well intentioned,

01:00:16.920 --> 01:00:18.060
[Amit Varma]: it's a good policy.

01:00:18.060 --> 01:00:22.560
[Amit Varma]: And the example of the price cap on stents shows that no, the intentions were the best,

01:00:22.560 --> 01:00:27.760
[Amit Varma]: the outcome was the worst. And similarly, we see a lot of our discourse is so shallow

01:00:27.760 --> 01:00:34.160
[Amit Varma]: in terms of interpreting policy in terms of intentions, like for example, last year, when

01:00:34.160 --> 01:00:40.520
[Amit Varma]: the labor laws were sort of, you know, there were changes in the labor laws, and people

01:00:40.520 --> 01:00:43.120
[Amit Varma]: kept defending these labor laws as if they were a good thing.

01:00:43.120 --> 01:00:46.880
[Amit Varma]: Now, these labor laws say good things, and they were made with good intentions, but they

01:00:46.880 --> 01:00:51.760
[Amit Varma]: had disastrous outcomes, which pretty much all economists have been in agreement about

01:00:51.760 --> 01:00:52.760
[Amit Varma]: for 25 years.

01:00:52.760 --> 01:00:56.960
[Amit Varma]: But just because an absolutely wild government, in this case, a UP government said that we'll

01:00:56.960 --> 01:01:00.560
[Amit Varma]: abolish the labor laws, everybody was up in arms and said, Oh, look, the labor laws are

01:01:00.560 --> 01:01:04.200
[Amit Varma]: protecting workers and all, whereas actually, no, they were harming workers.

01:01:04.200 --> 01:01:06.960
[Amit Varma]: You know, you can't go by intention, you have to go by outcome.

01:01:06.960 --> 01:01:09.840
[Amit Varma]: And the outcome is completely foreseeable.

01:01:09.840 --> 01:01:13.000
[Amit Varma]: This was the first of your points that don't go by good intentions.

01:01:13.000 --> 01:01:15.080
[Amit Varma]: Is this something that you'd like to elaborate upon?

01:01:15.080 --> 01:01:19.160
[Amit Varma]: Is it something that is a slightly difficult point to get across to your students?

01:01:19.160 --> 01:01:21.840
[Amit Varma]: Because it is a little counterintuitive?

01:01:21.840 --> 01:01:23.320
[Guest]: Yeah, absolutely.

01:01:23.320 --> 01:01:27.160
[Guest]: This is, I think, the toughest point to get across, right?

01:01:27.160 --> 01:01:30.440
[Guest]: And I mean, we all fall to this, right?

01:01:30.440 --> 01:01:37.280
[Guest]: Because we all think of intentions, when we think of governments, yeah, you know, he had

01:01:37.280 --> 01:01:41.680
[Guest]: good intentions, or she had good intentions at heart.

01:01:41.680 --> 01:01:47.320
[Guest]: So that that once you start from that mindset, it's difficult to process that or how can

01:01:47.320 --> 01:01:50.560
[Guest]: something which was started so well go wrong.

01:01:50.560 --> 01:01:53.440
[Guest]: And even if it goes wrong, then you will say, Oh, it was unintended.

01:01:53.440 --> 01:01:56.040
[Guest]: So it may be some effects will be there, right?

01:01:56.040 --> 01:02:00.080
[Guest]: So but that's where the idea is, right?

01:02:00.080 --> 01:02:07.120
[Guest]: Because you are managing such a complex system, just good intentions are no guarantee of getting

01:02:07.120 --> 01:02:08.120
[Guest]: good outcomes.

01:02:08.120 --> 01:02:14.480
[Guest]: And in fact, it is very important for us to understand how human motivations work, what

01:02:14.480 --> 01:02:19.840
[Guest]: are the kinds of things that might go wrong, and then you make your policy based on that.

01:02:19.840 --> 01:02:23.080
[Guest]: So the example that I give is of prohibition, right?

01:02:23.080 --> 01:02:26.720
[Guest]: So when prohibition started, yeah, good intentions, right?

01:02:26.720 --> 01:02:30.360
[Guest]: Stop alcoholism, at least that is the stated intent.

01:02:30.360 --> 01:02:34.880
[Guest]: So you say, okay, what's the best way to do this, you stop people from having alcohol

01:02:34.880 --> 01:02:35.880
[Guest]: itself.

01:02:35.880 --> 01:02:42.440
[Guest]: And once you had that prohibition in 50s and 60s, in Bombay, etc, also, it was there, and

01:02:42.440 --> 01:02:49.000
[Guest]: you had those really long run consequences, you know, so you because of prohibition, you

01:02:49.000 --> 01:02:55.000
[Guest]: had an underworld, which started doing, of course, you know, suddenly people will not

01:02:55.000 --> 01:02:59.760
[Guest]: stop drinking alcohol, because one good intention, CM has said, right?

01:02:59.760 --> 01:03:02.400
[Guest]: It is in an inelastic demand, right?

01:03:02.400 --> 01:03:07.400
[Guest]: So people would still want it just means that your demand will suddenly not drop because

01:03:07.400 --> 01:03:08.920
[Guest]: someone has said so.

01:03:08.920 --> 01:03:14.360
[Guest]: So you people want that demand to be served, it got served through other means.

01:03:14.360 --> 01:03:19.600
[Guest]: And the people who are supplying these are the people who are obviously outside the law,

01:03:19.600 --> 01:03:20.600
[Guest]: right?

01:03:20.600 --> 01:03:25.840
[Guest]: So they basically gained material wealth, they gained social wealth, they basically

01:03:25.840 --> 01:03:31.800
[Guest]: became richer, and they gained a lot of standing higher standing in the society as well, right?

01:03:31.800 --> 01:03:37.240
[Guest]: So those were also the people who eventually became use that money for smuggling and whole

01:03:37.240 --> 01:03:38.600
[Guest]: lot of other things, you know.

01:03:38.600 --> 01:03:45.880
[Guest]: So such a small action that you will just think are born out of such noble intentions,

01:03:45.880 --> 01:03:48.400
[Guest]: actually had such disastrous consequences, right?

01:03:48.400 --> 01:03:53.360
[Guest]: You add a whole lot of underworld, mafia, and so many things which are related.

01:03:53.360 --> 01:03:57.640
[Guest]: Now, we can't say what percentage of it was due to this, that would be difficult.

01:03:57.640 --> 01:04:03.800
[Guest]: But there is a causal chain, which maps to it, you know, so it's really important.

01:04:03.800 --> 01:04:10.720
[Guest]: Another example that I give for this is just this idea of MSP and connection with the daily

01:04:10.720 --> 01:04:12.200
[Guest]: smog, right?

01:04:12.200 --> 01:04:14.680
[Guest]: It's such a profound connection, right?

01:04:14.680 --> 01:04:19.560
[Guest]: So then, I think we'll just trace it just for the fun of it.

01:04:19.560 --> 01:04:25.200
[Guest]: So daily smog happens, what is the biggest reason people say it's the crop residue, right?

01:04:25.200 --> 01:04:31.680
[Guest]: So first question we ask is, okay, if it is crop residue, then why can't we stop it?

01:04:31.680 --> 01:04:35.040
[Guest]: So one thing would be, okay, why don't you stagger it, right?

01:04:35.040 --> 01:04:40.960
[Guest]: The whole reason it's happening is because most people are burning that crop at the same

01:04:40.960 --> 01:04:43.880
[Guest]: particular point of time, it's really short window.

01:04:43.880 --> 01:04:45.760
[Guest]: So the idea is, why can't you stagger it?

01:04:45.760 --> 01:04:48.440
[Guest]: So staggering should resolve that problem.

01:04:48.440 --> 01:04:55.440
[Guest]: But that staggering is not possible, because I think before July 15, you can't grow a Kharif

01:04:55.440 --> 01:05:01.440
[Guest]: crop, because the government has put a restriction, the some Punjab Subsoil Act 2009.

01:05:01.440 --> 01:05:05.120
[Guest]: That you can't grow a paddy before that.

01:05:05.120 --> 01:05:09.600
[Guest]: So what happens is most people end up delaying their crop, and hence they have very little

01:05:09.600 --> 01:05:12.320
[Guest]: time before the next Rabi season starts.

01:05:12.320 --> 01:05:16.200
[Guest]: So what they do is in that short period, the only way to get rid is all of them burning

01:05:16.200 --> 01:05:18.080
[Guest]: their crop residues together, right?

01:05:18.080 --> 01:05:19.240
[Guest]: So that's a problem.

01:05:19.240 --> 01:05:22.920
[Guest]: So now the question you ask is, why did the government put this law in place?

01:05:22.920 --> 01:05:28.840
[Guest]: The reason is that during that time, Punjab and those regions have severe water shortage

01:05:28.840 --> 01:05:34.060
[Guest]: summer, peak summer, so they don't want water to be used for growing paddy.

01:05:34.060 --> 01:05:36.200
[Guest]: So the government has put this restriction.

01:05:36.200 --> 01:05:38.120
[Guest]: Now you go again one step back, right?

01:05:38.120 --> 01:05:41.720
[Guest]: Why are people growing paddy in the first place when there is no water?

01:05:41.720 --> 01:05:46.000
[Guest]: And then you realize that it is because you have distorted the incentives by saying that

01:05:46.000 --> 01:05:49.600
[Guest]: we will give you money for growing this particular crop, right?

01:05:49.600 --> 01:05:52.840
[Guest]: And that's what is the MSP, which government gives.

01:05:52.840 --> 01:06:00.280
[Guest]: So you see the entire chain of MSP actually leading to the disastrous consequences.

01:06:00.280 --> 01:06:04.920
[Guest]: No person could have imagined it back then, right, that, you know, suddenly, this might

01:06:04.920 --> 01:06:09.000
[Guest]: happen, Delhi smog might happen, probably they wouldn't have imagined way back in the

01:06:09.000 --> 01:06:10.000
[Amit Varma]: 60s.

01:06:10.000 --> 01:06:13.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, I want to add to this because there's a lot else and all of them have good intentions.

01:06:13.920 --> 01:06:17.640
[Amit Varma]: Like you said, this MSP is a good intention that hey, we'll support the farmers and we'll

01:06:17.640 --> 01:06:19.740
[Amit Varma]: give this price and they'll grow paddy.

01:06:19.740 --> 01:06:24.280
[Amit Varma]: But the other thing is that despite this, because this rice is a water intensive crop,

01:06:24.280 --> 01:06:28.960
[Amit Varma]: they would not have grown rice, had it not been for free electricity, again, free electricity

01:06:28.960 --> 01:06:31.600
[Amit Varma]: to farmers is given with the best intentions.

01:06:31.600 --> 01:06:35.080
[Amit Varma]: But what they did with it is they built a lot of dew bells or whatever it is with which

01:06:35.080 --> 01:06:41.420
[Amit Varma]: you get water out of the surface, which allowed them to actually grow rice, which they otherwise

01:06:41.420 --> 01:06:42.420
[Amit Varma]: would not have.

01:06:42.420 --> 01:06:46.920
[Amit Varma]: So you have a combination of the MSP, the free electricity to the farmers, the absolutely

01:06:46.920 --> 01:06:51.040
[Amit Varma]: the best intentions, and you have this perverse situation where people in Delhi can't breathe

01:06:51.040 --> 01:06:55.120
[Amit Varma]: and every day is like smoking 30-40 cigarettes or something of the sort.

01:06:55.120 --> 01:06:57.200
[Amit Varma]: And these are unintended consequences.

01:06:57.200 --> 01:06:58.520
[Amit Varma]: And the point is, are they unforeseeable?

01:06:58.520 --> 01:07:03.160
[Amit Varma]: Well, to the specific degree that back when MSP was set, you could not have said that

01:07:03.160 --> 01:07:05.360
[Amit Varma]: this will cause Delhi smog.

01:07:05.360 --> 01:07:06.760
[Amit Varma]: You could not have said that.

01:07:06.760 --> 01:07:11.840
[Amit Varma]: But you could have very easily said that markets are going to be distorted, that never ends

01:07:11.840 --> 01:07:12.840
[Amit Varma]: well.

01:07:12.840 --> 01:07:16.100
[Amit Varma]: And you know, down the road, this will hurt the people that you're trying to help.

01:07:16.100 --> 01:07:20.480
[Amit Varma]: And throughout India, we've kind of seen those sort of distortions happening.

01:07:20.480 --> 01:07:21.640
[Amit Varma]: And you mentioned prohibition.

01:07:21.640 --> 01:07:26.360
[Amit Varma]: So I also want to sort of give another beautiful phrase, one of my favorite phrases, which

01:07:26.360 --> 01:07:30.480
[Amit Varma]: when I was learning about economics, which I learned, and it's a phrase coined by the

01:07:30.480 --> 01:07:32.680
[Amit Varma]: regulatory economist Bruce Yandel.

01:07:32.680 --> 01:07:34.860
[Amit Varma]: And it's called Baptists and bootleggers.

01:07:34.860 --> 01:07:39.640
[Amit Varma]: So the funda here is that when prohibition happens first, why does prohibition happens?

01:07:39.640 --> 01:07:44.720
[Amit Varma]: Because people he describes as Baptists will come up and say it is evil to have alcohol

01:07:44.720 --> 01:07:48.600
[Amit Varma]: and husbands are beating wives and all of this and they'll make a moral issue out of

01:07:48.600 --> 01:07:50.320
[Amit Varma]: it that alcohol should be banned.

01:07:50.320 --> 01:07:55.360
[Amit Varma]: So Baptists get alcohol banned, Baptists I'm using in a loose sense, not in a literal sense

01:07:55.360 --> 01:07:56.360
[Amit Varma]: here.

01:07:56.360 --> 01:08:00.520
[Amit Varma]: But basically, people preaching in a virtuous way about the evils of alcohol will get it

01:08:00.520 --> 01:08:01.520
[Amit Varma]: banned.

01:08:01.520 --> 01:08:03.720
[Amit Varma]: Who is it good for is good for bootleggers.

01:08:03.720 --> 01:08:09.040
[Amit Varma]: Because the moment you ban something like that, the underground market will spring up.

01:08:09.040 --> 01:08:13.540
[Amit Varma]: And you know, bootleggers then come into the picture and you know, make a huge profit.

01:08:13.540 --> 01:08:18.780
[Amit Varma]: And what this illustrates, this phrase illustrates is that Baptists and bootleggers are actually

01:08:18.780 --> 01:08:22.080
[Amit Varma]: perfect allies, which people don't understand.

01:08:22.080 --> 01:08:26.280
[Amit Varma]: And the amusing subtext to that is that for a very brief while, I think three or four

01:08:26.280 --> 01:08:32.400
[Amit Varma]: years ago, the editor of Huffington Post at the time Huffington Post India, he was a friend

01:08:32.400 --> 01:08:35.400
[Amit Varma]: of mine, he saw something I wrote about a film on Facebook, and he said, Why don't you

01:08:35.400 --> 01:08:37.060
[Amit Varma]: write film reviews for me.

01:08:37.060 --> 01:08:40.920
[Amit Varma]: So I reviewed one film, which I think was Aamir Khan's Dangal where I had a throwaway

01:08:40.920 --> 01:08:46.560
[Amit Varma]: line about how of the superstars, he's the only one who can act a little bit something

01:08:46.560 --> 01:08:47.920
[Amit Varma]: to that effect.

01:08:47.920 --> 01:08:51.800
[Amit Varma]: And Shah Rukh Khan read that and got offended and called up HuffPo and said, Who is this

01:08:51.800 --> 01:08:52.800
[Amit Varma]: Amit Verma?

01:08:52.800 --> 01:08:53.800
[Amit Varma]: And why is he sniping at me?

01:08:53.800 --> 01:08:54.800
[Amit Varma]: Right?

01:08:54.800 --> 01:08:57.400
[Amit Varma]: So anyway, so that moment passed, I wrote another review.

01:08:57.400 --> 01:09:03.680
[Amit Varma]: And then two weeks after that, Raees and some terrible Hrithik Roshan film, I don't remember,

01:09:03.680 --> 01:09:05.400
[Amit Varma]: they released simultaneously.

01:09:05.400 --> 01:09:09.480
[Amit Varma]: And I reviewed Raees, which I completely slammed because it's a terrible film.

01:09:09.480 --> 01:09:12.920
[Amit Varma]: Actually, actually, everybody acts very well in that except for one person.

01:09:12.920 --> 01:09:13.920
[Amit Varma]: And I slammed the film.

01:09:13.920 --> 01:09:17.960
[Amit Varma]: But one of the reasons I slammed the film was this Baptist and bootlegger thing that

01:09:17.960 --> 01:09:20.500
[Amit Varma]: his character plays a bootlegger in that.

01:09:20.500 --> 01:09:25.520
[Amit Varma]: And when a politician demanding prohibition is passing through the city, they build it

01:09:25.520 --> 01:09:26.920
[Amit Varma]: up as an enmity.

01:09:26.920 --> 01:09:28.980
[Amit Varma]: And I'm like, this doesn't make sense.

01:09:28.980 --> 01:09:33.240
[Amit Varma]: These are allies that they are working together, he should be delighted that a politician wants

01:09:33.240 --> 01:09:36.380
[Amit Varma]: to make alcohol illegal because that is his whole danda.

01:09:36.380 --> 01:09:39.880
[Amit Varma]: And by the way, after this fourth review, the editor sheepishly called me up and he

01:09:39.880 --> 01:09:44.920
[Amit Varma]: said that, you know, we've decided no more reviews from you, we'll just handle it internally.

01:09:44.920 --> 01:09:47.440
[Amit Varma]: So I didn't delve further into what happened.

01:09:47.440 --> 01:09:51.920
[Amit Varma]: But I remembered this in in the context of, you know, the recent scandal earlier this

01:09:51.920 --> 01:09:56.520
[Amit Varma]: week, a useless controversy about Tapsee Pannu getting pissed off at Shubhra Gupta's review

01:09:56.520 --> 01:09:58.200
[Amit Varma]: in Indian Express.

01:09:58.200 --> 01:10:01.360
[Amit Varma]: And Shubhra hadn't even said anything personal.

01:10:01.360 --> 01:10:02.880
[Amit Varma]: It was one throwaway line.

01:10:02.880 --> 01:10:08.000
[Amit Varma]: And the full Streisand effect came into being because Tapsee Pannu threw a hissy fit about

01:10:08.000 --> 01:10:09.280
[Amit Varma]: the review and all of that.

01:10:09.280 --> 01:10:12.800
[Amit Varma]: And it was a fairly good review and, and I actually liked Tapsee Pannu.

01:10:12.800 --> 01:10:15.720
[Amit Varma]: So I'm not taking sides, but no reason to throw a hissy fit.

01:10:15.720 --> 01:10:20.640
[Amit Varma]: Massive aside, but who would have thunk, by the way, the HuffPost archives got taken off

01:10:20.640 --> 01:10:24.280
[Amit Varma]: after that, like I would have linked it from the show notes, but I don't think that review

01:10:24.280 --> 01:10:25.280
[Amit Varma]: is on my site.

01:10:25.280 --> 01:10:29.440
[Amit Varma]: But what I'll do is I'll look in my email and from the archives, just I'll probably

01:10:29.440 --> 01:10:33.560
[Amit Varma]: put it on India Uncut, backdate it to whatever the date was and put it up so people can read

01:10:33.560 --> 01:10:36.060
[Guest]: it and see if there was anything to get offended by.

01:10:36.060 --> 01:10:40.560
[Guest]: So the opportunity cost of having Amit Verma was to lose Shah Rukh Khan.

01:10:40.560 --> 01:10:42.920
[Guest]: Well, to lose Shah Rukh Khan or to lose me.

01:10:42.920 --> 01:10:45.480
[Guest]: I mean, for them, that was the trade off.

01:10:45.480 --> 01:10:48.680
[Guest]: So they chose what they had to.

01:10:48.680 --> 01:10:49.680
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, yeah.

01:10:49.680 --> 01:10:51.720
[Amit Varma]: They made a rational choice, by the way.

01:10:51.720 --> 01:10:55.860
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I would not make that choice as an editor, but I can imagine why they did losing

01:10:55.860 --> 01:11:01.440
[Amit Varma]: access and all of that, and why do you want to piss off a superstar of that kind?

01:11:01.440 --> 01:11:03.240
[Amit Varma]: So I kind of found it funny.

01:11:03.240 --> 01:11:07.020
[Amit Varma]: So yeah, so that is the first of the things we have to unlearn.

01:11:07.020 --> 01:11:09.120
[Amit Varma]: Good intentions is equal to good policy.

01:11:09.120 --> 01:11:10.440
[Amit Varma]: And that's a fallacy.

01:11:10.440 --> 01:11:13.240
[Amit Varma]: Good intentions is, you know, you can begin with it.

01:11:13.240 --> 01:11:19.560
[Amit Varma]: But very often a policy based on good intentions alone will backfire massively.

01:11:19.560 --> 01:11:22.120
[Amit Varma]: And we have seven more to go through and then lots more to go through.

01:11:22.120 --> 01:11:27.120
[Amit Varma]: I also want to talk about your path breaking concept of societism, which was first expressed

01:11:27.120 --> 01:11:30.200
[Amit Varma]: in an essay that you wrote for Pragati when I was editor of Pragati.

01:11:30.200 --> 01:11:35.480
[Amit Varma]: So I almost feel this sort of paternal sense towards that essay of yours.

01:11:35.480 --> 01:11:37.080
[Amit Varma]: But we'll take a quick commercial break.

01:11:37.080 --> 01:11:42.400
[Amit Varma]: And then on the other side, we shall resume this conversation.

01:11:42.400 --> 01:11:45.040
[Amit Varma]: Long before I was a podcaster, I was a writer.

01:11:45.040 --> 01:11:50.160
[Amit Varma]: In fact, chances are that many of you first heard of me because of my blog, India Uncut,

01:11:50.160 --> 01:11:55.000
[Amit Varma]: which was active between 2003 and 2009 and became somewhat popular at the time.

01:11:55.000 --> 01:11:57.280
[Amit Varma]: I love the freedom the form gave me.

01:11:57.280 --> 01:12:00.040
[Amit Varma]: And I feel I was shaped by it in many ways.

01:12:00.040 --> 01:12:04.960
[Amit Varma]: I exercise my writing muscle every day and was forced to think about many different things

01:12:04.960 --> 01:12:07.200
[Amit Varma]: because I wrote about many different things.

01:12:07.200 --> 01:12:10.500
[Amit Varma]: Well, that phase in my life ended for various reasons.

01:12:10.500 --> 01:12:12.400
[Amit Varma]: And now it is time to revive it.

01:12:12.400 --> 01:12:15.000
[Amit Varma]: Only now I'm doing it through a newsletter.

01:12:15.000 --> 01:12:21.120
[Amit Varma]: I have started the India Uncut newsletter at indiancut.substack.com, where I will write

01:12:21.120 --> 01:12:23.640
[Amit Varma]: regularly about whatever catches my fancy.

