[Amit Varma]: Once you sign up, each new installment that I write will land up in your email inbox.

01:12:38.360 --> 01:12:40.140
[Amit Varma]: You don't need to go anywhere.

01:12:40.140 --> 01:12:42.180
[Amit Varma]: So subscribe now for free.

01:12:42.180 --> 01:12:46.500
[Amit Varma]: The India Uncut newsletter at indiancut.substack.com.

01:12:46.500 --> 01:12:48.480
[Amit Varma]: Thank you.

01:12:48.480 --> 01:12:49.840
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen.

01:12:49.840 --> 01:12:54.680
[Amit Varma]: I'm chatting with Pranay Kotesane, public policy scholar, extraordinary about public

01:12:54.680 --> 01:12:58.020
[Amit Varma]: policy, about his own life, about kind of the world around us.

01:12:58.020 --> 01:13:02.480
[Amit Varma]: Because what we build in our time learning economics and economic reasoning is a prism

01:13:02.480 --> 01:13:06.080
[Amit Varma]: through which we can see the world and understand it better as it were.

01:13:06.080 --> 01:13:10.480
[Amit Varma]: Now, we were going through the eight misconceptions about public policy per se.

01:13:10.480 --> 01:13:14.300
[Amit Varma]: And the first of them, which he elaborated upon before the break is that good intentions

01:13:14.300 --> 01:13:17.200
[Amit Varma]: don't necessarily make for good policy.

01:13:17.200 --> 01:13:18.200
[Amit Varma]: What's number two?

01:13:18.200 --> 01:13:19.200
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:13:19.200 --> 01:13:22.800
[Guest]: So the second one is sort of an extension of the first one.

01:13:22.800 --> 01:13:27.960
[Guest]: And I'm sure you would have heard this a lot about how we often say that our problem is

01:13:27.960 --> 01:13:33.560
[Guest]: that our policies are great on paper, just that implementation me gadbad ho gayi.

01:13:33.560 --> 01:13:36.040
[Guest]: Otherwise, policy was everything was good in it.

01:13:36.040 --> 01:13:42.480
[Guest]: So that is, again, a fallacy, because a policy is explicitly meant to take implementation

01:13:42.480 --> 01:13:43.480
[Guest]: into account.

01:13:43.480 --> 01:13:44.480
[Guest]: What else is a policy?

01:13:44.480 --> 01:13:46.960
[Guest]: Otherwise, you can at best say it was a good idea, right?

01:13:46.960 --> 01:13:52.560
[Guest]: I mean, all of us have great ideas about getting the world, making a world a better place.

01:13:52.560 --> 01:13:54.520
[Guest]: But those are just ideas, right?

01:13:54.520 --> 01:14:00.000
[Guest]: When you go into the nitty gritties, when you try to see how people will actually interpret

01:14:00.000 --> 01:14:06.160
[Guest]: this, how human motivations will play out, those are the things that a policy is precisely

01:14:06.160 --> 01:14:07.160
[Guest]: meant to address.

01:14:07.160 --> 01:14:08.160
[Guest]: Right.

01:14:08.160 --> 01:14:13.960
[Guest]: So when we, for example, teach a systematic way of making public policies on a problem,

01:14:13.960 --> 01:14:19.400
[Guest]: we expect people to have gone through a step of anticipating the unintended, projecting

01:14:19.400 --> 01:14:23.820
[Guest]: the outcomes, looking at the stakeholders, how would they interpret it?

01:14:23.820 --> 01:14:27.120
[Guest]: That is what implementation is essentially meant to capture.

01:14:27.120 --> 01:14:31.440
[Guest]: So if your policy is not doing that, it can't be a good policy.

01:14:31.440 --> 01:14:36.360
[Guest]: Basically, we've not thought through enough, you've just put a diktat on something which

01:14:36.360 --> 01:14:41.240
[Guest]: you thought will work great, because it sounds like a great idea in my mind, right?

01:14:41.240 --> 01:14:43.760
[Guest]: So that is a big fallacy.

01:14:43.760 --> 01:14:47.200
[Guest]: So there's nothing like a bad implementation, good policy.

01:14:47.200 --> 01:14:50.200
[Guest]: If your implementation is failing, your policy is also bad.

01:14:50.200 --> 01:14:53.000
[Guest]: So that is something we should keep in mind.

01:14:53.000 --> 01:14:57.400
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, you know, this is something I agree with so much, because for example, when it

01:14:57.400 --> 01:15:02.800
[Amit Varma]: came to GST, you know, there were again, people who said that GST was good, the previous government

01:15:02.800 --> 01:15:05.720
[Amit Varma]: also wanted it, but implementation was bad.

01:15:05.720 --> 01:15:11.960
[Amit Varma]: But no, the point is, the design of the policy was bad, which made it inevitable that everything

01:15:11.960 --> 01:15:13.920
[Amit Varma]: would go wrong when the policy came into play.

01:15:13.920 --> 01:15:18.440
[Amit Varma]: For example, the way the GST was originally conceived was that you have one rate or at

01:15:18.440 --> 01:15:21.720
[Amit Varma]: the most a couple of rates, you simplify everything.

01:15:21.720 --> 01:15:25.860
[Amit Varma]: You know, they had actually, even though it's a goods and services tax, they had hyped it

01:15:25.860 --> 01:15:28.420
[Amit Varma]: up as a good and simple tax, which is what it should have been.

01:15:28.420 --> 01:15:32.640
[Amit Varma]: But instead, it was a bad and complex tax, which is even the title of one of my episodes

01:15:32.640 --> 01:15:33.640
[Amit Varma]: on it.

01:15:33.640 --> 01:15:35.120
[Amit Varma]: And it was completely foreseeable.

01:15:35.120 --> 01:15:40.080
[Amit Varma]: And I will say that before GST was actually passed on this show, The Seen and the Unseen,

01:15:40.080 --> 01:15:43.680
[Amit Varma]: Devangshu Dutta and I actually spoke about all the things that would go wrong, because

01:15:43.680 --> 01:15:45.120
[Amit Varma]: of the design of the policy.

01:15:45.120 --> 01:15:46.720
[Amit Varma]: And all of them did eventually go wrong.

01:15:46.720 --> 01:15:51.680
[Amit Varma]: The problem with having multiple rates, the problem with making it so difficult for people

01:15:51.680 --> 01:15:56.040
[Amit Varma]: to have to file monthly returns and all the kind of nonsense like my life is like way,

01:15:56.040 --> 01:16:01.480
[Amit Varma]: way more complicated because of GST than it was before the impact that it had on small

01:16:01.480 --> 01:16:03.320
[Amit Varma]: and medium sized industries.

01:16:03.320 --> 01:16:04.880
[Amit Varma]: It was all foreseeable.

01:16:04.880 --> 01:16:10.400
[Amit Varma]: So that's a fantastic point that sometimes, you know, the implementation can also be foreseen

01:16:10.400 --> 01:16:14.200
[Amit Varma]: if you just look at the design of the policy.

01:16:14.200 --> 01:16:18.720
[Amit Varma]: And in a sense, this is a larger question that I have saved for later, which we'll talk

01:16:18.720 --> 01:16:23.360
[Amit Varma]: about when we talk about the Indian state, because in a sense, you can look at the constitution

01:16:23.360 --> 01:16:29.000
[Amit Varma]: as a policy document that was written badly, which has led to a state which is a predatory

01:16:29.000 --> 01:16:33.680
[Amit Varma]: parasitic state and people can say that the constitution is good but the implementation

01:16:33.680 --> 01:16:34.680
[Amit Varma]: is wrong.

01:16:34.680 --> 01:16:35.680
[Amit Varma]: No, it's not the case.

01:16:35.680 --> 01:16:39.040
[Amit Varma]: It was an example of bad design, but we'll come back to that.

01:16:39.040 --> 01:16:42.120
[Amit Varma]: What's the third thing that people should unlearn?

01:16:42.120 --> 01:16:47.400
[Guest]: The third point I would say is this notion that politics is disgusting, you know, and

01:16:47.400 --> 01:16:54.360
[Guest]: again, you know, a few years back, we had this sense that apathy was the dominant notion

01:16:54.360 --> 01:16:59.160
[Guest]: when we thought of government, right, like, why even bother ourselves with it, right?

01:16:59.160 --> 01:17:04.160
[Guest]: And because people think that politics is disgusting, only evil people do it and we

01:17:04.160 --> 01:17:05.160
[Guest]: are good people.

01:17:05.160 --> 01:17:06.480
[Guest]: So we'll not do politics, right?

01:17:06.480 --> 01:17:10.560
[Guest]: But we all know, you know, politics starts when three people are in a room, you know,

01:17:10.560 --> 01:17:14.080
[Guest]: so there is politics going on even now, right?

01:17:14.080 --> 01:17:19.720
[Guest]: Even you, I and listeners said that politics is so essential, not just to human beings,

01:17:19.720 --> 01:17:22.240
[Guest]: you know, even primates engage in politics.

01:17:22.240 --> 01:17:29.000
[Guest]: So to think of politics as disgusting is a very problematic because as Sir Humphrey Appleby

01:17:29.000 --> 01:17:34.080
[Guest]: says, do you know Bernard, what happens when good people don't get power, the bad people

01:17:34.080 --> 01:17:35.080
[Guest]: get it.

01:17:35.080 --> 01:17:39.240
[Guest]: So that's why politics is important and there's no way around it.

01:17:39.240 --> 01:17:45.160
[Guest]: We have to engage in it if we want to make our country a better place, right?

01:17:45.160 --> 01:17:50.080
[Guest]: So getting around this idea that politics is disgusting, and that's why I will keep

01:17:50.080 --> 01:17:56.200
[Guest]: away and somehow things will be great for me is sort of a fallacy.

01:17:56.200 --> 01:17:59.600
[Amit Varma]: And would it then follow from this and the reason why this is important in practical

01:17:59.600 --> 01:18:03.980
[Amit Varma]: terms is when people are working in public policy, like yourselves, where you are coming

01:18:03.980 --> 01:18:08.760
[Amit Varma]: out with suggestions to governments and interacting with government and trying to get things through.

01:18:08.760 --> 01:18:13.880
[Amit Varma]: The reason this is important is that if you just aim for a certain kind of purity, without

01:18:13.880 --> 01:18:18.600
[Amit Varma]: considering what are the incentives of politicians or bureaucrats, whatever, then no one will

01:18:18.600 --> 01:18:21.600
[Amit Varma]: take you seriously, you won't even be part of the conversation.

01:18:21.600 --> 01:18:26.500
[Amit Varma]: And what you instead have to do is you have to tailor your proposals and sell them, keeping

01:18:26.500 --> 01:18:33.040
[Amit Varma]: in mind key politician incentives, our constraints, and similar with bureaucrats and similar with

01:18:33.040 --> 01:18:35.100
[Amit Varma]: other stakeholders along the way.

01:18:35.100 --> 01:18:39.800
[Amit Varma]: So by that, you can kind of get something workable through, you know, and not let the

01:18:39.800 --> 01:18:42.600
[Amit Varma]: perfect be the enemy of the good as the cliche goes.

01:18:42.600 --> 01:18:47.400
[Amit Varma]: So is that why this is so important in real world terms for people who work within policy

01:18:47.400 --> 01:18:48.400
[Amit Varma]: like yourself?

01:18:48.400 --> 01:18:50.160
[Guest]: Yeah, yeah, absolutely.

01:18:50.160 --> 01:18:58.960
[Guest]: And a more fundamental reason is that when we think of people who are at the margin,

01:18:58.960 --> 01:19:00.840
[Guest]: think of politics as disgusting.

01:19:00.840 --> 01:19:03.980
[Guest]: The only people who will be in politics are the partisans, right?

01:19:03.980 --> 01:19:10.040
[Guest]: So then you are only in politics because you are playing the Congress versus BJP versus

01:19:10.040 --> 01:19:11.880
[Guest]: some other party game.

01:19:11.880 --> 01:19:16.640
[Guest]: And then if you are already in that mode, then policies don't matter, right?

01:19:16.640 --> 01:19:22.120
[Guest]: Then your party and what the party is doing, what the leader is doing, defines what will

01:19:22.120 --> 01:19:26.760
[Guest]: be the implications, how you will interpret policies, right?

01:19:26.760 --> 01:19:28.920
[Guest]: The consequences be damned, right?

01:19:28.920 --> 01:19:30.520
[Guest]: That will be how it is.

01:19:30.520 --> 01:19:38.000
[Guest]: So in order for us who are not on either side to just aim for making things better than

01:19:38.000 --> 01:19:41.080
[Guest]: the way they are, you need to keep this notion aside, right?

01:19:41.080 --> 01:19:45.720
[Guest]: And you will encounter it in any policy space that you go, right?

01:19:45.720 --> 01:19:50.840
[Guest]: There's no policy space where you will not have to look at the cognitive maps of all

01:19:50.840 --> 01:19:58.960
[Guest]: the people, you know, what their goals are, what they imagine causality is, how they think,

01:19:58.960 --> 01:20:00.880
[Guest]: and what they think the others think.

01:20:00.880 --> 01:20:07.120
[Guest]: All those things you need to map in order to do just good stakeholder management and

01:20:07.120 --> 01:20:09.920
[Guest]: get a policy change actually happen.

01:20:09.920 --> 01:20:12.880
[Guest]: I'll give you an example of this, Amit.

01:20:12.880 --> 01:20:19.360
[Guest]: This pension reform which happened in 2004, I think I would count it as an example of

01:20:19.360 --> 01:20:25.760
[Guest]: one policy which did manage to do this really well, you know.

01:20:25.760 --> 01:20:30.840
[Guest]: So the thing was, basically, until then, the civil service pension, the way it worked was,

01:20:30.840 --> 01:20:35.440
[Guest]: you got the pension, it was a defined benefit pension, right?

01:20:35.440 --> 01:20:40.320
[Guest]: You always got that pension, irrespective of government's finances, it's a promise

01:20:40.320 --> 01:20:42.280
[Guest]: that the government has made to you.

01:20:42.280 --> 01:20:45.680
[Guest]: And they wanted to transition it to a contribution scheme, right?

01:20:45.680 --> 01:20:50.720
[Guest]: So you contribute, the government also contribute, and from that corpus, you get that money later.

01:20:50.720 --> 01:20:55.800
[Guest]: Now, if you look at it, the first reaction you would think to this is, there will be

01:20:55.800 --> 01:20:57.080
[Guest]: massive protests, right?

01:20:57.080 --> 01:20:59.040
[Guest]: Like, why will anyone agree to it?

01:20:59.040 --> 01:21:02.120
[Guest]: That to someone in the government who's used to all this.

01:21:02.120 --> 01:21:05.920
[Guest]: But this policy change happened so smoothly that we haven't even heard of it.

01:21:05.920 --> 01:21:09.200
[Guest]: It's not in our public imagination at all, right?

01:21:09.200 --> 01:21:10.200
[Guest]: And why was that?

01:21:10.200 --> 01:21:12.920
[Guest]: Because there was a really neat solution to that.

01:21:12.920 --> 01:21:19.600
[Guest]: The way the people did this is, one, it didn't apply to people who were already in the government

01:21:19.600 --> 01:21:20.600
[Guest]: back then.

01:21:20.600 --> 01:21:21.640
[Guest]: It was not backdated.

01:21:21.640 --> 01:21:26.120
[Guest]: It started for people who were not in the government at that point of time.

01:21:26.120 --> 01:21:28.160
[Guest]: So it was a front-ended scheme, right?

01:21:28.160 --> 01:21:34.160
[Guest]: So you removed the opposition that might have come in an organized manner from say unions

01:21:34.160 --> 01:21:35.320
[Guest]: back then, right?

01:21:35.320 --> 01:21:40.400
[Guest]: The second thing that you did was you also promised a higher outgo to people who are

01:21:40.400 --> 01:21:45.600
[Guest]: coming in because government was contributing an additional, whatever, 10% from their kitty

01:21:45.600 --> 01:21:50.360
[Guest]: and the people who are going to join in, they are going to contribute 10%, right?

01:21:50.360 --> 01:21:55.080
[Guest]: So there is an added incentive for people who are joining in as well, right?

01:21:55.080 --> 01:21:57.440
[Guest]: A small one, but nevertheless an important one.

01:21:57.440 --> 01:22:04.020
[Guest]: So when this change happened, so basically you have managed even the concentrated loss

01:22:04.020 --> 01:22:07.560
[Guest]: that people would have imagined very nicely, right?

01:22:07.560 --> 01:22:09.320
[Guest]: You didn't have those protests.

01:22:09.320 --> 01:22:16.280
[Guest]: So once we think of what are the various interests, what are the way people might react and then

01:22:16.280 --> 01:22:20.280
[Guest]: try to get a policy around that, then it is possible.

01:22:20.280 --> 01:22:21.800
[Guest]: So we need to take that into account.

01:22:21.800 --> 01:22:25.800
[Guest]: I think something similar could also have been done with Air India long back, right?

01:22:25.800 --> 01:22:30.840
[Guest]: You could have just, you know that there will be people who will oppose it who are already

01:22:30.840 --> 01:22:31.840
[Guest]: there.

01:22:31.840 --> 01:22:37.000
[Guest]: So maybe you take care of them in some way or the other, but you don't need to run an

01:22:37.000 --> 01:22:40.200
[Guest]: airlines just to pay people their salaries.

01:22:40.200 --> 01:22:45.520
[Guest]: So that's why I think understanding politics, understanding interest groups is important.

01:22:45.520 --> 01:22:47.640
[Guest]: There's no way around it.

01:22:47.640 --> 01:22:51.400
[Guest]: Otherwise a great policy solution might not work.

01:22:51.400 --> 01:22:57.040
[Guest]: So that's why what we say is always think of whatever policy solution you have.

01:22:57.040 --> 01:23:04.440
[Guest]: Imagine the outcome that you want, the world as it would be if your policy were to be implemented.

01:23:04.440 --> 01:23:06.880
[Guest]: Imagine that world and imagine the world now.

01:23:06.880 --> 01:23:12.120
[Guest]: Then the gap which exists between them, how do you transition from this to that is an

01:23:12.120 --> 01:23:14.360
[Guest]: important learning to imagine.

01:23:14.360 --> 01:23:18.480
[Guest]: Then when you try to project these outcomes at that point of time, you will notice there

01:23:18.480 --> 01:23:21.840
[Guest]: will be politics, there will be alliances, there will be opposition.

01:23:21.840 --> 01:23:26.660
[Guest]: And how do you get around that is then the key challenge.

01:23:26.660 --> 01:23:30.880
[Amit Varma]: So I have a further question following up on this point before we go to the next learning

01:23:30.880 --> 01:23:35.840
[Amit Varma]: we need to make, which is that one, I completely agree with you about how people's political

01:23:35.840 --> 01:23:40.240
[Amit Varma]: affiliations can sometimes distort the way that they look at a policy.

01:23:40.240 --> 01:23:45.880
[Amit Varma]: For example, the recent farm bills, which were actually almost 20 years in the making

01:23:45.880 --> 01:23:50.960
[Amit Varma]: by different experts and incorporated things that everybody across the aisle had at one

01:23:50.960 --> 01:23:53.600
[Amit Varma]: time agreed that these were necessary reforms.

01:23:53.600 --> 01:23:57.840
[Amit Varma]: And I don't like all nuances of the particular bill, there are some things which can go,

01:23:57.840 --> 01:24:00.760
[Amit Varma]: but on the whole, they're a step in the right direction.

01:24:00.760 --> 01:24:04.800
[Amit Varma]: But our politics is so polarized that there was never any chance that something like this

01:24:04.800 --> 01:24:06.560
[Amit Varma]: would not find protest.

01:24:06.560 --> 01:24:10.600
[Amit Varma]: And this is something both the economics and the politics of it is something that I discussed

01:24:10.600 --> 01:24:14.880
[Amit Varma]: in detail with Ajay Shah in an episode we did on the farm bills, where we went into

01:24:14.880 --> 01:24:18.220
[Amit Varma]: a fair bit of detail, and both of us felt that the bill was great, but the politics

01:24:18.220 --> 01:24:22.040
[Amit Varma]: around it, that the Modi government mishandled it completely.

01:24:22.040 --> 01:24:26.680
[Amit Varma]: And their approach to the protesters was just completely wrong and out of whack.

01:24:26.680 --> 01:24:30.480
[Amit Varma]: And also the anti-democratic way this was passed through, but leave that aside.

01:24:30.480 --> 01:24:34.880
[Amit Varma]: And another example of that is the repealing of the labor laws by the UP government last

01:24:34.880 --> 01:24:35.880
[Amit Varma]: year.

01:24:35.880 --> 01:24:38.600
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, maybe the repealing could have been done slightly differently.

01:24:38.600 --> 01:24:42.880
[Amit Varma]: But there is no doubt that the labor laws were a blot that they hurt workers far more

01:24:42.880 --> 01:24:43.880
[Amit Varma]: than they helped them.

01:24:43.880 --> 01:24:47.440
[Amit Varma]: They were in fact, one of the many causes for the continuing poverty across many parts

01:24:47.440 --> 01:24:48.440
[Amit Varma]: of the country.

01:24:48.440 --> 01:24:52.920
[Amit Varma]: And yet, because of which politician happened to announce it, you know, it became a polarized

01:24:52.920 --> 01:24:53.920
[Amit Varma]: issue.

01:24:53.920 --> 01:24:58.480
[Amit Varma]: Now, my thing is that in times where politics has become so deeply polarized, perhaps exacerbated

01:24:58.480 --> 01:25:05.080
[Amit Varma]: by social media, does that make the art of getting policy through even more difficult?

01:25:05.080 --> 01:25:08.480
[Amit Varma]: Because then the question that comes up is like, no matter what you do, you are going

01:25:08.480 --> 01:25:12.840
[Amit Varma]: to have mad opposition, you're going to have mad organized opposition to it, no matter

01:25:12.840 --> 01:25:17.080
[Amit Varma]: what you do, you know, even if you happen to do something good, because even a broken

01:25:17.080 --> 01:25:20.720
[Amit Varma]: clock is right twice a day, you know, even a bad government can get one random policy

01:25:20.720 --> 01:25:22.040
[Amit Varma]: right somewhere.

01:25:22.040 --> 01:25:28.120
[Amit Varma]: So now you have, of course, been through this for seven in public policy for seven years,

01:25:28.120 --> 01:25:30.240
[Amit Varma]: almost as long as Modi ji himself.

01:25:30.240 --> 01:25:35.520
[Amit Varma]: So do you feel that that changing landscape makes a difference or do you feel that besides

01:25:35.520 --> 01:25:39.400
[Amit Varma]: these kind of big bang reforms, which get in get in the news, there's scope for doing

01:25:39.400 --> 01:25:43.320
[Amit Varma]: a lot of small, small things at a local level and all of that, which do make a positive

01:25:43.320 --> 01:25:44.320
[Amit Varma]: difference?

01:25:44.320 --> 01:25:52.600
[Guest]: Yeah, I think not just local level, you know, it is possible to see still, changes are happening,

01:25:52.600 --> 01:25:53.600
[Guest]: right?

01:25:53.600 --> 01:25:57.280
[Guest]: They are not happening in the direction that you or I want to eat them to go.

01:25:57.280 --> 01:26:03.400
[Guest]: But changes are happening quick and fast, right, lots of policy changes do get made.

01:26:03.400 --> 01:26:07.480
[Guest]: So the idea is that anyways, politics is the art of the possible, right?

01:26:07.480 --> 01:26:13.200
[Guest]: So there will be people who will get through, they know how to manage the interests of lot

01:26:13.200 --> 01:26:17.120
[Guest]: of people, politicians know it much, much better than you and I do.

01:26:17.120 --> 01:26:24.840
[Guest]: So the idea is, can the policy wonk at least propose solutions which they can reasonably

01:26:24.840 --> 01:26:27.000
[Guest]: go and present to their constituents, you know.

01:26:27.000 --> 01:26:32.640
[Guest]: So that is the idea and the responsibility of the policy wonk that they have thought

01:26:32.640 --> 01:26:37.520
[Guest]: through the solutions, thought through the implementation, proposed a transition path,

01:26:37.520 --> 01:26:38.520
[Guest]: right?

01:26:38.520 --> 01:26:43.360
[Guest]: I think your example of the farm bills is similar to what you said about the GST bill,

01:26:43.360 --> 01:26:44.440
[Guest]: I would say, right?

01:26:44.440 --> 01:26:49.960
[Guest]: In the sense that, again, yeah, both are great on paper, but implementation went bad, right?

01:26:49.960 --> 01:26:54.000
[Guest]: So you could have thought of, you know, see there, you know that there will be people

01:26:54.000 --> 01:27:00.360
[Guest]: who will oppose this, the government has literally paid people to grow a crop for 30-40 years

01:27:00.360 --> 01:27:04.760
[Guest]: and today, tomorrow it is saying that maybe we won't do that in one way or the other,

01:27:04.760 --> 01:27:05.760
[Guest]: right?

01:27:05.760 --> 01:27:11.080
[Guest]: So you know that upfront, how do you propose a solution which would have sort of taken

01:27:11.080 --> 01:27:13.160
[Guest]: into account this fear, right?

01:27:13.160 --> 01:27:16.640
[Guest]: That is, I think, something could have been anticipated, right?

01:27:16.640 --> 01:27:22.840
[Guest]: So that's why I would say, again, it is the same fallacy, good policy and bad implementation.

01:27:22.840 --> 01:27:27.000
[Guest]: It was not implemented well, so it is not a good policy, it should have thought through

01:27:27.000 --> 01:27:31.200
[Guest]: that these are the people who are losing out, okay, so if they are losing out, how do we

01:27:31.200 --> 01:27:32.680
[Guest]: make things better for them?

01:27:32.680 --> 01:27:35.800
[Guest]: How do we take them along, which wasn't done, right?

01:27:35.800 --> 01:27:38.800
[Guest]: So that's where I would put it.

01:27:38.800 --> 01:27:44.320
[Amit Varma]: I think this was not so much though the false dichotomy of policy and implementation.

01:27:44.320 --> 01:27:49.160
[Amit Varma]: This was more about the often real dichotomy of economics and politics, that sometimes

01:27:49.160 --> 01:27:54.680
[Amit Varma]: good economics can be bad politics, you know, or sometimes, you know, the way a politician

01:27:54.680 --> 01:27:58.800
[Amit Varma]: might sell an idea can lead you in the wrong direction, either it's, you know, there might

01:27:58.800 --> 01:28:03.920
[Amit Varma]: be a good policy which is sold badly, or there might be a bad policy which is sold well,

01:28:03.920 --> 01:28:10.640
[Amit Varma]: you know, like a lot of paternalistic policies will be because often the popular or the populist

01:28:10.640 --> 01:28:15.440
[Amit Varma]: understanding of economics will contain a lot of things that we know are fallacies,

01:28:15.440 --> 01:28:19.360
[Amit Varma]: for example, the zero sumness of everything, the fact that the notion that government spending

01:28:19.360 --> 01:28:24.720
[Amit Varma]: has no opportunity cost, which is why, you know, the most popular thing you can offer

01:28:24.720 --> 01:28:27.360
[Amit Varma]: farmers before an election is a farm loan waiver.

01:28:27.360 --> 01:28:32.320
[Amit Varma]: And sometimes the farmers are in such dire straits that it is actually justified anesthesia,

01:28:32.320 --> 01:28:37.000
[Amit Varma]: but it is only an immediate painkiller while there is a deeper cancer that has to be sorted

01:28:37.000 --> 01:28:41.840
[Amit Varma]: and which is not there in the popular imagination, and there's no demand for it.

01:28:41.840 --> 01:28:45.200
[Amit Varma]: But yeah, that's that's a kind of a complex problem.

01:28:45.200 --> 01:28:49.080
[Amit Varma]: Let's go on to the fourth thing that we need to unlearn about public policy.

01:28:49.080 --> 01:28:54.480
[Guest]: Yeah, the fourth one thing, we've discussed it already, just the idea that you judge a

01:28:54.480 --> 01:28:57.520
[Guest]: policy by the benefits alone, right.

01:28:57.520 --> 01:29:02.760
[Guest]: So that is, again, a fallacy, as we discussed, you need to take into account both costs and

01:29:02.760 --> 01:29:03.760
[Guest]: benefits, right.

01:29:03.760 --> 01:29:10.280
[Guest]: So the thing is, public policy is what government or any, any of the three organs of the government

01:29:10.280 --> 01:29:11.280
[Guest]: do, right.

01:29:11.280 --> 01:29:17.000
[Guest]: And the fact that there is so much money going into it, and it is the government, the state

01:29:17.000 --> 01:29:23.760
[Guest]: as an institution as force behind it, it can impact all citizens, right, even citizens,

01:29:23.760 --> 01:29:25.640
[Guest]: even people who are not in India.

01:29:25.640 --> 01:29:31.920
[Guest]: So with that power behind you, obviously, even the worst public policy will generate

01:29:31.920 --> 01:29:37.880
[Guest]: some benefits, you know, it's so just to justify a public policy, because you have counted

01:29:37.880 --> 01:29:41.360
[Guest]: some small benefits is again, a fallacy, right.

01:29:41.360 --> 01:29:46.400
[Guest]: So you need to take into account costs and benefits on both sides, and then say whether

01:29:46.400 --> 01:29:48.360
[Guest]: this policy should be implemented or not.

01:29:48.360 --> 01:29:49.960
[Guest]: And this is not again, what happens, right.

01:29:49.960 --> 01:29:56.240
[Guest]: So you will say, yeah, demonetization, but maybe reduce some underground financing in

01:29:56.240 --> 01:30:00.240
[Guest]: one part of the country or something like that and say that, you know, see, there were

01:30:00.240 --> 01:30:01.240
[Guest]: benefits.

01:30:01.240 --> 01:30:05.080
[Guest]: Yeah, of course, there will be benefit, I can say that in there's no public policy,

01:30:05.080 --> 01:30:09.200
[Guest]: which has no benefits, you know, they're even the worst of things.

01:30:09.200 --> 01:30:11.680
[Guest]: For example, even COVID had benefits, right.

01:30:11.680 --> 01:30:18.080
[Guest]: So yeah, even lockdown had benefits, people will say they could see the shivaliks from

01:30:18.080 --> 01:30:20.680
[Guest]: Uttar Pradesh or something.

01:30:20.680 --> 01:30:21.680
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:30:21.680 --> 01:30:25.080
[Guest]: So that doesn't mean that COVID-19 is a great thing to have happened, right.

01:30:25.080 --> 01:30:32.280
[Guest]: So similarly, judging a policy by benefits alone is a fallacy that we need to be aware

01:30:32.280 --> 01:30:35.600
[Guest]: of before learning public policy.

01:30:35.600 --> 01:30:38.600
[Amit Varma]: And a couple of nuances I'll add to this, not only do you should you calculate costs

01:30:38.600 --> 01:30:43.920
[Amit Varma]: and benefits, but it's also important to see, you know, who incurs the costs and who gets

01:30:43.920 --> 01:30:44.920
[Amit Varma]: the benefits.

01:30:44.920 --> 01:30:48.920
[Amit Varma]: Like, you know, in the first episode I did on demonetization with Suyash Rai, back when

01:30:48.920 --> 01:30:52.320
[Amit Varma]: the show was not four hours, but four minutes or something like that.

01:30:52.320 --> 01:30:56.120
[Amit Varma]: One of the things Suyash pointed out is that the issue with demon is that I mean, both

01:30:56.120 --> 01:30:59.720
[Amit Varma]: of us were clear that there'll be no benefits despite what they were doubting.

01:30:59.720 --> 01:31:03.240
[Amit Varma]: But both of us were clear that even their calculation takes into account that one group

01:31:03.240 --> 01:31:07.880
[Amit Varma]: of people will bear substantial costs and another group of people down the line will

01:31:07.880 --> 01:31:09.520
[Amit Varma]: get some benefits.

01:31:09.520 --> 01:31:12.200
[Amit Varma]: And is that ethical is another question to ask.

01:31:12.200 --> 01:31:17.440
[Amit Varma]: I mean, one of the issues I have with consequentialism or utilitarianism or whatever, which, you

01:31:17.440 --> 01:31:22.560
[Amit Varma]: know, tries to look at the value of an action according to its consequences and basically

01:31:22.560 --> 01:31:28.320
[Amit Varma]: looking at costs and benefits is the calculation problem that society is so complex that you

01:31:28.320 --> 01:31:32.200
[Amit Varma]: can't possibly figure out the impact of any action.

01:31:32.200 --> 01:31:37.720
[Amit Varma]: And when you claim to do so, you are basically doing wishful thinking based on your biases.

01:31:37.720 --> 01:31:44.520
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, beyond that whole cost benefit analysis or a consequentialist kind of worldview.

01:31:44.520 --> 01:31:48.760
[Amit Varma]: Beyond that, there have to be some moral underpinnings that are not open to question.

01:31:48.760 --> 01:31:52.200
[Amit Varma]: And I would say like human rights, individual rights, individual freedom.

01:31:52.200 --> 01:31:57.440
[Amit Varma]: Those are some of those sort of aspects of which, you know, we should hold sacred and

01:31:57.440 --> 01:31:59.040
[Amit Varma]: consider very strongly.

01:31:59.040 --> 01:32:00.640
[Amit Varma]: And in the case of something like Demon, we didn't.

01:32:00.640 --> 01:32:06.000
[Amit Varma]: It was the largest assault on property rights in human history, as I keep saying, it's almost

01:32:06.000 --> 01:32:08.040
[Amit Varma]: become a cliche on the show, but it was.

01:32:08.040 --> 01:32:12.800
[Amit Varma]: So just at that deontological level, just at a moral level, it was wrong period.

01:32:12.800 --> 01:32:17.000
[Amit Varma]: And to me, the cost benefit calculation didn't even matter, though, obviously, the costs

01:32:17.000 --> 01:32:19.720
[Amit Varma]: were far greater than the benefits, if at all there were any.

01:32:19.720 --> 01:32:23.120
[Amit Varma]: But the point is, to me, it didn't matter because the damage, the suffering that you're

01:32:23.120 --> 01:32:26.120
[Amit Varma]: causing, what can possibly justify that?

01:32:26.120 --> 01:32:29.840
[Amit Varma]: Of course, I don't intend to shit upon the whole concept of costs and benefits.

01:32:29.840 --> 01:32:34.040
[Amit Varma]: Of course, you have to take it into account because there are trade-offs in any action.

01:32:34.040 --> 01:32:38.160
[Amit Varma]: And because when you propose a public policy, there is a certain state of affairs in the

01:32:38.160 --> 01:32:40.160
[Amit Varma]: world which you are trying to change.

01:32:40.160 --> 01:32:44.960
[Amit Varma]: And if it, you know, makes things better, then that's great, except that we need to

01:32:44.960 --> 01:32:49.520
[Amit Varma]: consider all angles of it, do some probabilistic thinking and so on and so forth.

01:32:49.520 --> 01:32:50.520
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:32:50.520 --> 01:32:55.120
[Guest]: And I would add to it, even in cost benefits, yes, you will look at concentrated benefits

01:32:55.120 --> 01:32:58.000
[Guest]: versus dispersed costs and all that, right?

01:32:58.000 --> 01:33:01.840
[Guest]: So it's not just about cost to the government, right?

01:33:01.840 --> 01:33:04.000
[Guest]: It's cost to the society as a whole.

01:33:04.000 --> 01:33:07.440
[Guest]: So you will take into account these things.

01:33:07.440 --> 01:33:12.400
[Guest]: And yeah, I mean, our preference would be that, you know, you don't want to just incur

01:33:12.400 --> 01:33:17.560
[Guest]: huge dispersed costs on a large number of people just to achieve some concentrated benefits.

01:33:17.560 --> 01:33:22.520
[Guest]: In fact, there's a nice Wilson's interest group matrix that probably we can link to,

01:33:22.520 --> 01:33:26.080
[Guest]: where it says that client politics is the easiest to do.

01:33:26.080 --> 01:33:30.880
[Guest]: Client politics is when you have concentrated benefits, but dispersed costs, right?

01:33:30.880 --> 01:33:32.640
[Guest]: And that's the easiest thing.

01:33:32.640 --> 01:33:37.520
[Guest]: But exactly the opposite thing is the toughest type of politics to do, right?

01:33:37.520 --> 01:33:42.760
[Guest]: And I think he calls it entrepreneurial politics, but where actually the benefits are dispersed

01:33:42.760 --> 01:33:45.020
[Guest]: and the costs are concentrated.

01:33:45.020 --> 01:33:47.520
[Guest]: So that is the difficult thing to do.

01:33:47.520 --> 01:33:51.640
[Guest]: But I mean, again, as I said, politics is the art of possible.

01:33:51.640 --> 01:33:56.520
[Guest]: So people can, we at least we should push the government towards achieving that.

01:33:56.520 --> 01:34:01.480
[Guest]: And I know you've discussed this before, but I would put petrol prices also in this category.

01:34:01.480 --> 01:34:05.880
[Guest]: It's the same thing, you are incurring so much dispersed costs to a large number of

01:34:05.880 --> 01:34:06.880
[Guest]: people.

01:34:06.880 --> 01:34:08.400
[Guest]: And that doesn't make sense.

01:34:08.400 --> 01:34:13.600
[Guest]: It has a lot of attendant costs down the line also.

01:34:13.600 --> 01:34:18.600
[Guest]: But just why would you incur that to so many people for achieving whatever you want to

01:34:18.600 --> 01:34:20.440
[Guest]: do with the government?

01:34:20.440 --> 01:34:25.160
[Amit Varma]: You know, one way of thinking about this is that, let us say that I make a public policy

01:34:25.160 --> 01:34:31.260
[Amit Varma]: proposal that every year Pranay Kutasane will get a subsidy from the government of more

01:34:31.260 --> 01:34:33.000
[Amit Varma]: than a hundred crores, right?

01:34:33.000 --> 01:34:37.920
[Amit Varma]: Now, the benefit of this is, of course, to Mr. Kutasane who gets a hundred crores a year.

01:34:37.920 --> 01:34:38.920
[Amit Varma]: What is the cost of it?

01:34:38.920 --> 01:34:42.840
[Amit Varma]: It's one rupee for every citizen, a little less than that, depending on what our population

01:34:42.840 --> 01:34:43.840
[Amit Varma]: is.

01:34:43.840 --> 01:34:44.840
[Amit Varma]: It's less than a rupee for every citizen.

01:34:44.840 --> 01:34:48.600
[Amit Varma]: Now, this is what is known as concentrated benefit and dispersed costs.

01:34:48.600 --> 01:34:52.200
[Amit Varma]: And because these costs are dispersed, most people won't even know that they are losing

01:34:52.200 --> 01:34:54.000
[Amit Varma]: one rupee effectively.

01:34:54.000 --> 01:34:57.480
[Amit Varma]: And even if they know that they are losing one rupee, they won't really care enough about

01:34:57.480 --> 01:35:02.340
[Amit Varma]: it because that one rupee is not worth the cost of protesting and so on and so forth.

01:35:02.340 --> 01:35:04.520
[Amit Varma]: And it will probably be unseen anyway.

01:35:04.520 --> 01:35:09.400
[Amit Varma]: And where this corrupts the system is that Pranay out of that hundred crores can now

01:35:09.400 --> 01:35:14.840
[Amit Varma]: give, it's perfectly rational for him to give 50 crores in bribes to MPs and legislators

01:35:14.840 --> 01:35:18.800
[Amit Varma]: and ministers and all of that and say that keep the policy going, bhaiya.

01:35:18.800 --> 01:35:22.880
[Amit Varma]: Tumhara bhi fayda, hamara bhi fayda, positive sum game between the two of them, society

01:35:22.880 --> 01:35:23.880
[Amit Varma]: loses.

01:35:23.880 --> 01:35:27.000
[Amit Varma]: You know, and of course, this interest groups problem is, interest groups and lobbying,

01:35:27.000 --> 01:35:31.480
[Amit Varma]: this problem is far worse in the US and here, I think Jonathan Rauch had a great book on

01:35:31.480 --> 01:35:36.000
[Amit Varma]: it called Government's End, which I'll link from the show notes, which really goes deeply

01:35:36.000 --> 01:35:37.240
[Amit Varma]: into the problem.

01:35:37.240 --> 01:35:42.800
[Amit Varma]: But this becomes a problem structurally because all politics then comes down to interest groups

01:35:42.800 --> 01:35:47.680
[Amit Varma]: lobbying for whoever they're representing to get a benefit.

01:35:47.680 --> 01:35:52.200
[Amit Varma]: Another example of this is, for example, both the Aam Aadmi Party and the BJP at one point

01:35:52.200 --> 01:35:56.600
[Amit Varma]: in time, I think the BJP kind of changed his mind eventually, but at one point in time,

01:35:56.600 --> 01:36:01.800
[Amit Varma]: they were on the same page when it came to FDI in retail, where they were against it.

01:36:01.800 --> 01:36:06.880
[Amit Varma]: And the reason is simple to understand that all the small retailers could easily get together

01:36:06.880 --> 01:36:11.480
[Amit Varma]: and form an interest group and lobby and pay off whatever politicians they had to give

01:36:11.480 --> 01:36:16.080
[Amit Varma]: and fill the party coffers or whatever party they were supporting, or just form a significant

01:36:16.080 --> 01:36:20.260
[Amit Varma]: vote bank as they do in Delhi and say, no, you know, ban FDI.

01:36:20.260 --> 01:36:21.640
[Amit Varma]: And who lost through this?

01:36:21.640 --> 01:36:24.880
[Amit Varma]: Consumers lost through this because consumers would have got everything cheaper, cheaper

01:36:24.880 --> 01:36:28.880
[Amit Varma]: or better, or both had FDI and retail been allowed.

01:36:28.880 --> 01:36:32.000
[Amit Varma]: And in the long run, all the money they would have saved would have gone back into the economy

01:36:32.000 --> 01:36:35.560
[Amit Varma]: and generated jobs and society would have been much better off.

01:36:35.560 --> 01:36:37.900
[Amit Varma]: But those benefits were diffused.

01:36:37.900 --> 01:36:42.160
[Amit Varma]: And in this specific case, invisible, because, you know, you can't put a number to it, it's

01:36:42.160 --> 01:36:44.100
[Amit Varma]: a scene in the unseen.

01:36:44.100 --> 01:36:48.520
[Amit Varma]: And that powerful interest group with, you know, concentrated benefits kind of gets away

01:36:48.520 --> 01:36:53.720
[Amit Varma]: and so much of politics is like this that I am sometimes, I sometimes wonder if there

01:36:53.720 --> 01:36:56.320
[Amit Varma]: can be any politics outside of this.

01:36:56.320 --> 01:37:04.280
[Guest]: No, I just gave you an example of a policy where they were able to overcome exactly this

01:37:04.280 --> 01:37:06.560
[Guest]: kind of situation, right?

01:37:06.560 --> 01:37:12.040
[Guest]: So I mean, imagine you tell a government person that you won't get pension the way you used

01:37:12.040 --> 01:37:16.200
[Guest]: to earlier, what protests would have been there?

01:37:16.200 --> 01:37:21.400
[Guest]: There are other examples also computerization of banks, it did happen, there was same fears,

01:37:21.400 --> 01:37:22.400
[Guest]: right?

01:37:22.400 --> 01:37:24.440
[Guest]: That no computerization will take away our jobs.

01:37:24.440 --> 01:37:28.040
[Guest]: So why should we and but that did happen, right?

01:37:28.040 --> 01:37:35.080
[Guest]: So there are many examples, which we don't appreciate because just the way it was done

01:37:35.080 --> 01:37:36.080
[Guest]: is unseen, right?

01:37:36.080 --> 01:37:42.640
[Guest]: The way these effects were overcome the way interest groups were mollified or taken on

01:37:42.640 --> 01:37:43.720
[Guest]: board is unseen.

01:37:43.720 --> 01:37:49.920
[Guest]: So we that's why I think we need a better understanding of policy successes, we look

01:37:49.920 --> 01:37:55.240
[Guest]: at policy failures, and we can pontificate a lot, you and I know that, okay, these are

01:37:55.240 --> 01:37:59.560
[Guest]: the failures, but we need to document our success as well as well, you know, and that

01:37:59.560 --> 01:38:05.000
[Guest]: will probably tell us and give us clues as to how do you overcome some of these things.

01:38:05.000 --> 01:38:09.880
[Guest]: And for at least I can say there are these two examples, which say it is possible, you

01:38:09.880 --> 01:38:10.880
[Amit Varma]: know.

01:38:10.880 --> 01:38:14.520
[Amit Varma]: No, and that's a profound point in the sense that if you're pushing a policy, the way to

01:38:14.520 --> 01:38:19.120
[Amit Varma]: push it is not to go to the people in charge and say that, listen, here are the benefits,

01:38:19.120 --> 01:38:20.760
[Amit Varma]: society will benefit, that means nothing.

01:38:20.760 --> 01:38:24.040
[Amit Varma]: You also have to consider that who are the people this will hurt?

01:38:24.040 --> 01:38:25.620
[Amit Varma]: How do we get past that?

01:38:25.620 --> 01:38:27.380
[Amit Varma]: How do we find compromises?

01:38:27.380 --> 01:38:32.280
[Amit Varma]: Like you said, politics being the art of the possible, which is all so fascinating to me.

01:38:32.280 --> 01:38:36.920
[Amit Varma]: Let's move on to the fifth thing now, the fifth thing that one should unlearn.

01:38:36.920 --> 01:38:41.240
[Guest]: Yeah, so I think this is more of a personal sort of thing.

01:38:41.240 --> 01:38:47.040
[Guest]: But just the fact that you need to always defend your model of the world is one again

01:38:47.040 --> 01:38:52.240
[Guest]: a fallacy because public policy is different from physics in that sense, right?

01:38:52.240 --> 01:38:58.000
[Guest]: I mean, you will not come with really strong, you know, you won't come to blows, at least

01:38:58.000 --> 01:38:59.520
[Guest]: you and I probably won't.

01:38:59.520 --> 01:39:04.720
[Guest]: Maybe physicists do, but we won't come to blows on some of the things about quantum

01:39:04.720 --> 01:39:05.720
[Guest]: mechanics.

01:39:05.720 --> 01:39:11.440
[Guest]: But you will come to blows on how the world works or whether government should have capital

01:39:11.440 --> 01:39:13.560
[Guest]: punishment or not or things like that, you know.

01:39:13.560 --> 01:39:21.960
[Guest]: So the idea is that it is actually, we are not learning if we think that we know how

01:39:21.960 --> 01:39:23.560
[Guest]: the world functions, right?

01:39:23.560 --> 01:39:29.680
[Guest]: And the whole idea is like how Ambedkar had written about is that consistency is the virtue

01:39:29.680 --> 01:39:31.260
[Guest]: of an ass.

01:39:31.260 --> 01:39:35.680
[Guest]: And I'm not one of them, like he quoted someone to this effect.

01:39:35.680 --> 01:39:36.680
[Guest]: That's the idea, right?

01:39:36.680 --> 01:39:41.280
[Guest]: So why would you think that the model that you have has all the answers?

01:39:41.280 --> 01:39:47.200
[Guest]: So the more we are open to the fact that, you know, there are complex human motivations,

01:39:47.200 --> 01:39:53.280
[Guest]: the way we learn and our models and our priors can change, then we start off on the right

01:39:53.280 --> 01:39:55.480
[Guest]: foot by learning public policy.

01:39:55.480 --> 01:40:00.480
[Guest]: Otherwise, we just go away, reinforcing the priors with which we began.

01:40:00.480 --> 01:40:01.480
[Guest]: And that doesn't help.

01:40:01.480 --> 01:40:05.720
[Amit Varma]: No, and it's a profound point because like another of the people who did my writing course,

01:40:05.720 --> 01:40:10.040
[Amit Varma]: Nishant Jain, who is called Sneaky Art on Twitter, really good artist, does situational

01:40:10.040 --> 01:40:11.040
[Amit Varma]: street art.

01:40:11.040 --> 01:40:12.520
[Amit Varma]: If he's sitting near you, he's probably drawing you.

01:40:12.520 --> 01:40:13.520
[Amit Varma]: So beware of him.

01:40:13.520 --> 01:40:17.600
[Amit Varma]: He shared a quote with you, which I just love and the quote is quote, every model is wrong.

01:40:17.600 --> 01:40:19.720
[Amit Varma]: Some models are useful, stop quote.

01:40:19.720 --> 01:40:23.000
[Amit Varma]: And that's useful to remember that you might have a model of how the world works at the

01:40:23.000 --> 01:40:27.080
[Amit Varma]: state must do everything or that markets will solve everything or whatever the model might

01:40:27.080 --> 01:40:28.080
[Amit Varma]: be.

01:40:28.080 --> 01:40:33.200
[Amit Varma]: But the point is that you can't get wedded to a model as if it is a religious idea.

01:40:33.200 --> 01:40:37.360
[Amit Varma]: You have to always, as John Maynard Keynes said, that when the facts change, I change

01:40:37.360 --> 01:40:38.360
[Amit Varma]: my mind.

01:40:38.360 --> 01:40:39.360
[Amit Varma]: So what do you do?

01:40:39.360 --> 01:40:42.520
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote in response to somebody saying that you said that 10 years ago, now you are

01:40:42.520 --> 01:40:43.660
[Amit Varma]: saying this.

01:40:43.660 --> 01:40:48.320
[Amit Varma]: And the point is that the real world is so deeply complex that even if you have a mental

01:40:48.320 --> 01:40:54.680
[Amit Varma]: model, which is incredibly useful, you always have to be open to, you know, rethinking aspects

01:40:54.680 --> 01:41:00.480
[Amit Varma]: of it or just looking or even going against your model, when reality means that your model

01:41:00.480 --> 01:41:03.920
[Amit Varma]: in a pure form can't actually be carried out.

01:41:03.920 --> 01:41:09.600
[Amit Varma]: So yeah, that's that's a profound point, just calling for intellectual humility.

01:41:09.600 --> 01:41:10.600
[Guest]: What's the sixth view?

01:41:10.600 --> 01:41:17.000
[Guest]: Yeah, sixth is something we've already discussed in the sense how economics is capitalism versus

01:41:17.000 --> 01:41:19.840
[Guest]: socialism, that's again a fallacy.

01:41:19.840 --> 01:41:24.440
[Guest]: And because it is economics, capitalism versus socialism, I don't need it.

01:41:24.440 --> 01:41:29.760
[Guest]: And a lot of people will start with this assumption, you know, that's why economics is useless.

01:41:29.760 --> 01:41:34.280
[Guest]: It's about Adam Smith versus Karl Marx, and why should I bother?

01:41:34.280 --> 01:41:39.700
[Guest]: But like we've already discussed, economic reasoning is so fundamental to making good

01:41:39.700 --> 01:41:44.560
[Guest]: public policies or better public policies that we need to get out of this mindset, right?

01:41:44.560 --> 01:41:49.720
[Guest]: Basically, it's nothing to do with capitalism or socialism.

01:41:49.720 --> 01:41:54.920
[Guest]: It's just at least microeconomics is just about understanding human behavior.

01:41:54.920 --> 01:41:56.600
[Guest]: It's a science of scarcity.

01:41:56.600 --> 01:41:59.240
[Guest]: How do you allocate resources when you have scarcity?

01:41:59.240 --> 01:42:02.760
[Guest]: That is precisely what public policy will try to address, right?

01:42:02.760 --> 01:42:09.200
[Guest]: So that's why just getting out of this mindset is important before you dive in in this domain.

01:42:09.200 --> 01:42:10.200
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:42:10.200 --> 01:42:11.640
[Amit Varma]: And how do people respond to incentives?

01:42:11.640 --> 01:42:16.360
[Amit Varma]: And earlier during our conversation, at some point, I wrote behave on my page.

01:42:16.360 --> 01:42:19.420
[Amit Varma]: And that was not an exhortation either to you or to me.

01:42:19.420 --> 01:42:24.000
[Amit Varma]: But it's because I meant to plug a book which I forgot to plug, which is Behave by Robert

01:42:24.000 --> 01:42:25.000
[Amit Varma]: Sapolsky.

01:42:25.000 --> 01:42:29.600
[Amit Varma]: Robert Sapolsky is this great biologist, he also has these incredible lectures on YouTube,

01:42:29.600 --> 01:42:31.160
[Amit Varma]: which are linked from the show notes.

01:42:31.160 --> 01:42:34.800
[Amit Varma]: It's a wonder that, you know, such people can share their insights and everyone in the

01:42:34.800 --> 01:42:37.100
[Amit Varma]: world can listen to it, theoretically.

01:42:37.100 --> 01:42:42.160
[Amit Varma]: But what the book is about is it looks at the origins of behavior at several different

01:42:42.160 --> 01:42:43.160
[Amit Varma]: levels.

01:42:43.160 --> 01:42:45.560
[Amit Varma]: Like if I do something now, right?

01:42:45.560 --> 01:42:51.360
[Amit Varma]: Like if you say something and I lose my temper, it will first examine the most proximate cause

01:42:51.360 --> 01:42:53.800
[Amit Varma]: what you said and why I lost my temper.

01:42:53.800 --> 01:42:57.000
[Amit Varma]: But then it'll go a little further back, what is the neurochemistry of my brain?

01:42:57.000 --> 01:43:02.520
[Amit Varma]: What is, you know, did I wake up late and not have breakfast or did I have some disease

01:43:02.520 --> 01:43:05.680
[Amit Varma]: a week ago for which I had some medication which changed my imbalance?

01:43:05.680 --> 01:43:08.520
[Amit Varma]: So it'll look at that layer of causation.

01:43:08.520 --> 01:43:12.400
[Amit Varma]: And like that, it keeps peeling the layers back all the way till you get to prehistoric

01:43:12.400 --> 01:43:17.160
[Amit Varma]: times and evolution shaped, you know, the way our brain works and the way we react to

01:43:17.160 --> 01:43:18.700
[Amit Varma]: everything and all of that.

01:43:18.700 --> 01:43:23.300
[Amit Varma]: And it makes you kind of realize that there are so many layers of causation behind every

01:43:23.300 --> 01:43:24.900
[Amit Varma]: little thing that we do.

01:43:24.900 --> 01:43:29.780
[Amit Varma]: And sometimes we may not even be kind of aware of what those things are, you know, which

01:43:29.780 --> 01:43:34.520
[Amit Varma]: means that it's always important to think of humans as containing these multitudes as

01:43:34.520 --> 01:43:37.580
[Amit Varma]: being complex and all these different factors.

01:43:37.580 --> 01:43:42.240
[Amit Varma]: So even there, there are limits to, I mean, that fundamental thing that humans respond

01:43:42.240 --> 01:43:45.880
[Amit Varma]: to incentives are true, but those incentives aren't just proximate incentives, there's

01:43:45.880 --> 01:43:47.920
[Amit Varma]: a lot of other shit going on.

01:43:47.920 --> 01:43:52.240
[Amit Varma]: And there's a lot of, you know, what is important is not just defining incentives, but defining

01:43:52.240 --> 01:43:53.240
[Amit Varma]: humans.

01:43:53.240 --> 01:43:56.860
[Amit Varma]: And humans are, you know, a mix of so many different things.

01:43:56.860 --> 01:44:04.000
[Amit Varma]: But I think economic reasoning certainly helps in increasing your chance of, you know, understanding

01:44:04.000 --> 01:44:05.000
[Amit Varma]: the world.

01:44:05.000 --> 01:44:10.360
[Amit Varma]: But, you know, my little mini lecture apart, let's move on to point number seven.

01:44:10.360 --> 01:44:17.480
[Guest]: Yeah, point number seven is, again, this idea of experience versus theory, you know, often

01:44:17.480 --> 01:44:22.640
[Guest]: will again come across this idea that what works for me works for everyone else, or I

01:44:22.640 --> 01:44:28.320
[Guest]: stayed in a village, I know how people work there, or how they respond to policy incentives.

01:44:28.320 --> 01:44:31.440
[Guest]: So that's why it will work all across the world, right.

01:44:31.440 --> 01:44:36.800
[Guest]: But like, it really ties in nicely to what you mentioned, that, you know, we have our

01:44:36.800 --> 01:44:42.240
[Guest]: own limitations of perception and memory, both the way we interpret lead to cognitive

01:44:42.240 --> 01:44:43.240
[Guest]: biases.

01:44:43.240 --> 01:44:47.200
[Guest]: And there are hundreds of cognitive biases now, documented ones.

01:44:47.200 --> 01:44:53.480
[Guest]: And those cognitive biases just say that, you know, just because you saw one thing,

01:44:53.480 --> 01:44:59.480
[Guest]: the way it worked, or a one policy, maybe NREGS worked great in your village, and people

01:44:59.480 --> 01:45:01.600
[Guest]: actually had benefits for that.

01:45:01.600 --> 01:45:07.080
[Guest]: But does that make sense at a national level, you have to go down further, right, you have

01:45:07.080 --> 01:45:11.760
[Guest]: to ask the cost, you have to ask what were the unintended effects, and things like that.

01:45:11.760 --> 01:45:16.960
[Guest]: It can't be just because you were in a village, and there were great things happened there,

01:45:16.960 --> 01:45:19.320
[Guest]: that you justify that entire policy.

01:45:19.320 --> 01:45:25.240
[Guest]: So that idea is, again, just something to keep in mind, because you'll always see experience

01:45:25.240 --> 01:45:28.680
[Guest]: alone masquerading as good policy knowledge.

01:45:28.680 --> 01:45:30.240
[Guest]: And that is something to keep in mind.

01:45:30.240 --> 01:45:35.880
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and I also had a good episode on this with Shruti Rajgopalan and Alex Tabarrok.

01:45:35.880 --> 01:45:40.320
[Amit Varma]: And the technical term they used is isomorphic mimicry, where just because you know, one

01:45:40.320 --> 01:45:45.160
[Amit Varma]: policy has worked in one place, you try it in another place and assume that it will work.

01:45:45.160 --> 01:45:50.160
[Amit Varma]: You know, and that goes well with this Indian tendency of trying to have an answer to everything,

01:45:50.160 --> 01:45:53.920
[Amit Varma]: where there's this old joke about how you go on the street of any Indian city and you

01:45:53.920 --> 01:45:56.560
[Amit Varma]: ask a passerby, ki wahan kaise jaana hai?

01:45:56.560 --> 01:46:00.840
[Amit Varma]: Even if you name a fictional place, they will give you directions, ki dine jaye, phir left

01:46:00.840 --> 01:46:05.520
[Amit Varma]: jaye, phir seeda jaye, 200 meter ke baad aap paan wale se pooch lijiye.

01:46:05.520 --> 01:46:10.000
[Amit Varma]: Possibly I'm sort of caricaturing it as an Indian trait, where it might be a universal

01:46:10.000 --> 01:46:12.640
[Amit Varma]: trait, and we've only noticed it in India.

01:46:12.640 --> 01:46:14.240
[Amit Varma]: But nowadays, of course, we have Google Maps.

01:46:14.240 --> 01:46:19.160
[Amit Varma]: So thankfully, we don't have to ask so many people, technology kind of really helping

01:46:19.160 --> 01:46:20.160
[Amit Varma]: us here.

01:46:20.160 --> 01:46:22.440
[Amit Varma]: So what's the eighth thing that we have to unlearn?

01:46:22.440 --> 01:46:28.160
[Guest]: Yeah, so the eighth thing is, again, it ties into what we were saying about one rupee of

01:46:28.160 --> 01:46:32.840
[Guest]: government spending being the same as one rupee of social spending, you know.

01:46:32.840 --> 01:46:38.200
[Guest]: And that's, again, a fallacy because, you know, there's something called a marginal

01:46:38.200 --> 01:46:39.800
[Guest]: cost of public finance.

01:46:39.800 --> 01:46:46.800
[Guest]: The idea being that the government, when it raises resources, there is some friction because

01:46:46.800 --> 01:46:48.520
[Guest]: of which money is lost, right?

01:46:48.520 --> 01:46:55.320
[Guest]: So the idea is you can't justify that government say spending 5000 crore on a project, the

01:46:55.320 --> 01:46:58.200
[Guest]: cost to society is actually much larger, right?

01:46:58.200 --> 01:47:02.080
[Guest]: And I think, again, Shah and Kelkar in their book say that it is 3x, right?

01:47:02.080 --> 01:47:08.400
[Guest]: So it might be the cost to society is probably 15,000 crores for a 5000 crore rupee that

01:47:08.400 --> 01:47:12.660
[Guest]: government has raised and intends to spend for the perfect of causes.

01:47:12.660 --> 01:47:16.760
[Guest]: So the way you would go about this is you need to ask the question, what is the government

01:47:16.760 --> 01:47:18.040
[Guest]: using this money on?

01:47:18.040 --> 01:47:23.160
[Guest]: Is the benefit of that more than 15,000 crores, not 5000 crores, right?

01:47:23.160 --> 01:47:24.920
[Guest]: That would be your comparison point.

01:47:24.920 --> 01:47:32.320
[Guest]: And that is another important thing to learn because that way we will think of governments

01:47:32.320 --> 01:47:35.160
[Guest]: raising money in a different manner, right?

01:47:35.160 --> 01:47:39.000
[Guest]: And we will think of governments doing the big things that it is supposed to do.

01:47:39.000 --> 01:47:43.720
[Guest]: So when governments spend on public goods or any of the market failures, then we can

01:47:43.720 --> 01:47:50.000
[Guest]: justify that the benefits probably would be more than 3x the cost that government has

01:47:50.000 --> 01:47:51.560
[Guest]: imposed on society.

01:47:51.560 --> 01:47:54.240
[Guest]: But otherwise, it doesn't make sense, you know.

01:47:54.240 --> 01:47:58.760
[Guest]: So that to me is another learning that we need to keep in mind.

01:47:58.760 --> 01:47:59.760
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:47:59.760 --> 01:48:03.320
[Amit Varma]: And this is really hard to get through to people because in India, it's almost I keep

01:48:03.320 --> 01:48:07.840
[Amit Varma]: saying our biggest religion is not even Hinduism, it's a religion of government, where anything

01:48:07.840 --> 01:48:12.120
[Amit Varma]: goes wrong, you want to fix anything in society, you say government karegi as if money falls

01:48:12.120 --> 01:48:13.120
[Amit Varma]: from the skies.

01:48:13.120 --> 01:48:14.640
[Amit Varma]: The point is money has a cost.

01:48:14.640 --> 01:48:18.400
[Amit Varma]: So if you're saying that, oh, for national pride, we need to, you know, have a giant

01:48:18.400 --> 01:48:23.280
[Amit Varma]: Sardar Patel statue, or we need to fund a space program or whatever it is.

01:48:23.280 --> 01:48:26.680
[Amit Varma]: And we say that no, all this, you know, this is the money that should be spent, we assume

01:48:26.680 --> 01:48:31.040
[Amit Varma]: that it has no cost, but the cost it has, is actually much more than what is actually

01:48:31.040 --> 01:48:35.120
[Amit Varma]: being spent, like you pointed out, if it's 5000 crores, you know, the cost to society

01:48:35.120 --> 01:48:40.600
[Amit Varma]: is 15,000 crores, Shah and Kelkar have a great explanation of this in their book and in their

01:48:40.600 --> 01:48:43.480
[Amit Varma]: episode with me, both of which I'll link from the show notes.

01:48:43.480 --> 01:48:47.400
[Amit Varma]: The other thing to remember is something that's probably summed up by an old column of mine,

01:48:47.400 --> 01:48:51.240
[Amit Varma]: where the headline was every act of government is an act of violence.

01:48:51.240 --> 01:48:55.240
[Amit Varma]: And we don't realize that, you know, what does a government need to exist, it needs

01:48:55.240 --> 01:49:00.120
[Amit Varma]: taxes, those taxes are taken essentially through this threat of coercion.

01:49:00.120 --> 01:49:04.480
[Amit Varma]: If taxes were not compulsory, if we were not going to get arrested, nobody would pay taxes.

01:49:04.480 --> 01:49:08.400
[Amit Varma]: Now it is not to say that there should be no taxes, it is just to say that we should

01:49:08.400 --> 01:49:13.160
[Amit Varma]: therefore be careful that not only is there an actual monetary cost to our spending where

01:49:13.160 --> 01:49:17.840
[Amit Varma]: 5 rupees is equal to 15 rupees or whatever, not only is that there's also a moral cost,

01:49:17.840 --> 01:49:22.920
[Amit Varma]: it involves coercion and everyone in India pays taxes, income tax may be a small percentage,

01:49:22.920 --> 01:49:28.680
[Amit Varma]: but even someone begging on the street who is later buying salt or buying soap or whatever,

01:49:28.680 --> 01:49:32.120
[Amit Varma]: they are effectively paying taxes because everything is taxed.

01:49:32.120 --> 01:49:36.040
[Amit Varma]: Therefore the point is you are committing violence on the poorest of the poor also for

01:49:36.040 --> 01:49:37.760
[Amit Varma]: every act of government spending.

01:49:37.760 --> 01:49:42.920
[Amit Varma]: So it's important that whenever there is government spending, you need to be able to justify it

01:49:42.920 --> 01:49:48.440
[Amit Varma]: and talk about whether it is actually worth it or whether this is not something that we

01:49:48.440 --> 01:49:49.440
[Amit Varma]: should do.

01:49:49.440 --> 01:49:52.800
[Amit Varma]: And moving on from that, because I wanted to talk about the Indian state next and this

01:49:52.800 --> 01:49:54.660
[Amit Varma]: seems a natural segue.

01:49:54.660 --> 01:49:58.560
[Amit Varma]: One thing that I think both of us would agree on is that there's no easy answer in terms

01:49:58.560 --> 01:50:03.680
[Amit Varma]: of the government is either spending too little or too much because I think both of us would

01:50:03.680 --> 01:50:10.080
[Amit Varma]: agree that in areas where the government has a legitimate function, like the rule of law,

01:50:10.080 --> 01:50:14.380
[Amit Varma]: like certain public goods or whatever, it does not do enough, it is basically absent.

01:50:14.380 --> 01:50:20.400
[Amit Varma]: But in areas where it has no business interfering, it has a massive superstructure, which is

01:50:20.400 --> 01:50:27.520
[Amit Varma]: a massive waste of money and also constrains society in various different ways.

01:50:27.520 --> 01:50:32.800
[Amit Varma]: How should we think about the state like before we get interested in these subjects of political

01:50:32.800 --> 01:50:36.760
[Amit Varma]: philosophy and economics and all that, we think of the state, especially in India as

01:50:36.760 --> 01:50:41.200
[Amit Varma]: oh my bab hai, you know, their job is to look after us and we will vote once in five years

01:50:41.200 --> 01:50:43.960
[Amit Varma]: and then my bab will take care of everything.

01:50:43.960 --> 01:50:50.660
[Amit Varma]: But conceptually, how did you begin to sort of fashion your thinking about the state?

01:50:50.660 --> 01:50:56.360
[Amit Varma]: And also, how did you arrive at societism, which is going to ask you about that next,

01:50:56.360 --> 01:51:02.320
[Amit Varma]: because when I was editing Pragati, the policy magazine, you'd written a famous, almost iconic,

01:51:02.320 --> 01:51:07.760
[Amit Varma]: and seminal essay for me called A Case for Societism, which argued that when it comes

01:51:07.760 --> 01:51:12.720
[Amit Varma]: to the state markets and society, we spend too much time thinking about the state and

01:51:12.720 --> 01:51:16.400
[Amit Varma]: markets and actually society can solve many of our problems.

01:51:16.400 --> 01:51:17.900
[Amit Varma]: So I'm going to ask you to elaborate on that.

01:51:17.900 --> 01:51:22.280
[Amit Varma]: But I guess before we elaborate on that, it's useful to talk about how do we conceive of

01:51:22.280 --> 01:51:23.280
[Amit Varma]: a state?

01:51:23.280 --> 01:51:26.680
[Amit Varma]: How do we conceive of its relationship with society?

01:51:26.680 --> 01:51:32.240
[Amit Varma]: And in contrast with whatever that ideal conception would be, what are things in India actually

01:51:32.240 --> 01:51:33.240
[Guest]: like?

01:51:33.240 --> 01:51:34.240
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:51:34.240 --> 01:51:36.080
[Guest]: So let's begin with India itself, right?

01:51:36.080 --> 01:51:40.920
[Guest]: Because there are lots of theories about the state and a lot of people have written books

01:51:40.920 --> 01:51:42.280
[Guest]: on great books on it.

01:51:42.280 --> 01:51:47.480
[Guest]: But let's begin with the Indian state itself and I would ask you a question.

01:51:47.480 --> 01:51:49.320
[Guest]: Why do you think that's the case?

01:51:49.320 --> 01:51:56.600
[Guest]: Like if you think that we rely on the state a lot, what are your sort of speculation about

01:51:56.600 --> 01:51:57.600
[Guest]: it?

01:51:57.600 --> 01:51:59.720
[Amit Varma]: Why is it so in India?

01:51:59.720 --> 01:52:03.720
[Amit Varma]: I think one reason is that we need to think about where our conception of the state came

01:52:03.720 --> 01:52:06.200
[Amit Varma]: from, like through the independent struggle.

01:52:06.200 --> 01:52:10.480
[Amit Varma]: The notion really was that it is a British who are evil.

01:52:10.480 --> 01:52:13.160
[Amit Varma]: It is colonialism, which is evil.

01:52:13.160 --> 01:52:15.060
[Amit Varma]: And we didn't drill one layer down.

01:52:15.060 --> 01:52:19.200
[Amit Varma]: And I would have drilled a layer down and said, okay, the British are evil, colonialism

01:52:19.200 --> 01:52:20.200
[Amit Varma]: is bad.

01:52:20.200 --> 01:52:21.200
[Amit Varma]: Why?

01:52:21.200 --> 01:52:22.320
[Amit Varma]: Let's go a little further.

01:52:22.320 --> 01:52:28.280
[Amit Varma]: And the core answer to me lies in coercion, lies in not respecting individual rights,

01:52:28.280 --> 01:52:30.760
[Amit Varma]: lies in a top-down vision of society.

01:52:30.760 --> 01:52:33.320
[Amit Varma]: Like what was the state in the conception of the British?

01:52:33.320 --> 01:52:36.080
[Amit Varma]: It was something to keep the natives under control.

01:52:36.080 --> 01:52:37.200
[Amit Varma]: That's basically what it was.

01:52:37.200 --> 01:52:41.960
[Amit Varma]: The entire IPC, the Indian Penal Code, most of which we still have on our books, came

01:52:41.960 --> 01:52:42.960
[Amit Varma]: from the British.

01:52:42.960 --> 01:52:49.120
[Amit Varma]: We still have many of those laws against free speech, for example, 295A, 153A.

01:52:49.120 --> 01:52:53.200
[Amit Varma]: All of those are still with us because what happened at independence was that there was

01:52:53.200 --> 01:52:56.080
[Amit Varma]: this massive sense of relief that the British are gone.

01:52:56.080 --> 01:52:58.800
[Amit Varma]: And partly it wasn't even that our freedom struggle really succeeded.

01:52:58.800 --> 01:53:03.600
[Amit Varma]: They were just bankrupt after the war and exhausted and whatever, but the British left.

01:53:03.600 --> 01:53:07.040
[Amit Varma]: And when they left, we took over the same state apparatus.

01:53:07.040 --> 01:53:11.840
[Amit Varma]: Even when we sat down to design the constitution, you know, there was a comment in the Constituent

01:53:11.840 --> 01:53:16.040
[Amit Varma]: Assembly when someone said that, hey, you know, we are designing the state from the

01:53:16.040 --> 01:53:18.000
[Amit Varma]: point of view of a policeman.

01:53:18.000 --> 01:53:19.360
[Amit Varma]: And that's exactly what we did.

01:53:19.360 --> 01:53:24.080
[Amit Varma]: We kept the colonial apparatus, we kept the state, we kept the Indian Penal Code, and

01:53:24.080 --> 01:53:25.080
[Amit Varma]: we kept the mindset.

01:53:25.080 --> 01:53:29.320
[Amit Varma]: You know, the British had that extremely racist mindset that, oh, these natives know nothing.

01:53:29.320 --> 01:53:33.400
[Amit Varma]: We have to civilize them and we have to teach some of them English so they can be our local

01:53:33.400 --> 01:53:38.440
[Amit Varma]: officers and all that, the whole Macaulay way of thinking.

01:53:38.440 --> 01:53:42.600
[Amit Varma]: And somehow we kept that entire apparatus and we brought that thinking when we became

01:53:42.600 --> 01:53:43.760
[Amit Varma]: independent.

01:53:43.760 --> 01:53:45.800
[Amit Varma]: And also power corrupts, right?

01:53:45.800 --> 01:53:47.260
[Amit Varma]: Power always corrupts.

01:53:47.260 --> 01:53:52.000
[Amit Varma]: So whatever ideals these people might have, when out of power, when in power, they kind

01:53:52.000 --> 01:53:58.000
[Amit Varma]: of continued, you know, all the mechanics of subjugating the people remained.

01:53:58.000 --> 01:54:03.120
[Amit Varma]: And a classic illustration of this actually comes in an episode I did with Tripur Dhaman

01:54:03.120 --> 01:54:06.080
[Amit Varma]: Singh, who wrote a great book on the First Amendment.

01:54:06.080 --> 01:54:10.840
[Amit Varma]: And what happened there was that one of these laws in the IPC, the Sedition Law, was actually

01:54:10.840 --> 01:54:15.840
[Amit Varma]: taken before the courts in 1950, where the argument before the courts was that this is

01:54:15.840 --> 01:54:20.980
[Amit Varma]: against Article 19, which guarantees us free speech, and the court struck it down.

01:54:20.980 --> 01:54:23.540
[Amit Varma]: So the Sedition Law was struck down in 1950.

01:54:23.540 --> 01:54:28.000
[Amit Varma]: And then Nehru brought it back with the First Amendment, because he wanted to use it against

01:54:28.000 --> 01:54:32.600
[Amit Varma]: political enemies of his and people who were criticizing him, right?

01:54:32.600 --> 01:54:37.120
[Amit Varma]: And of course, Nehru did, I won't say everything is Nehru's fault, he did a lot of great things,

01:54:37.120 --> 01:54:41.040
[Amit Varma]: but he was also very anti-liberal in certain ways.

01:54:41.040 --> 01:54:45.800
[Amit Varma]: In fact, the person who argued against this First Amendment and against the law of sedition

01:54:45.800 --> 01:54:48.460
[Amit Varma]: being brought back was Shyama Prasad Mukherjee.

01:54:48.460 --> 01:54:53.200
[Amit Varma]: So people contain multitudes, and you can't look at them in simplistic ways.

01:54:53.200 --> 01:54:56.560
[Amit Varma]: But what we basically did was we took that Maibab mindset.

01:54:56.560 --> 01:55:00.520
[Amit Varma]: And you know, even when designing the Constitution, I have an episode with the historian Gyan

01:55:00.520 --> 01:55:04.220
[Amit Varma]: Prakash, where Gyan Prakash wrote a book on the emergency.

01:55:04.220 --> 01:55:07.080
[Amit Varma]: And his whole point was the emergency was not an aberration.

01:55:07.080 --> 01:55:12.320
[Amit Varma]: It was not the case of a truly venal and vile mother and son pair and Indira Gandhi and

01:55:12.320 --> 01:55:14.640
[Amit Varma]: Sanjay Gandhi gone mad.

01:55:14.640 --> 01:55:20.160
[Amit Varma]: It was designed within the Constitution because the Constitution centralized power and made

01:55:20.160 --> 01:55:23.400
[Amit Varma]: it possible for Indira to do what she did.

01:55:23.400 --> 01:55:25.040
[Amit Varma]: And why did they centralize power?

01:55:25.040 --> 01:55:28.680
[Amit Varma]: Because at the time the Constitution was being debated and written, there were riots all

01:55:28.680 --> 01:55:29.920
[Amit Varma]: across the country.

01:55:29.920 --> 01:55:32.700
[Amit Varma]: There was no certainty that the center would hold as it were.

01:55:32.700 --> 01:55:37.000
[Amit Varma]: There was no certainty that the map of India would look anything like it does now.

01:55:37.000 --> 01:55:40.200
[Amit Varma]: So that urge to centralize power is understandable.

01:55:40.200 --> 01:55:45.400
[Amit Varma]: But what we ended up with was power that is too centralized and power always corrupts.

01:55:45.400 --> 01:55:50.340
[Amit Varma]: And this mindset then went to the people now, again, to continue the other sort of aspect

01:55:50.340 --> 01:55:54.720
[Amit Varma]: which you have also written about and commented upon is that the other aspect was that all

01:55:54.720 --> 01:55:59.360
[Amit Varma]: of these great freedom fighters recognized that there were many social ills that had

01:55:59.360 --> 01:56:00.660
[Amit Varma]: to be sorted out.

01:56:00.660 --> 01:56:06.200
[Amit Varma]: And people like Gandhi and to a large extent Ambedkar said that these can come out of that

01:56:06.200 --> 01:56:08.360
[Amit Varma]: society can solve these problems.

01:56:08.360 --> 01:56:13.200
[Amit Varma]: But there was also a strain of top-down thinking which said that, no, let's design a constitution

01:56:13.200 --> 01:56:17.840
[Amit Varma]: which makes sure that the state solves these social problems, a transformative constitution

01:56:17.840 --> 01:56:21.680
[Amit Varma]: as it were in Gautam Bhatia's words, he's written a book on it.

01:56:21.680 --> 01:56:23.240
[Amit Varma]: And many people support this mission.

01:56:23.240 --> 01:56:27.400
[Amit Varma]: I think it was a very flawed mission because you cannot solve these problems from the top

01:56:27.400 --> 01:56:28.400
[Amit Varma]: down.

01:56:28.400 --> 01:56:30.720
[Amit Varma]: In that one sense, Gandhi and Ambedkar were right.

01:56:30.720 --> 01:56:35.280
[Amit Varma]: In fact, Ambedkar said that the Constitution was just like a top soil and therefore implying

01:56:35.280 --> 01:56:39.440
[Amit Varma]: that it is extremely superficial, that society is not like that.

01:56:39.440 --> 01:56:44.480
[Amit Varma]: And this leads to another problem that the Constitution, while I find that it is not

01:56:44.480 --> 01:56:49.440
[Amit Varma]: liberal enough for me in terms of protecting individual rights and so on, was probably

01:56:49.440 --> 01:56:54.860
[Amit Varma]: way too liberal for the society itself, which isn't illiberal and was imposed on that society.

01:56:54.860 --> 01:56:58.280
[Amit Varma]: And what we are seeing in the current time was actually inevitable.

01:56:58.280 --> 01:57:02.640
[Amit Varma]: It just took a few decades to get here, but society has caught up and everyone who cared

01:57:02.640 --> 01:57:08.960
[Amit Varma]: for those values failed in that essential mission of propagating them through society.

01:57:08.960 --> 01:57:13.480
[Amit Varma]: So that's my kind of long answer, half of what I said about the state and whatever is

01:57:13.480 --> 01:57:15.000
[Amit Varma]: not even relevant to what you asked.

01:57:15.000 --> 01:57:21.120
[Amit Varma]: But the first half of why we are in this state is that it goes down to the design of the

01:57:21.120 --> 01:57:23.560
[Amit Varma]: Indian state at the time of independence.

01:57:23.560 --> 01:57:25.600
[Amit Varma]: And then that percolates through the culture.

01:57:25.600 --> 01:57:29.640
[Amit Varma]: Because then if all the power is concentrated in the state and markets aren't allowed to

01:57:29.640 --> 01:57:35.280
[Amit Varma]: function as they weren't for decades, and in some areas still aren't, like in agriculture,

01:57:35.280 --> 01:57:37.160
[Amit Varma]: then what are you going to do if you want to get ahead?

01:57:37.160 --> 01:57:41.160
[Amit Varma]: You will want to be part of the state, you'll want to be part of the rent-seeking apparatus,

01:57:41.160 --> 01:57:45.720
[Amit Varma]: instead of focusing your energies onto making a profit the good way, which is to make other

01:57:45.720 --> 01:57:47.560
[Amit Varma]: people's lives better off.

01:57:47.560 --> 01:57:51.480
[Amit Varma]: And you know, the dependence on the state grows, the mindset kind of gets worse and

01:57:51.480 --> 01:57:52.480
[Amit Varma]: worse.

01:57:52.480 --> 01:57:54.120
[Guest]: And that's my broad take on it.

01:57:54.120 --> 01:57:55.120
[Guest]: Right.

01:57:55.120 --> 01:58:00.560
[Guest]: So I'll come at it from a slightly different angle, because one thing it doesn't explain

01:58:00.560 --> 01:58:07.840
[Guest]: is that if British state was so extractive, it should have inspired a complete distrust

01:58:07.840 --> 01:58:09.040
[Guest]: of the state, right?

01:58:09.040 --> 01:58:13.960
[Guest]: When we were sort of moving on from that, we should have hated that state so viscerally

01:58:13.960 --> 01:58:17.040
[Guest]: that we would have wanted an anti-state, right?

01:58:17.040 --> 01:58:20.000
[Guest]: Something like what Gandhi was probably advocating.

01:58:20.000 --> 01:58:22.280
[Guest]: But yet, that didn't happen, right?

01:58:22.280 --> 01:58:25.040
[Guest]: So why is that the case?

01:58:25.040 --> 01:58:30.160
[Guest]: And I'm completely speculating here, I have no data on this, but the way I think of this

01:58:30.160 --> 01:58:37.800
[Guest]: is, think of the three institutions, state, market and society, either of all three of

01:58:37.800 --> 01:58:42.960
[Guest]: these can cause some change, bring good things, bring bad things, whatever, all have complementary

01:58:42.960 --> 01:58:46.200
[Guest]: strengths, all have complementary and weaknesses as well.

01:58:46.200 --> 01:58:52.280
[Guest]: So at that point of time, when we are talking about the fact that India is independent and

01:58:52.280 --> 01:58:56.560
[Guest]: all that, at that point of time, markets were discredited.

01:58:56.560 --> 01:59:03.120
[Guest]: Because you had this idea of markets being very closely linked with British colonialism

01:59:03.120 --> 01:59:04.440
[Guest]: and exploitation.

01:59:04.440 --> 01:59:11.320
[Guest]: So the fact that markets can bring things for us, can make our lives better, was completely

01:59:11.320 --> 01:59:14.800
[Guest]: discredited and still continuing to be discredited, right?

01:59:14.800 --> 01:59:17.480
[Guest]: So we still want to overcome some of those things.

01:59:17.480 --> 01:59:22.360
[Guest]: So if you think of these three elements, one element sort of got discredited.

01:59:22.360 --> 01:59:27.080
[Guest]: Now think of the second change maker, which could have probably been the society as well,

01:59:27.080 --> 01:59:28.080
[Guest]: right?

01:59:28.080 --> 01:59:31.760
[Guest]: And the Indian society has always been, the communities have been strong, right?

01:59:31.760 --> 01:59:33.360
[Guest]: The ties have been strong.

01:59:33.360 --> 01:59:39.400
[Guest]: The state has always played a small role until that point of time, until this welfare state

01:59:39.400 --> 01:59:42.400
[Guest]: becomes a popular ideology across the world.

01:59:42.400 --> 01:59:47.960
[Guest]: But there again, this idea came about of the social revolution, right, and what you already

01:59:47.960 --> 01:59:49.520
[Guest]: mentioned.

01:59:49.520 --> 01:59:54.400
[Guest]: And the social revolution sort of says that the constitution is not just meant to bring

01:59:54.400 --> 01:59:59.600
[Guest]: a political and an economic revolution, it will also transform society, right?

01:59:59.600 --> 02:00:04.400
[Guest]: And that was a very big challenge that the state took on to itself.

02:00:04.400 --> 02:00:08.000
[Guest]: Now, I think that trade-off was very well made.

02:00:08.000 --> 02:00:13.760
[Guest]: And I would disagree with you that that trade-off was not worth it, because we've seen a lot

02:00:13.760 --> 02:00:17.280
[Guest]: of benefits that have happened because of this, right?

02:00:17.280 --> 02:00:23.720
[Guest]: Just this idea of at least this, at that point of time, the caste inequities that were there,

02:00:23.720 --> 02:00:25.200
[Guest]: the gender inequities were there.

02:00:25.200 --> 02:00:29.240
[Guest]: We are definitely way better than we were at that point of time, right?

02:00:29.240 --> 02:00:32.720
[Guest]: And so that trade-off did have a lot of benefits.

02:00:32.720 --> 02:00:41.960
[Guest]: But one sort of unintended effect of that was, yes, that people thought that state is

02:00:41.960 --> 02:00:45.440
[Guest]: the ultimate arbiter of all these things, right?

02:00:45.440 --> 02:00:47.600
[Guest]: Society can never cause this change.

02:00:47.600 --> 02:00:52.000
[Guest]: It is the state whose responsibility is to bring all these changes.

02:00:52.000 --> 02:00:56.640
[Guest]: So, the idea again is, and you will see all this in our popular imagination as well, that

02:00:56.640 --> 02:00:57.640
[Guest]: I pay taxes.

02:00:57.640 --> 02:01:01.000
[Guest]: So, now it's the job of the government to do X, Y, Z, right?

02:01:01.000 --> 02:01:03.040
[Guest]: Why the hell am I paying them taxes?

02:01:03.040 --> 02:01:05.920
[Guest]: But that's not how any society does, right?

02:01:05.920 --> 02:01:09.200
[Guest]: You actually don't want the state to do some of the things.

02:01:09.200 --> 02:01:14.040
[Guest]: And you want probably the markets or societies to resolve some things on themselves.

02:01:14.040 --> 02:01:19.480
[Guest]: So, I think that's sort of the way I look at it, that because of one, markets getting

02:01:19.480 --> 02:01:24.760
[Guest]: discredited and second, the idea of social revolution, meaning that state should solve

02:01:24.760 --> 02:01:29.320
[Guest]: things and society can't, we are left with only one player in the game, and that is the

02:01:29.320 --> 02:01:30.440
[Guest]: state.

02:01:30.440 --> 02:01:35.400
[Guest]: And one direct consequence of this is what you said, and I call it the omni-absent state,

02:01:35.400 --> 02:01:36.400
[Guest]: right?

02:01:36.400 --> 02:01:41.160
[Guest]: So, the idea is that it is present where you don't want it to be and absent where absolutely

02:01:41.160 --> 02:01:42.160
[Guest]: you want it to be.

02:01:42.160 --> 02:01:46.880
[Guest]: So, there's a paradox which comes because of this, there's a paradox between ambition

02:01:46.880 --> 02:01:48.240
[Guest]: and competence, right?

02:01:48.240 --> 02:01:53.640
[Guest]: So, ambition of the state is to move the world, change the world, but it does not have competence

02:01:53.640 --> 02:01:55.520
[Guest]: on many of these grounds, right?

02:01:55.520 --> 02:01:59.240
[Guest]: And in fact, competence of the state has reduced over time, right?

02:01:59.240 --> 02:02:01.840
[Guest]: Remember, earlier there were Navaratnas, right?

02:02:01.840 --> 02:02:04.600
[Guest]: The best in the world wanted to be in the state.

02:02:04.600 --> 02:02:11.080
[Guest]: Even after independence, when the state was the only player in the town, the best people

02:02:11.080 --> 02:02:12.240
[Guest]: would go to the state.

02:02:12.240 --> 02:02:19.040
[Guest]: But as economy liberalized, people had better options, so the competency of the state decreased.

02:02:19.040 --> 02:02:24.280
[Guest]: So paradoxically, with economic growth, you had this governance gap increasing, right?

02:02:24.280 --> 02:02:29.880
[Guest]: So you had people, the government still being in 19th century and society and markets moving

02:02:29.880 --> 02:02:31.640
[Guest]: to the 21st century.

02:02:31.640 --> 02:02:38.720
[Guest]: So, you have a state which has very little competence, but you also have a state which

02:02:38.720 --> 02:02:43.800
[Guest]: has ambition to do a lot of things and that ambition has popular legitimacy.

02:02:43.800 --> 02:02:50.160
[Guest]: Lot of us think that the state should do this, markets are not good, society is not good

02:02:50.160 --> 02:02:56.440
[Guest]: and that is, I think, the reason why we perceive the state the way we do.

02:02:56.440 --> 02:02:58.200
[Amit Varma]: So a couple of observations.

02:02:58.200 --> 02:03:02.760
[Amit Varma]: One is, I love that phrase, the omni-absent state and I completely agree with you on the

02:03:02.760 --> 02:03:06.480
[Amit Varma]: Indian state being absent everywhere where it should be present and vice versa.

02:03:06.480 --> 02:03:12.040
[Amit Varma]: What I'd say, what I've seen over the last few decades is that Indian society has by

02:03:12.040 --> 02:03:15.120
[Amit Varma]: and large in a Jugaadu way solved its own problems.

02:03:15.120 --> 02:03:19.560
[Amit Varma]: So most of the progress that has actually happened within society is society just solving

02:03:19.560 --> 02:03:22.080
[Amit Varma]: its own problems despite of the state.

02:03:22.080 --> 02:03:25.600
[Amit Varma]: The fact is, there is no rule of law in most of the country, there's an illusion of it.

02:03:25.600 --> 02:03:29.920
[Amit Varma]: You have police stations and policemen in uniforms, but there is no rule of law, but

02:03:29.920 --> 02:03:31.840
[Amit Varma]: society has kind of gotten along.

02:03:31.840 --> 02:03:36.080
[Amit Varma]: Similarly, I'd say that whatever little progress and I would say it's too little, whatever

02:03:36.080 --> 02:03:40.360
[Amit Varma]: little progress we've made on issues like gender and caste has again come from within

02:03:40.360 --> 02:03:41.360
[Amit Varma]: society.

02:03:41.360 --> 02:03:45.560
[Amit Varma]: I think the job of the state really was to protect the rights of every individual regardless

02:03:45.560 --> 02:03:49.960
[Amit Varma]: of gender and caste, and it has firstly not managed to do that at all.

02:03:49.960 --> 02:03:53.160
[Amit Varma]: Secondly, there is a lot of progress yet to be made.

02:03:53.160 --> 02:03:58.600
[Amit Varma]: Thirdly, you know, one could argue that the way the state approached it has actually solidified

02:03:58.600 --> 02:04:04.320
[Amit Varma]: a lot of the toxic identity politics that goes on across the country and that Indian

02:04:04.320 --> 02:04:08.200
[Amit Varma]: politics has been plagued with, you know, and in a sense, of course, a lot of those

02:04:08.200 --> 02:04:13.440
[Amit Varma]: identities have started getting subsumed within the larger identity of Hindutva that the BJP

02:04:13.440 --> 02:04:14.480
[Amit Varma]: are building up.

02:04:14.480 --> 02:04:20.440
[Amit Varma]: But even there, all the considerations of, say, Amit Shah while planning the 2014 elections

02:04:20.440 --> 02:04:24.240
[Amit Varma]: were on the basis of caste, where he said that, okay, you know, people say we won't

02:04:24.240 --> 02:04:27.960
[Amit Varma]: get the OBC vote in UP, but actually it's the Yadavs we won't get.

02:04:27.960 --> 02:04:31.440
[Amit Varma]: We'll go after the non-Yadav OBCs who resent the Yadavs.

02:04:31.440 --> 02:04:35.740
[Amit Varma]: We'll go after the non-Jatav Dalits who resent the Jatavs.

02:04:35.740 --> 02:04:40.800
[Amit Varma]: In Maharashtra, the non-Maratha OBCs very much premised on caste.

02:04:40.800 --> 02:04:44.760
[Amit Varma]: And I would argue that a lot of those problems we haven't solved and to the extent that it

02:04:44.760 --> 02:04:51.560
[Amit Varma]: is better, it is really better because of social attitudes and tendencies like urbanization,

02:04:51.560 --> 02:04:54.920
[Amit Varma]: which is not to say that caste is not a problem in the cities, it's a problem everywhere in

02:04:54.920 --> 02:04:59.040
[Amit Varma]: India, but it's less in the cities because wider economic networks and self-interest

02:04:59.040 --> 02:05:01.080
[Amit Varma]: and all those things come into play.

02:05:01.080 --> 02:05:03.320
[Amit Varma]: Nothing to sort of do with the state.

02:05:03.320 --> 02:05:07.320
[Amit Varma]: Now, before we kind of move on, and I, by the way, did some interesting episodes with

02:05:07.320 --> 02:05:12.400
[Amit Varma]: Ashwin Mahesh also, and I think in the first of them, he spoke about how the problem in

02:05:12.400 --> 02:05:16.280
[Amit Varma]: the early decades of India was that the balance between the state and society was too much

02:05:16.280 --> 02:05:20.400
[Amit Varma]: on the side of the state and we needed to bring it more to the social side.

02:05:20.400 --> 02:05:27.100
[Amit Varma]: But I'm at a definitional level going to argue with the conventional view that, you know,

02:05:27.100 --> 02:05:31.280
[Amit Varma]: you have stated, Agoram Rajan has stated, of there being these three prongs, which are

02:05:31.280 --> 02:05:33.920
[Amit Varma]: the state, society and markets.

02:05:33.920 --> 02:05:39.140
[Amit Varma]: And to me, if we look at markets as a marketplaces where goods and services are exchanged, yeah,

02:05:39.140 --> 02:05:41.080
[Amit Varma]: you can look at it as something separate.

02:05:41.080 --> 02:05:46.680
[Amit Varma]: But I think of markets really as a web of voluntary action, you know, involving members

02:05:46.680 --> 02:05:51.960
[Amit Varma]: of society, and therefore a mechanism through which society expresses itself.

02:05:51.960 --> 02:05:56.440
[Amit Varma]: And often the state tries to control this mechanism to subvert this mechanism to use

02:05:56.440 --> 02:06:00.140
[Amit Varma]: its power to, you know, do cronyism and all of that.

02:06:00.140 --> 02:06:04.280
[Amit Varma]: But I look at it as a sort of this web of voluntary action.

02:06:04.280 --> 02:06:08.480
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, I would say that even you and I, right, no money has exchanged hands between

02:06:08.480 --> 02:06:13.320
[Amit Varma]: you and I being on this podcast together now, but we are doing it for mutual benefit of

02:06:13.320 --> 02:06:18.120
[Amit Varma]: different kinds of goodwill between us and you know, I'm sure we'll both enjoy this conversation

02:06:18.120 --> 02:06:21.140
[Amit Varma]: and blah, blah, blah variety of reasons.

02:06:21.140 --> 02:06:24.840
[Amit Varma]: And I'd view that as a market transaction, even though there's no money shifting hands.

02:06:24.840 --> 02:06:30.560
[Amit Varma]: So in a sense, rather than pigeonhole markets into one particular category, ki marketplace

02:06:30.560 --> 02:06:35.260
[Amit Varma]: mein stall hai, mai paisa dera ho, shawl lera ho, that is a market, no, I think I'd include

02:06:35.260 --> 02:06:39.800
[Amit Varma]: it as one form of voluntary interaction and where it is not voluntary, I wouldn't call

02:06:39.800 --> 02:06:44.040
[Amit Varma]: it a market in sort of the true sense, therefore.

02:06:44.040 --> 02:06:48.760
[Amit Varma]: So clearly, you don't agree and you think that it's a separate prong, which is a conventional

02:06:48.760 --> 02:06:49.760
[Amit Varma]: view.

02:06:49.760 --> 02:06:53.480
[Amit Varma]: So I realized that I'm saying something that might seem that is a very different way of

02:06:53.480 --> 02:06:54.480
[Amit Varma]: looking at things.

02:06:54.480 --> 02:06:56.160
[Amit Varma]: So what's kind of your response?

02:06:56.160 --> 02:07:02.320
[Guest]: Yeah, a couple of things, one, for example, and I've heard your episodes before where

02:07:02.320 --> 02:07:09.160
[Guest]: you were differentiating with state, the defining criteria of state being that it is a coercive

02:07:09.160 --> 02:07:10.160
[Guest]: entity, right?

02:07:10.160 --> 02:07:16.080
[Guest]: And the markets aren't, but look at it from another way that state alone isn't coercive,

02:07:16.080 --> 02:07:21.300
[Guest]: you know, like, for example, societies can also be coercive, you know, and markets probably

02:07:21.300 --> 02:07:24.120
[Guest]: aren't if they are working in a voluntary manner.

02:07:24.120 --> 02:07:25.120
[Guest]: So for example,

02:07:25.120 --> 02:07:29.640
[Amit Varma]: No, to clarify that, I think what I would have meant is that the state has a monopoly

02:07:29.640 --> 02:07:30.640
[Amit Varma]: on violence.

02:07:30.640 --> 02:07:35.040
[Amit Varma]: Now, other people can be violent, but I'm only willing to accept that the coercion of

02:07:35.040 --> 02:07:37.080
[Amit Varma]: the state is justified.

02:07:37.080 --> 02:07:42.480
[Amit Varma]: Because you know, that's a liberal paradox that to protect our rights, you need the state

02:07:42.480 --> 02:07:45.880
[Amit Varma]: to exist and the existence of the state means some rights are gone.

02:07:45.880 --> 02:07:50.200
[Amit Varma]: But in general, I would say that coercion everywhere else, whether in markets or society,

02:07:50.200 --> 02:07:54.000
[Amit Varma]: coercion is bad period, you know, and even within the state, I would say you need to

02:07:54.000 --> 02:07:58.640
[Amit Varma]: accept that coercion is bad, but you need to accept that some coercion is necessary,

02:07:58.640 --> 02:08:02.680
[Amit Varma]: because you need some coercion for there to be policemen and for there to be the rule

02:08:02.680 --> 02:08:03.680
[Guest]: of law and so on.

02:08:03.680 --> 02:08:04.680
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:08:04.680 --> 02:08:06.280
[Guest]: So here we enter a paradox, right?

02:08:06.280 --> 02:08:10.640
[Guest]: Like you were mentioning in the beginning that society should have sorted out things

02:08:10.640 --> 02:08:14.400
[Guest]: for itself, and the state shouldn't get into a lot of things.

02:08:14.400 --> 02:08:17.280
[Guest]: But how does society sort out things?

02:08:17.280 --> 02:08:21.640
[Guest]: Society will use coercion as one of the instruments, right?

02:08:21.640 --> 02:08:22.720
[Guest]: And that will be there.

02:08:22.720 --> 02:08:27.400
[Guest]: It might actually be beneficial also in some way, you know, maybe it will align people's

02:08:27.400 --> 02:08:31.360
[Guest]: interests to a particular goal, otherwise, everyone will be dispersed, etc.

02:08:31.360 --> 02:08:37.960
[Guest]: So I think there is, even if society would be the way you wanted it, it would have used

02:08:37.960 --> 02:08:43.800
[Guest]: coercion as one of the means, probably for good benefits, mostly for outcomes that we

02:08:43.800 --> 02:08:47.080
[Guest]: don't want, but there will be this element which exists.

02:08:47.080 --> 02:08:49.120
[Guest]: So that is sort of my one point.

02:08:49.120 --> 02:08:56.200
[Guest]: The second point, I think there is an alternative criteria to look at it, just because thinking

02:08:56.200 --> 02:09:00.640
[Guest]: in terms of what are states, markets, society good at, and there is a difference in all

02:09:00.640 --> 02:09:02.920
[Guest]: three, as I see it, you know.

02:09:02.920 --> 02:09:07.840
[Guest]: So if you look at, place individual at the center, and you look at these three ends of

02:09:07.840 --> 02:09:12.120
[Guest]: a triangle, what does the state provide to the individual?

02:09:12.120 --> 02:09:17.520
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, human rights, which you said, human rights can't exist without a state,

02:09:17.520 --> 02:09:18.520
[Guest]: right?

02:09:18.520 --> 02:09:19.520
[Guest]: Right?

02:09:19.520 --> 02:09:21.160
[Guest]: Yeah, we have human rights, but who will enforce them?

02:09:21.160 --> 02:09:23.840
[Guest]: In the state of nature, what are our human rights, right?

02:09:23.840 --> 02:09:28.640
[Guest]: So you need a state which enforces the human rights that I have, right?

02:09:28.640 --> 02:09:33.840
[Guest]: So that is the goal of the state, to provide security, justice, etc., right?

02:09:33.840 --> 02:09:39.560
[Guest]: The market to the individual will provide an outlet for creativity, and the most important

02:09:39.560 --> 02:09:40.720
[Guest]: thing choice, right?

02:09:40.720 --> 02:09:43.840
[Guest]: That is really fundamental, and that is what it provides.

02:09:43.840 --> 02:09:49.640
[Guest]: And there is one more thing that you would need, right, like we've discussed about how

02:09:49.640 --> 02:09:55.440
[Guest]: individuals are essentially tribal by nature, for good, bad reasons, both, right?

02:09:55.440 --> 02:09:58.200
[Guest]: But that is the way we are constructed.

02:09:58.200 --> 02:10:03.800
[Guest]: So in a sense, we need this third element, which provides a sense of identity, values,

02:10:03.800 --> 02:10:05.440
[Guest]: norms, etc., right?

02:10:05.440 --> 02:10:10.320
[Guest]: And that, I think, is what the third element provides, which is society, okay?

02:10:10.320 --> 02:10:15.200
[Guest]: Now, you can think of markets and societies on a continuum, and I agree, you know, most

02:10:15.200 --> 02:10:21.520
[Guest]: people who say markets and society is different, they also agree that it is on a continuum.

02:10:21.520 --> 02:10:24.440
[Guest]: But the way this operates is different, right?

02:10:24.440 --> 02:10:30.080
[Guest]: In markets, you benefit precisely because you are in a web of these relationships, and

02:10:30.080 --> 02:10:35.080
[Guest]: you don't care about knowing who has supplied this microphone to you, right?

02:10:35.080 --> 02:10:40.320
[Guest]: We all benefit because there's a web of sort of transactions which are formed, and all

02:10:40.320 --> 02:10:41.320
[Guest]: of us benefit.

02:10:41.320 --> 02:10:42.320
[Guest]: So that's great.

02:10:42.320 --> 02:10:47.160
[Guest]: You don't get any sense of belonging, identity, with that person who's selling this to you,

02:10:47.160 --> 02:10:48.160
[Guest]: right?

02:10:48.160 --> 02:10:50.400
[Guest]: You only know that yes, all of us gain with it.

02:10:50.400 --> 02:10:57.800
[Guest]: But when you look at the society, probably it is at the other end of the spectrum, where

02:10:57.800 --> 02:11:02.960
[Guest]: you have this sense, you build a relationship with people, you try to think of what are

02:11:02.960 --> 02:11:07.520
[Guest]: the values that are there, what are the norms that are there, and things like that, right?

02:11:07.520 --> 02:11:13.440
[Guest]: So those are at the other end of the same continuum of market and society.

02:11:13.440 --> 02:11:19.080
[Guest]: So I would say that there is a difference between market and society in this way.

02:11:19.080 --> 02:11:22.960
[Guest]: One more thing, I talked about how functionally they are different.

02:11:22.960 --> 02:11:27.640
[Guest]: Even the way they fail and they succeed are different, you know, markets, societies and

02:11:27.640 --> 02:11:28.880
[Guest]: societies, right?

02:11:28.880 --> 02:11:33.680
[Guest]: So for example, when we talk about market failures, what is a market failure?

02:11:33.680 --> 02:11:39.160
[Guest]: Essentially, we are saying when an efficient allocation of scarce resource doesn't happen,

02:11:39.160 --> 02:11:41.240
[Guest]: that's when you say markets have failed, right?

02:11:41.240 --> 02:11:44.000
[Guest]: So that is an example of a market failure.

02:11:44.000 --> 02:11:46.580
[Guest]: Similarly, you know what government failure is.

02:11:46.580 --> 02:11:50.480
[Guest]: But where would you put, for example, caste discrimination, right?

02:11:50.480 --> 02:11:55.080
[Guest]: It's probably not so much the mistake of the government also, they have tried various things

02:11:55.080 --> 02:11:59.720
[Guest]: that they could, not a market failure also, but I think it's a social failure, right?

02:11:59.720 --> 02:12:06.760
[Guest]: Like, we as a society itself have not been able to overcome it the way we would have

02:12:06.760 --> 02:12:12.840
[Guest]: wanted to, you know, similarly, religious majoritarianism, is it a market failure?

02:12:12.840 --> 02:12:14.920
[Guest]: Is it a government failure?

02:12:14.920 --> 02:12:21.480
[Guest]: Probably I would say it's a third category, the way our values, norms have emerged, have

02:12:21.480 --> 02:12:23.120
[Guest]: led us on this path, you know.

02:12:23.120 --> 02:12:28.960
[Guest]: So that's why I would classify it as a third kind of category, which is society.

02:12:28.960 --> 02:12:31.520
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, very wise words.

02:12:31.520 --> 02:12:35.280
[Amit Varma]: And I guess one way, and I'm just thinking a lot of thinking about this is of society

02:12:35.280 --> 02:12:36.640
[Amit Varma]: as a kind of superstructure.

02:12:36.640 --> 02:12:41.880
[Amit Varma]: And you have these webs of voluntary actions and a certain class of those form markets.

02:12:41.880 --> 02:12:46.000
[Amit Varma]: But you also need order in the society for which at some point, you need a state and

02:12:46.000 --> 02:12:48.280
[Amit Varma]: then a state emerges and that is a state.

02:12:48.280 --> 02:12:52.400
[Amit Varma]: And of course, then the state just takes over and power corrupts and all of that and the

02:12:52.400 --> 02:12:55.600
[Amit Varma]: state starts interfering in markets also and all of that happens.

02:12:55.600 --> 02:12:59.960
[Amit Varma]: And the term you've used for society kind of solving its own problems is societism.

02:12:59.960 --> 02:13:04.960
[Amit Varma]: So I want to sort of look at this in a couple of contexts, which you know, you've also spoken

02:13:04.960 --> 02:13:08.640
[Amit Varma]: about you gave a great talk at Manthan, which is run by my friend Ajay Gandhi.

02:13:08.640 --> 02:13:10.960
[Amit Varma]: So I linked to that as well on YouTube.

02:13:10.960 --> 02:13:14.920
[Amit Varma]: And let's look at a couple of these contexts, the context which you bring up, for example,

02:13:14.920 --> 02:13:20.220
[Amit Varma]: is that smaller languages are dying out, because everybody for rational reasons is drawn to

02:13:20.220 --> 02:13:23.800
[Amit Varma]: bigger languages like English or like Hindi or whatever.

02:13:23.800 --> 02:13:25.840
[Amit Varma]: And that's hurting language diversity.

02:13:25.840 --> 02:13:30.680
[Amit Varma]: You know, last week, I did an episode with Peggy Mohan on language is fantastic episode.

02:13:30.680 --> 02:13:34.240
[Amit Varma]: And I mean, in the sense that I'm not praising my own show, I'm just saying that she's written

02:13:34.240 --> 02:13:36.800
[Amit Varma]: an incredible book and was so insightful.

02:13:36.800 --> 02:13:38.560
[Amit Varma]: And she points to this also.

02:13:38.560 --> 02:13:42.660
[Amit Varma]: And I brought up the question of, say, the cavendish banana, which the great food writer

02:13:42.660 --> 02:13:44.960
[Amit Varma]: Vikram doctor had once told me about that.

02:13:44.960 --> 02:13:47.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, which just held it up.

02:13:47.240 --> 02:13:48.520
[Amit Varma]: I'll take a screenshot.

02:13:48.520 --> 02:13:50.280
[Amit Varma]: Hold it up again.

02:13:50.280 --> 02:13:52.280
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, so screenshot of Cavendish banana.

02:13:52.280 --> 02:13:56.080
[Amit Varma]: And the thing with the Cavendish banana is that I think we exported it to begin with.

02:13:56.080 --> 02:13:57.680
[Amit Varma]: And then it became popular in America.

02:13:57.680 --> 02:14:01.560
[Amit Varma]: And then economies of scale happened and it became the dominant banana as it were.

02:14:01.560 --> 02:14:06.500
[Amit Varma]: And then it came back to India and the economies of scale continued along with something Peggy

02:14:06.500 --> 02:14:09.300
[Amit Varma]: pointed out that it lasts better than other bananas.

02:14:09.300 --> 02:14:13.160
[Amit Varma]: And now all our hundreds of varieties of indigenous bananas are dying out.

02:14:13.160 --> 02:14:18.940
[Amit Varma]: And Cavendish is taking over because everybody is making voluntary and rational choices.

02:14:18.940 --> 02:14:19.940
[Amit Varma]: One example.

02:14:19.940 --> 02:14:22.160
[Amit Varma]: Now, we can all agree diversity is good.

02:14:22.160 --> 02:14:26.120
[Amit Varma]: But as an individual, you know, you just went out and bought the Cavendish banana and we

02:14:26.120 --> 02:14:27.320
[Amit Varma]: are both speaking in English.

02:14:27.320 --> 02:14:28.320
[Amit Varma]: So what are we talking about?

02:14:28.320 --> 02:14:30.040
[Amit Varma]: And you know, how do we solve this?

02:14:30.040 --> 02:14:34.760
[Amit Varma]: A similar problem is big tech, like I constantly feel that when we talk about the polarization

02:14:34.760 --> 02:14:38.920
[Amit Varma]: that happens online, and so on and so forth, I think it is horrible.

02:14:38.920 --> 02:14:43.020
[Amit Varma]: So much of social media is just made our discourse toxic, but I don't want the state to step

02:14:43.020 --> 02:14:46.920
[Amit Varma]: in because of the state steps in and hey, power corrupts, depending on the person who

02:14:46.920 --> 02:14:47.920
[Amit Varma]: is in charge.

02:14:47.920 --> 02:14:51.400
[Amit Varma]: It'll just lead to free speech dying, dissent dying, I don't want the state to have too

02:14:51.400 --> 02:14:52.400
[Amit Varma]: much power here.

02:14:52.400 --> 02:14:54.480
[Amit Varma]: I've always said it's a social problem.

02:14:54.480 --> 02:14:56.920
[Amit Varma]: We got to figure out how to sort it out.

02:14:56.920 --> 02:15:02.720
[Amit Varma]: Other problems that you point out is the context of for example, ghettoization in cities, where

02:15:02.720 --> 02:15:06.680
[Amit Varma]: Hindu landlords will say we won't give our apartments on rent to meat eaters and therefore

02:15:06.680 --> 02:15:08.600
[Amit Varma]: Muslims and whatever.

02:15:08.600 --> 02:15:13.840
[Amit Varma]: Similarly, from the rational choices of individuals, which as individuals, they have a right to

02:15:13.840 --> 02:15:17.880
[Amit Varma]: make you have this ghettoization where Muslims live in certain areas, Hindus live in other

02:15:17.880 --> 02:15:20.880
[Amit Varma]: areas, and the social outcome is terrible.

02:15:20.880 --> 02:15:24.160
[Amit Varma]: But at an individual level, everyone is making a choice that they have a right to make.

02:15:24.160 --> 02:15:28.080
[Amit Varma]: I mean, if you know, somebody says it's my house, I'll give it to whoever I want.

02:15:28.080 --> 02:15:29.080
[Amit Varma]: That's fair enough.

02:15:29.080 --> 02:15:31.400
[Amit Varma]: You want to protect his individual rights also, but what do you do about the larger

02:15:31.400 --> 02:15:32.400
[Amit Varma]: social problem?

02:15:32.400 --> 02:15:36.560
[Amit Varma]: Now, the way I think about all these social problems is that hey, these are problems that

02:15:36.560 --> 02:15:39.960
[Amit Varma]: society has to solve, the state cannot solve everything.

02:15:39.960 --> 02:15:44.280
[Amit Varma]: The state can step in when individual rights are abrogated.

02:15:44.280 --> 02:15:47.600
[Amit Varma]: So when there is something like Sati and a woman is being killed, the state has to step

02:15:47.600 --> 02:15:48.600
[Amit Varma]: in.

02:15:48.600 --> 02:15:49.840
[Amit Varma]: You know, that's the job of the state.

02:15:49.840 --> 02:15:54.240
[Amit Varma]: When you know, people are enslaved in different ways or a Khab panchayat says that honor killing

02:15:54.240 --> 02:15:58.280
[Amit Varma]: karo, the state has to step in because individual rights are hurt by that.

02:15:58.280 --> 02:16:03.600
[Amit Varma]: But in all of these cases, that a kid says that I don't want my child to learn Awadhi,

02:16:03.600 --> 02:16:04.640
[Amit Varma]: which is what I speak.

02:16:04.640 --> 02:16:07.800
[Amit Varma]: I want my child to get ahead in the world and there's an opportunity cost for learning

02:16:07.800 --> 02:16:10.720
[Amit Varma]: Awadhi, which is that they won't know English and Hindi so well.

02:16:10.720 --> 02:16:12.680
[Amit Varma]: So I want them to get ahead in the world.

02:16:12.680 --> 02:16:13.840
[Amit Varma]: And this is a rational choice.

02:16:13.840 --> 02:16:15.480
[Amit Varma]: You can't argue with this.

02:16:15.480 --> 02:16:20.320
[Amit Varma]: So through the frame of societism, what insight can you give on these problems?

02:16:20.320 --> 02:16:28.280
[Guest]: Yeah, I think my priors are similar to yours, Amit that I would say, because there are opportunity

02:16:28.280 --> 02:16:32.880
[Guest]: costs to state action, you would want the state to do things which are in the range

02:16:32.880 --> 02:16:36.440
[Guest]: of market failures, address them, and things like that.

02:16:36.440 --> 02:16:41.200
[Guest]: So you wouldn't want the government to do all these things, even though both of us agree

02:16:41.200 --> 02:16:43.760
[Guest]: that they are not desirable, right?

02:16:43.760 --> 02:16:46.000
[Guest]: And they are, they should be overcome.

02:16:46.000 --> 02:16:50.920
[Guest]: But the idea is whose job is it right, the one, the default action, because we discussed

02:16:50.920 --> 02:16:56.200
[Guest]: about our part dependence, we lot of people will say it's the state's job, right?

02:16:56.200 --> 02:17:02.680
[Guest]: And a small minority will say probably, you should solve it by doing probably property

02:17:02.680 --> 02:17:05.400
[Guest]: rights and solving it through markets.

02:17:05.400 --> 02:17:10.440
[Guest]: But the idea is that even I don't think both of them can solve this particular issue.

02:17:10.440 --> 02:17:12.520
[Guest]: And maybe you will need a third element.

02:17:12.520 --> 02:17:17.840
[Guest]: And that's what my essay was about that we often think of society as this patient on

02:17:17.840 --> 02:17:21.480
[Guest]: which two people are operating the state and the market.

02:17:21.480 --> 02:17:25.560
[Guest]: And this society is just lying there being operated on.

02:17:25.560 --> 02:17:30.600
[Guest]: But think of it in another way, society itself is a partner, you know, society can bring

02:17:30.600 --> 02:17:35.240
[Guest]: about a lot of changes, it can self correct, it has self corrected.

02:17:35.240 --> 02:17:41.320
[Guest]: So that's why think of it as all these three being partners and not as one being a patient

02:17:41.320 --> 02:17:43.640
[Guest]: being operated on the other.

02:17:43.640 --> 02:17:46.480
[Guest]: So that's where sort of I begin.

02:17:46.480 --> 02:17:52.400
[Guest]: And I said that, for example, all three have their own comparative strengths and weaknesses.

02:17:52.400 --> 02:17:57.000
[Guest]: And I'll give three examples where societies can actually self correct it.

02:17:57.000 --> 02:17:59.800
[Guest]: And I'll start with Eleanor Ostrom's work, right?

02:17:59.800 --> 02:18:06.280
[Guest]: I mean, governing the commons, very fundamental book that I think a lot of people should read.

02:18:06.280 --> 02:18:11.040
[Guest]: And she addressed the same question, she looked at there was this idea of tragedy of the commons,

02:18:11.040 --> 02:18:12.040
[Guest]: right?

02:18:12.040 --> 02:18:16.280
[Guest]: The idea that common resources will get over exploited.

02:18:16.280 --> 02:18:21.800
[Guest]: And the only way to overcome that is either through state restricting what people have

02:18:21.800 --> 02:18:23.720
[Guest]: access to, or market.

02:18:23.720 --> 02:18:29.720
[Guest]: So basically, you have private property rights being defined, you have fences, you have clear

02:18:29.720 --> 02:18:32.440
[Guest]: demarcation of who owns what and things like that.

02:18:32.440 --> 02:18:35.360
[Guest]: Now, she says there is another way to look at this.

02:18:35.360 --> 02:18:42.520
[Guest]: And they have documented studies of common resources, I think, close to 600, 700 or more

02:18:42.520 --> 02:18:48.760
[Guest]: studies where people manage this, neither by the state solution or by the market solution,

02:18:48.760 --> 02:18:49.760
[Guest]: right?

02:18:49.760 --> 02:18:51.600
[Guest]: And that was where sort of civil societies came in.

02:18:51.600 --> 02:18:58.120
[Guest]: So they found out that one, the context was very important, the solution couldn't be generalized.

02:18:58.120 --> 02:19:03.080
[Guest]: So what worked in one country didn't work in just another part of the country.

02:19:03.080 --> 02:19:06.600
[Guest]: But broadly, they tried to derive some lessons.

02:19:06.600 --> 02:19:11.720
[Guest]: And there were three or four principles that the study concludes, right?

02:19:11.720 --> 02:19:17.920
[Guest]: Whenever there is graduated sanctions, whenever there is a higher level of trust, whenever,

02:19:17.920 --> 02:19:23.600
[Guest]: you know, there was a lot of communication between the entire societal mass, they were

02:19:23.600 --> 02:19:25.600
[Guest]: able to forge out solutions.

02:19:25.600 --> 02:19:29.520
[Guest]: Some of them were coercive, right, the graduated sanctions are coercive.

02:19:29.520 --> 02:19:33.680
[Guest]: And yet, they were able to prevent this so called tragedy of the commons.

02:19:33.680 --> 02:19:37.520
[Guest]: So what it says is there is a third way out.

02:19:37.520 --> 02:19:42.040
[Guest]: In fact, what it says is market failures can be prevented not just by the state, but by

02:19:42.040 --> 02:19:43.040
[Guest]: society as well.

02:19:43.040 --> 02:19:48.200
[Guest]: You know, often, even in the most liberal tradition, we think that government should

02:19:48.200 --> 02:19:51.200
[Guest]: come in when there is a market failure.

02:19:51.200 --> 02:19:57.160
[Guest]: I would say even a more liberal proposition that even when there's a market failure, maybe

02:19:57.160 --> 02:19:59.960
[Guest]: wait, you know, maybe the society can solve it.

02:19:59.960 --> 02:20:05.120
[Guest]: And then even if society can't, then the state should come in, you know, so that is one way

02:20:05.120 --> 02:20:06.120
[Guest]: to think of it.

02:20:06.120 --> 02:20:07.440
[Guest]: So this is one example, right.

02:20:07.440 --> 02:20:12.920
[Guest]: So there are examples of common resources, which can be managed by local communities.

02:20:12.920 --> 02:20:14.680
[Guest]: So a lot of work needs to be done.

02:20:14.680 --> 02:20:15.720
[Guest]: I haven't done it.

02:20:15.720 --> 02:20:20.360
[Guest]: But things like maybe what engenders trust, we need to understand, right?

02:20:20.360 --> 02:20:22.360
[Guest]: What builds social capital?

02:20:22.360 --> 02:20:25.720
[Guest]: What builds bridging capital more than bonding capital, right?

02:20:25.720 --> 02:20:28.600
[Guest]: Those are questions that we need to investigate.

02:20:28.600 --> 02:20:33.480
[Guest]: But we don't because we think society is a useless thing, which has all its problems,

02:20:33.480 --> 02:20:36.880
[Guest]: which the great state or markets can solve.

02:20:36.880 --> 02:20:39.280
[Guest]: That's one kind of thing, right?

02:20:39.280 --> 02:20:41.360
[Guest]: Second one is just philanthropy.

02:20:41.360 --> 02:20:49.440
[Guest]: I would also classify as one way that civil society sort of corrects problems in societies,

02:20:49.440 --> 02:20:50.440
[Guest]: right.

02:20:50.440 --> 02:20:56.040
[Guest]: And I think it is very important in a state like India, for these initiatives, because

02:20:56.040 --> 02:21:01.840
[Guest]: our state for the foreseeable future will never have the resources to do all the things

02:21:01.840 --> 02:21:02.840
[Guest]: that we wanted, right.

02:21:02.840 --> 02:21:08.440
[Guest]: And the example I always talk about is public libraries, for example, we want them, we all

02:21:08.440 --> 02:21:10.860
[Guest]: desire that we should have them.

02:21:10.860 --> 02:21:16.520
[Guest]: But can you think of a state which is having so many challenges, developmental challenges

02:21:16.520 --> 02:21:23.240
[Guest]: to invest in, say, art or culture or libraries the way you want it?

02:21:23.240 --> 02:21:24.640
[Guest]: It won't, right?

02:21:24.640 --> 02:21:29.440
[Guest]: It's, in fact, immoral of us to expect of the state to do it because it needs to do

02:21:29.440 --> 02:21:30.800
[Guest]: more fundamental things.

02:21:30.800 --> 02:21:32.040
[Guest]: So who will solve it, right?

02:21:32.040 --> 02:21:37.960
[Guest]: So maybe I would again look at it as some things that civil society can solve for it.

02:21:37.960 --> 02:21:45.280
[Guest]: But we've again had this major problem where civil society initiatives end up substituting

02:21:45.280 --> 02:21:47.480
[Guest]: the state rather than complementing it, right.

02:21:47.480 --> 02:21:50.800
[Guest]: So the example that I gave is an example of complementing.

02:21:50.800 --> 02:21:55.240
[Guest]: The state does what it can, all the other things maybe the society solves for it.

02:21:55.240 --> 02:22:01.200
[Guest]: But when you have things like corporate social responsibility, or the state saying that,

02:22:01.200 --> 02:22:06.440
[Guest]: you know, you should do the schools because we have problems constructing schools, so

02:22:06.440 --> 02:22:12.840
[Guest]: now you pitch in, right, that's where the state is using coercion to paper over its

02:22:12.840 --> 02:22:14.280
[Guest]: own failures.

02:22:14.280 --> 02:22:19.200
[Guest]: And it is getting the society to do its dirty work, right, the things that it should have

02:22:19.200 --> 02:22:20.200
[Guest]: done it hasn't.

02:22:20.200 --> 02:22:26.360
[Guest]: So it brings in the civil society and channels all its resources to fix the failures of the

02:22:26.360 --> 02:22:27.360
[Guest]: state.

02:22:27.360 --> 02:22:29.920
[Guest]: And that's what I call when I say substituting the state.

02:22:29.920 --> 02:22:30.920
[Guest]: And you don't want it, right?

02:22:30.920 --> 02:22:36.880
[Guest]: So again, you want state to focus on things it does and you get the civil society to pitch

02:22:36.880 --> 02:22:41.520
[Guest]: in in things which the state won't do for a foreseeable future.

02:22:41.520 --> 02:22:44.560
[Guest]: The third example is just about social movements, right?

02:22:44.560 --> 02:22:51.080
[Guest]: We have seen how civil society initiatives by individuals, by communities have made the

02:22:51.080 --> 02:22:52.280
[Guest]: world better off, right?

02:22:52.280 --> 02:22:59.800
[Guest]: So we know of examples where people come together to solve problems for themselves.

02:22:59.800 --> 02:23:03.200
[Guest]: So I mean, there are many examples won't go into great detail.

02:23:03.200 --> 02:23:09.080
[Guest]: But these are just three illustrative cases where we can see civil society coming together

02:23:09.080 --> 02:23:15.320
[Guest]: to solve its own problems and that's why I say that we need to investigate why this happens,

02:23:15.320 --> 02:23:17.120
[Guest]: in which conditions this happens.

02:23:17.120 --> 02:23:22.240
[Guest]: Can we do something so that social capital is built instead of thinking only in state

02:23:22.240 --> 02:23:24.040
[Guest]: and market dichotomy?

02:23:24.040 --> 02:23:29.520
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, four points I want to make here as you see while you're speaking because I don't

02:23:29.520 --> 02:23:31.320
[Amit Varma]: like to interrupt, I take copious notes.

02:23:31.320 --> 02:23:35.840
[Amit Varma]: So therefore four points I cannot come up with one is just for my listeners that people

02:23:35.840 --> 02:23:37.680
[Amit Varma]: keep saying market failure, market failure.

02:23:37.680 --> 02:23:41.760
[Amit Varma]: The first thing that you know, reading public choice theory teaches you and I had an episode

02:23:41.760 --> 02:23:45.920
[Amit Varma]: on that where I was in fact, interviewed by a former colleague, Pawan Srinath on public

02:23:45.920 --> 02:23:46.920
[Amit Varma]: choice theory.

02:23:46.920 --> 02:23:48.000
[Amit Varma]: I'll link that from the show notes.

02:23:48.000 --> 02:23:50.960
[Amit Varma]: And the first thing it teaches you is that government failure is ubiquitous, nobody talks

02:23:50.960 --> 02:23:51.960
[Amit Varma]: about it.

02:23:51.960 --> 02:23:56.640
[Amit Varma]: Everybody says that, oh, there has been that market failure, which is an outlier to begin

02:23:56.640 --> 02:23:57.640
[Amit Varma]: with.

02:23:57.640 --> 02:24:01.240
[Amit Varma]: And then they'll say government will step in and they're comparing the ideal government

02:24:01.240 --> 02:24:06.200
[Amit Varma]: action with the actual thing that went wrong in the outlier example from the marketplace.

02:24:06.200 --> 02:24:10.360
[Amit Varma]: Well, actually, you should compare actual versus actual and government failure is ubiquitous

02:24:10.360 --> 02:24:14.280
[Amit Varma]: because the incentives are wrong, because you're spending somebody else's money on somebody

02:24:14.280 --> 02:24:15.280
[Amit Varma]: else.

02:24:15.280 --> 02:24:19.520
[Amit Varma]: Unlike in a marketplace, where you are driven by better incentives, and despite that market

02:24:19.520 --> 02:24:24.440
[Amit Varma]: failures may happen, but we have to sort of think about it in this context as well.

02:24:24.440 --> 02:24:30.080
[Guest]: My second point is that if I just wanted to add to this, in fact, when we teach this failures,

02:24:30.080 --> 02:24:32.800
[Guest]: we teach three types of failures, not even two.

02:24:32.800 --> 02:24:36.320
[Guest]: So just like how markets can fail, governments can fail.

02:24:36.320 --> 02:24:41.280
[Guest]: And we give a lot of examples for that in ways in which governments can fail, right?

02:24:41.280 --> 02:24:47.040
[Guest]: So a lot of rent seeking, rent capture, all those are examples of government failures,

02:24:47.040 --> 02:24:48.040
[Guest]: we know that.

02:24:48.040 --> 02:24:50.160
[Guest]: And the third failure is social failures.

02:24:50.160 --> 02:24:54.360
[Guest]: And that's where I told you about, you know, just the fact that if you have a society where

02:24:54.360 --> 02:25:01.900
[Guest]: there is much of bonding capital and no bridging capital is an example where society has failed.

02:25:01.900 --> 02:25:07.160
[Guest]: So there are three failures, you know, it's not just that markets fail, we think of markets

02:25:07.160 --> 02:25:11.360
[Guest]: failing and then that's why government should pitch in, but all three can fail.

02:25:11.360 --> 02:25:14.880
[Amit Varma]: All three can fail and all three can fail together in India as sometimes happens.

02:25:14.880 --> 02:25:19.240
[Amit Varma]: The second point I wanted to make was about what you say about, you know, social actions,

02:25:19.240 --> 02:25:21.320
[Amit Varma]: you know, complementing state action.

02:25:21.320 --> 02:25:24.960
[Amit Varma]: That's something that Ashwin Mahesh has spoken about at length with all the episodes I've

02:25:24.960 --> 02:25:25.960
[Amit Varma]: done with him.

02:25:25.960 --> 02:25:31.040
[Amit Varma]: So I'll link them because he is someone who is in many ways a sort of a social reformer

02:25:31.040 --> 02:25:35.720
[Amit Varma]: in terms of just doing so much work to work with government and saying that, hey, you

02:25:35.720 --> 02:25:39.160
[Amit Varma]: just can't leave everything to the state and rant against the state on Twitter, you've

02:25:39.160 --> 02:25:44.240
[Amit Varma]: got to also move your own butt and as a citizen, work with the state to make things happen.

02:25:44.240 --> 02:25:46.720
[Amit Varma]: And I've had arguments with that as well.

02:25:46.720 --> 02:25:48.320
[Amit Varma]: But those are fascinating episodes.

02:25:48.320 --> 02:25:50.080
[Amit Varma]: And he's got a very interesting point of view.

02:25:50.080 --> 02:25:51.820
[Amit Varma]: So do listen to those.

02:25:51.820 --> 02:25:56.960
[Amit Varma]: My third point was about, you know, what you pointed out that sometimes, you know, like

02:25:56.960 --> 02:25:58.840
[Amit Varma]: CSR, the state will say, okay, I failed.

02:25:58.840 --> 02:26:00.560
[Amit Varma]: So you do it, they'll put the onus on the state.

02:26:00.560 --> 02:26:03.880
[Amit Varma]: There's something worse than that, which is where the state will say, okay, I'm failing,

02:26:03.880 --> 02:26:04.880
[Amit Varma]: but you can't try.

02:26:04.880 --> 02:26:05.880
[Amit Varma]: I won't let you try.

02:26:05.880 --> 02:26:10.080
[Amit Varma]: And a classic example of this is education, where, you know, running a for profit school

02:26:10.080 --> 02:26:13.480
[Amit Varma]: in India is illegal, it has been illegal for decades.

02:26:13.480 --> 02:26:16.880
[Amit Varma]: And you know, there have been studies over the last couple of decades, which have shown

02:26:16.880 --> 02:26:21.320
[Amit Varma]: that the poorest of poor parents would rather send their kid to a budget private school,

02:26:21.320 --> 02:26:25.160
[Amit Varma]: which is a really low cost private school, rather than a free government school, because

02:26:25.160 --> 02:26:27.700
[Amit Varma]: of free government schools are just so bad.

02:26:27.700 --> 02:26:31.700
[Amit Varma]: And no one is saying shut down government schools or the government shouldn't do education,

02:26:31.700 --> 02:26:35.960
[Amit Varma]: but it doesn't even want choice to be available to parents so that they can choose.

02:26:35.960 --> 02:26:40.360
[Amit Varma]: And in this way, they're not only not solving a problem of education, they're not even letting

02:26:40.360 --> 02:26:43.960
[Amit Varma]: society solve it, you know, and it's not an either or it's not that the government should

02:26:43.960 --> 02:26:44.960
[Amit Varma]: stop completely.

02:26:44.960 --> 02:26:49.000
[Amit Varma]: People like me would always say that, you know, education is important, let the government

02:26:49.000 --> 02:26:54.120
[Amit Varma]: do whatever it's doing, but allow private people to actually function, which it doesn't.

02:26:54.120 --> 02:26:57.760
[Amit Varma]: I've had great episodes on this with Amit Chandra and Karthik Muralidharan, I'll link

02:26:57.760 --> 02:26:59.520
[Amit Varma]: those from the show notes as well.

02:26:59.520 --> 02:27:02.840
[Amit Varma]: And this is also true of vaccines, it's a point Ajay Shah made that not only did the

02:27:02.840 --> 02:27:08.320
[Amit Varma]: government not procure any vaccines, it didn't even allow private parties to enter into arrangements

02:27:08.320 --> 02:27:09.320
[Amit Varma]: to do so.

02:27:09.320 --> 02:27:15.240
[Amit Varma]: When Pfizer wanted to enter India in the later months of last year, it told them to get lost,

02:27:15.240 --> 02:27:18.720
[Amit Varma]: you know, and then you have this and that's basically murder.

02:27:18.720 --> 02:27:23.160
[Amit Varma]: At that point in time for the government to tell Pfizer to get lost is equal to murder,

02:27:23.160 --> 02:27:26.800
[Amit Varma]: you know, and again, something we've discussed at length in the episode on vaccination.

02:27:26.800 --> 02:27:30.000
[Amit Varma]: So that's, you know, it's not even that the state doesn't do it, and then it passes that

02:27:30.000 --> 02:27:31.200
[Amit Varma]: responsibility on.

02:27:31.200 --> 02:27:36.040
[Amit Varma]: Sometimes it doesn't do it, and it won't let you do it, which is even worse.

02:27:36.040 --> 02:27:37.880
[Amit Varma]: And what is the fourth point I was going to make?

02:27:37.880 --> 02:27:39.360
[Amit Varma]: Okay, my fourth point is a scribble.

02:27:39.360 --> 02:27:40.680
[Amit Varma]: I can't read my own handwriting.

02:27:40.680 --> 02:27:43.920
[Amit Varma]: If it strikes me later, I'll kind of come back to it.

02:27:43.920 --> 02:27:46.120
[Amit Varma]: But do you want to sort of respond to any of these?

02:27:46.120 --> 02:27:48.120
[Guest]: And then we'll move ahead.

02:27:48.120 --> 02:27:56.880
[Guest]: No, yeah, I agree with your point on just that sometimes the state will even prevent

02:27:56.880 --> 02:28:02.080
[Guest]: a solution from emerging and we've seen many examples of that.

02:28:02.080 --> 02:28:06.480
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, my fourth point is this, my fourth point is saying that society will solve its own

02:28:06.480 --> 02:28:12.440
[Amit Varma]: problems is assuming that it is inevitable that there will be moral progress as we define

02:28:12.440 --> 02:28:16.640
[Amit Varma]: it, right, that there is an arc of history, and it is going towards freedom or justice

02:28:16.640 --> 02:28:20.800
[Amit Varma]: or whatever, and that arc of history makes it inevitable that social action will move

02:28:20.800 --> 02:28:22.320
[Amit Varma]: in that direction.

02:28:22.320 --> 02:28:24.840
[Amit Varma]: But what if that arc of history isn't inevitable?

02:28:24.840 --> 02:28:27.480
[Amit Varma]: And what if social action moves in the other direction?

02:28:27.480 --> 02:28:32.400
[Amit Varma]: So liberals like you and I will say that khap panchayats are a problem, that coercive action

02:28:32.400 --> 02:28:34.920
[Amit Varma]: by them should be banned, and so on and so forth.

02:28:34.920 --> 02:28:39.720
[Amit Varma]: But social action may go in the opposite direction, because you and I are firmly in the minority,

02:28:39.720 --> 02:28:44.840
[Amit Varma]: you know, English speaking elites, influenced by the ideas of the Enlightenment and so on.

02:28:44.840 --> 02:28:49.400
[Amit Varma]: So that's another key problem with societism that you assume that things will move in a

02:28:49.400 --> 02:28:50.400
[Amit Varma]: good direction.

02:28:50.400 --> 02:28:52.520
[Amit Varma]: But what if they don't?

02:28:52.520 --> 02:28:55.800
[Amit Varma]: What if people get lynched because somebody was seen with a cow?

02:28:55.800 --> 02:28:57.440
[Amit Varma]: That is also social action.

02:28:57.440 --> 02:28:58.440
[Amit Varma]: And it's horrendous.

02:28:58.440 --> 02:28:59.440
[Guest]: Absolutely.

02:28:59.440 --> 02:29:02.800
[Guest]: So that's why that is an example of social failures, right?

02:29:02.800 --> 02:29:05.200
[Guest]: That's why all three can fail, right?

02:29:05.200 --> 02:29:09.060
[Guest]: And that's so the idea is you need to guard against that failure.

02:29:09.060 --> 02:29:10.920
[Guest]: And that's really tough challenge, right?

02:29:10.920 --> 02:29:16.360
[Guest]: So you would want society to actually solve some things and again, not be where you don't

02:29:16.360 --> 02:29:17.640
[Guest]: want it to be.

02:29:17.640 --> 02:29:24.000
[Guest]: And that is challenging, and no doubt, but that's why you have a balance, right?

02:29:24.000 --> 02:29:31.440
[Guest]: You would want state to assert itself whenever any human right violation happens, or whenever

02:29:31.440 --> 02:29:34.720
[Guest]: the principles of the republic aren't followed, right?

02:29:34.720 --> 02:29:39.040
[Guest]: And that's why you need a strong state on those counts, you don't want a weak state

02:29:39.040 --> 02:29:40.600
[Guest]: on those counts, right?

02:29:40.600 --> 02:29:44.760
[Guest]: And similarly, you need markets, society will coerce you into saying that you are we all

02:29:44.760 --> 02:29:46.080
[Guest]: should be similar.

02:29:46.080 --> 02:29:50.400
[Guest]: And that's why I don't do something which is different from us.

02:29:50.400 --> 02:29:57.120
[Guest]: But you need market to expressly have choice, you need people to do crazy things and try

02:29:57.120 --> 02:29:59.060
[Guest]: their luck in various things.

02:29:59.060 --> 02:30:05.320
[Guest]: So that's why it is a balance, which I talked about, it's not about one being a problem

02:30:05.320 --> 02:30:09.360
[Guest]: and the other being a solution, all three are problems, all three are solutions.

02:30:09.360 --> 02:30:10.360
[Amit Varma]: Marvelous.

02:30:10.360 --> 02:30:11.840
[Amit Varma]: So let's move on to the questions now.

02:30:11.840 --> 02:30:16.440
[Amit Varma]: And there are some 480 questions on Twitter, well, not so many, but I mean, I haven't counted.

02:30:16.440 --> 02:30:18.120
[Amit Varma]: But we'll go through a few of the questions.

02:30:18.120 --> 02:30:22.640
[Amit Varma]: And then I'll ask you about the course that you guys are doing at Takshashila and why

02:30:22.640 --> 02:30:26.080
[Amit Varma]: everyone should sign up or at least apply for it.

02:30:26.080 --> 02:30:30.080
[Amit Varma]: Because I'm sure you have limited seats which are going fast.

02:30:30.080 --> 02:30:34.000
[Amit Varma]: And the first question I want to ask since we're talking about societism is from Akshay

02:30:34.000 --> 02:30:35.040
[Amit Varma]: Alladi.

02:30:35.040 --> 02:30:37.240
[Amit Varma]: And Akshay has a number of questions.

02:30:37.240 --> 02:30:40.720
[Amit Varma]: But the first of them is how is societism different from conservatism?

02:30:40.720 --> 02:30:46.440
[Guest]: Yeah, I've had debates with Akshay on this.

02:30:46.440 --> 02:30:53.080
[Guest]: Yeah, conservative, again, the idea behind conservatism, as I understand it, would be

02:30:53.080 --> 02:30:58.640
[Guest]: yes, that society can solve some problems on its own, right.

02:30:58.640 --> 02:31:03.920
[Guest]: So in that sense, they are similar, and that sort of maps.

02:31:03.920 --> 02:31:09.840
[Guest]: But when I'm talking about societism, I'm also trying to explore what are the things

02:31:09.840 --> 02:31:15.040
[Guest]: that markets are good at, what are the things governments are good at, and then trying to

02:31:15.040 --> 02:31:16.880
[Guest]: see where that balance rides, right.

02:31:16.880 --> 02:31:23.840
[Guest]: So I'm not saying that society is the only solution or society is a better solution compared

02:31:23.840 --> 02:31:24.840
[Guest]: to the others.

02:31:24.840 --> 02:31:28.600
[Guest]: I'm just trying to look at where are the strengths of each of these.

02:31:28.600 --> 02:31:34.480
[Guest]: So I think that is the nuance, which is slightly different from what conservatism would say,

02:31:34.480 --> 02:31:38.720
[Guest]: right, that yes, society is the leading actor, and it determines.

02:31:38.720 --> 02:31:43.840
[Guest]: So for example, that is why I would still say that the social revolution experiment

02:31:43.840 --> 02:31:46.800
[Guest]: was a one that we should have had.

02:31:46.800 --> 02:31:51.080
[Guest]: Whereas a conservative idea would say, I mean, the state shouldn't have gotten to this and

02:31:51.080 --> 02:31:57.360
[Guest]: society would have solved it for itself, which was, you know, the Gandhian view as well.

02:31:57.360 --> 02:32:03.520
[Guest]: But I would say that it is, you need the state to have said that, you know, some things are

02:32:03.520 --> 02:32:04.520
[Guest]: not right.

02:32:04.520 --> 02:32:07.640
[Guest]: They are violations of human rights and human dignity.

02:32:07.640 --> 02:32:12.320
[Guest]: And that's why we won't allow it, even though there is broad acceptance in every quarter

02:32:12.320 --> 02:32:13.320
[Guest]: of the society, right.

02:32:13.320 --> 02:32:16.440
[Guest]: So that's where I think conservatism and societalism differs.

02:32:16.440 --> 02:32:20.720
[Amit Varma]: Fair enough, I guess, you know, arrive at a similar solution through very different

02:32:20.720 --> 02:32:21.720
[Amit Varma]: frameworks.

02:32:21.720 --> 02:32:23.480
[Amit Varma]: So that's kind of one way of looking at it.

02:32:23.480 --> 02:32:27.400
[Amit Varma]: I had an episode on Indian conservatism, by the way, with Jerry Rao, who had written a

02:32:27.400 --> 02:32:28.400
[Amit Varma]: book on that.

02:32:28.400 --> 02:32:31.000
[Amit Varma]: So people who are interested could look that up.

02:32:31.000 --> 02:32:36.000
[Amit Varma]: Akshay also asks three other questions, but all are to do with foreign policy and defense.

02:32:36.000 --> 02:32:40.280
[Amit Varma]: And by the way, Pranay and I decided we won't talk about foreign policy and defense today,

02:32:40.280 --> 02:32:44.600
[Amit Varma]: even though he's one of our foremost foreign policy experts, simply because we spent a

02:32:44.600 --> 02:32:47.020
[Amit Varma]: whole episode last year talking about that.

02:32:47.020 --> 02:32:48.280
[Amit Varma]: So kindly go and listen to that.

02:32:48.280 --> 02:32:49.760
[Amit Varma]: I'll link it from the show notes.

02:32:49.760 --> 02:32:53.280
[Amit Varma]: And no doubt he will be on at a future date to talk about that as well.

02:32:53.280 --> 02:32:58.480
[Amit Varma]: But today, I thought we'll focus on public policy and some of his broader meta thinking

02:32:58.480 --> 02:33:03.800
[Amit Varma]: than what might now be happening in Afghanistan or Kashmir or the theater command imbroglio

02:33:03.800 --> 02:33:06.320
[Amit Varma]: as Akshay puts it, which, you know, I don't know what that is.

02:33:06.320 --> 02:33:09.840
[Amit Varma]: I'll have to Google it to find out after this.

02:33:09.840 --> 02:33:13.280
[Amit Varma]: Question from Sudhir Sarnobat, where he says his Hindi is very good.

02:33:13.280 --> 02:33:14.280
[Amit Varma]: Where did he learn that?

02:33:14.280 --> 02:33:15.840
[Amit Varma]: Is he from Nagpur or not somewhere?

02:33:15.840 --> 02:33:17.840
[Amit Varma]: You already answered this, I guess.

02:33:17.840 --> 02:33:20.400
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, so I'm not from the north.

02:33:20.400 --> 02:33:25.040
[Guest]: I mean, I spent seven years, first seven years.

02:33:25.040 --> 02:33:28.560
[Guest]: And I speak Marathi and now just Hindi at home.

02:33:28.560 --> 02:33:33.880
[Guest]: But I would say that Hindi newspaper reading improved my Hindi a lot.

02:33:33.880 --> 02:33:36.120
[Guest]: That's the simple answer to it.

02:33:36.120 --> 02:33:40.680
[Guest]: And I've always thought in Hindi, I don't think in English even today.

02:33:40.680 --> 02:33:45.400
[Guest]: That's the language which comes to my mind is Hindi, even though it's not my mother tongue.

02:33:45.400 --> 02:33:47.440
[Guest]: So I mean, yeah, somehow it's happened.

02:33:47.440 --> 02:33:49.760
[Guest]: So I guess it's because of the reading.

02:33:49.760 --> 02:33:55.160
[Guest]: You know, once you start getting ideas in a particular medium, probably you start thinking

02:33:55.160 --> 02:33:56.160
[Guest]: in.

02:33:56.160 --> 02:33:57.160
[Guest]: What about you, Amit?

02:33:57.160 --> 02:33:58.160
[Guest]: Always in English?

02:33:58.160 --> 02:33:59.160
[Amit Varma]: My Hindi?

02:33:59.160 --> 02:34:00.160
[Amit Varma]: No, no.

02:34:00.160 --> 02:34:04.560
[Amit Varma]: In fact, in class 10 and class 12, I got more marks in Hindi than in English.

02:34:04.560 --> 02:34:09.240
[Amit Varma]: And marks are no indicator, I mean, it tells you how flawed our education system is in

02:34:09.240 --> 02:34:11.120
[Amit Varma]: terms of metrics.

02:34:11.120 --> 02:34:14.360
[Amit Varma]: And my trick was there what a lot of people do in English, which is I just learned a whole

02:34:14.360 --> 02:34:19.160
[Amit Varma]: bunch of Hindi big words and put them together randomly and it kind of worked for me.

02:34:19.160 --> 02:34:23.280
[Amit Varma]: But otherwise, I have unfortunately lost lost touch with the languages.

02:34:23.280 --> 02:34:26.840
[Amit Varma]: So I'm not like Hindi, I can read and write Bengali.

02:34:26.840 --> 02:34:27.840
[Amit Varma]: My mom was Bengali.

02:34:27.840 --> 02:34:29.640
[Amit Varma]: So I grew up speaking Bengali at home.

02:34:29.640 --> 02:34:33.840
[Amit Varma]: And Marathi now I can understand after all these years in Pune and then Bombay for 20

02:34:33.840 --> 02:34:34.840
[Amit Varma]: plus years.

02:34:34.840 --> 02:34:36.780
[Amit Varma]: But it's not as good as I would like it to be.

02:34:36.780 --> 02:34:41.520
[Amit Varma]: And I would, I want to, you know, get it back working properly at some point.

02:34:41.520 --> 02:34:45.440
[Amit Varma]: And at some point later this year, I want to do things on YouTube and try out different

02:34:45.440 --> 02:34:46.440
[Amit Varma]: things and all of that.

02:34:46.440 --> 02:34:49.400
[Amit Varma]: And maybe you can join me and we can do something in Hindi, let's see.

02:34:49.400 --> 02:34:50.400
[Guest]: Sure.

02:34:50.400 --> 02:34:51.400
[Guest]: Yeah, that would be fun.

02:34:51.400 --> 02:34:53.480
[Guest]: Because that's one of my passions.

02:34:53.480 --> 02:34:57.200
[Guest]: This this idea that there's so much great content in English, right?

02:34:57.200 --> 02:34:59.400
[Guest]: You have the best in the world.

02:34:59.400 --> 02:35:01.200
[Guest]: But what about the other languages?

02:35:01.200 --> 02:35:02.200
[Guest]: Right?

02:35:02.200 --> 02:35:04.840
[Guest]: I mean, do we talk about opportunity costs in Hindi?

02:35:04.840 --> 02:35:09.480
[Guest]: Have you ever heard of engaging conversation in Hindi on this?

02:35:09.480 --> 02:35:10.480
[Guest]: I haven't.

02:35:10.480 --> 02:35:14.000
[Guest]: I have listened to a lot of Hindi content, but no, right?

02:35:14.000 --> 02:35:21.200
[Guest]: You will either have this really shuddh Hindi, which no one will understand, or it will be,

02:35:21.200 --> 02:35:22.720
[Guest]: you won't discuss these at all, right?

02:35:22.720 --> 02:35:28.880
[Guest]: So you will only discuss who won the elections or what is happening on in cricket or, you

02:35:28.880 --> 02:35:32.640
[Guest]: know, that ABCD of Indian marketing, right?

02:35:32.640 --> 02:35:35.480
[Guest]: Astrology, Bollywood, cricket and devotional.

02:35:35.480 --> 02:35:37.560
[Guest]: So these were the topics that you discuss.

02:35:37.560 --> 02:35:43.240
[Guest]: But who discusses economic reasoning, public policy, maybe some do, but not, I haven't

02:35:43.240 --> 02:35:44.240
[Guest]: heard of it.

02:35:44.240 --> 02:35:48.720
[Amit Varma]: No, I think everybody everywhere has a great hunger and desire to understand the world.

02:35:48.720 --> 02:35:53.000
[Amit Varma]: And the thing is, we assume that we live in a lucky age where everything is on the internet,

02:35:53.000 --> 02:35:54.780
[Amit Varma]: so all knowledge is available to us.

02:35:54.780 --> 02:35:59.560
[Amit Varma]: But if you think about it, that's the privilege of being English language speakers, that we

02:35:59.560 --> 02:36:01.240
[Amit Varma]: have that available to us.

02:36:01.240 --> 02:36:05.720
[Amit Varma]: People in Hindi who, you know, may not know English that well or be comfortable in it,

02:36:05.720 --> 02:36:08.920
[Amit Varma]: don't have that world open to them entirely.

02:36:08.920 --> 02:36:13.840
[Amit Varma]: And you know, people like you and me who keep talking about how, you know, elites designed

02:36:13.840 --> 02:36:18.200
[Amit Varma]: a constitution and it was nothing like society and Gandhi said society should be changed

02:36:18.200 --> 02:36:19.200
[Amit Varma]: from within.

02:36:19.200 --> 02:36:22.640
[Amit Varma]: Well, you know, we got to practice what we preach and actually speak the language of

02:36:22.640 --> 02:36:25.160
[Amit Varma]: society in whatever little way we can.

02:36:25.160 --> 02:36:27.160
[Amit Varma]: And otherwise, we are just speaking to fellow elites.

02:36:27.160 --> 02:36:28.680
[Amit Varma]: So I completely buy that.

02:36:28.680 --> 02:36:32.960
[Amit Varma]: There's another question on your language where Murlal asks, quote, can you ask him

02:36:32.960 --> 02:36:35.280
[Amit Varma]: about his accent, please, and where it comes from?

