[Amit Varma]: I don't know.

02:37:52.520 --> 02:37:54.560
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's more of a macroeconomic thing, right?

02:37:54.560 --> 02:37:55.560
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:37:55.560 --> 02:38:06.600
[Guest]: I mean, this idea that inflation is inherently something which is bad is, again, a fallacy,

02:38:06.600 --> 02:38:07.600
[Guest]: right?

02:38:07.600 --> 02:38:10.000
[Guest]: Inflation, any growing economy will have inflation.

02:38:10.000 --> 02:38:14.480
[Guest]: Why inflation happens is just because demand is greater than the supply for a particular

02:38:14.480 --> 02:38:15.480
[Guest]: product.

02:38:15.480 --> 02:38:16.480
[Guest]: Why is the demand greater?

02:38:16.480 --> 02:38:19.400
[Guest]: Because people's purchasing power has increased.

02:38:19.400 --> 02:38:26.600
[Guest]: So a society where there is no inflation means a society is getting stagnated in terms of

02:38:26.600 --> 02:38:31.840
[Guest]: its demand and the fact that people are having lesser purchasing power.

02:38:31.840 --> 02:38:35.200
[Guest]: So it will be a sad state of affairs when that happens.

02:38:35.200 --> 02:38:41.960
[Guest]: You know, we already see that in some countries where there is a stagnated economy.

02:38:41.960 --> 02:38:44.680
[Guest]: I don't think we have a good answer to this.

02:38:44.680 --> 02:38:45.680
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:38:45.680 --> 02:38:46.680
[Amit Varma]: So we don't have a good answer to this.

02:38:46.680 --> 02:38:53.360
[Amit Varma]: Randhir Borkar asks, too late, but please ask how he is smart in so many areas and working

02:38:53.360 --> 02:38:54.360
[Amit Varma]: habits.

02:38:54.360 --> 02:38:57.400
[Amit Varma]: We've spoken about your working habits, smart in so many areas, yes.

02:38:57.400 --> 02:39:01.400
[Amit Varma]: So broader question, which I had listed down, but I thought we don't have time.

02:39:01.400 --> 02:39:02.400
[Amit Varma]: So I won't ask.

02:39:02.400 --> 02:39:03.400
[Amit Varma]: But now it has come up.

02:39:03.400 --> 02:39:08.720
[Amit Varma]: Do you have mental models which you have thought about explicitly through which you kind of

02:39:08.720 --> 02:39:13.240
[Amit Varma]: look at the world or you apply them to different subjects and all of that to learn about them

02:39:13.240 --> 02:39:14.240
[Amit Varma]: better?

02:39:14.240 --> 02:39:15.240
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:39:15.240 --> 02:39:18.520
[Guest]: So I think I'll say this in three ways, OK?

02:39:18.520 --> 02:39:23.160
[Guest]: So one thing, I am not a specialist in anything.

02:39:23.160 --> 02:39:26.480
[Guest]: And actually, like, I don't like the word expert as well.

02:39:26.480 --> 02:39:28.880
[Guest]: So because I'm definitely not one of them.

02:39:28.880 --> 02:39:35.680
[Guest]: But in general, it's difficult to be expert in anything related to human humanities, right?

02:39:35.680 --> 02:39:36.680
[Guest]: We are always learning.

02:39:36.680 --> 02:39:43.320
[Guest]: So I'm so the way I approach it is think of it in a very general overview.

02:39:43.320 --> 02:39:49.240
[Guest]: So what I always advise people who want to start in public policy also that don't go

02:39:49.240 --> 02:39:53.240
[Guest]: into one narrow domain in at a very early stage.

02:39:53.240 --> 02:39:56.800
[Guest]: A lot of people will start with no health excites me.

02:39:56.800 --> 02:39:58.600
[Guest]: So I just want to do public health.

02:39:58.600 --> 02:40:00.600
[Guest]: But I would say go the opposite way, you know.

02:40:00.600 --> 02:40:02.720
[Guest]: So think of it as two axes.

02:40:02.720 --> 02:40:05.040
[Guest]: One is domains and one is disciplines.

02:40:05.040 --> 02:40:10.800
[Guest]: So domains are things like health, defense, environment, climate change, whatever, right?

02:40:10.800 --> 02:40:13.600
[Guest]: So these are domains of public policy.

02:40:13.600 --> 02:40:19.640
[Guest]: And on the other axis is disciplines, which are things like economic reasoning, psychology,

02:40:19.640 --> 02:40:23.080
[Guest]: social psychology, sociology, public finance, etc.

02:40:23.080 --> 02:40:27.360
[Guest]: So the idea is, don't dive into just one domain.

02:40:27.360 --> 02:40:35.120
[Guest]: But think of can you arm yourself with certain key ideas or toolkits from these disciplines

02:40:35.120 --> 02:40:36.120
[Guest]: as well.

02:40:36.120 --> 02:40:41.760
[Guest]: And then you so learn all these, you know, public finance, economic reasoning, and then

02:40:41.760 --> 02:40:46.640
[Guest]: you can apply them to one or two domains, you know, so you get bored with doing just

02:40:46.640 --> 02:40:47.640
[Guest]: one thing.

02:40:47.640 --> 02:40:48.640
[Guest]: So why would you just do one domain?

02:40:48.640 --> 02:40:52.840
[Guest]: So for example, I would love to do things on foreign policy when I'm bored of it.

02:40:52.840 --> 02:40:56.120
[Guest]: I would love to do things in public finance or something else.

02:40:56.120 --> 02:41:03.080
[Guest]: So just pick two or three domains and arm yourself with all these disciplines so that

02:41:03.080 --> 02:41:07.320
[Guest]: you can apply that frame to a variety of domains.

02:41:07.320 --> 02:41:10.720
[Guest]: Another additional thing that happens is, you know, a lot of knowledge generation happens

02:41:10.720 --> 02:41:16.280
[Guest]: at the intersection of one domain and one discipline, you know, so for example, a lot

02:41:16.280 --> 02:41:21.240
[Guest]: of people will think of Pakistan in a very foreign policy sense, right?

02:41:21.240 --> 02:41:26.360
[Guest]: So yeah, there are things which they do to India, and you wouldn't want them to.

02:41:26.360 --> 02:41:28.620
[Guest]: So the analysis is very political.

02:41:28.620 --> 02:41:34.000
[Guest]: But maybe if you are armed with the principles of public finance, if you are able to read

02:41:34.000 --> 02:41:39.480
[Guest]: the budget that Pakistan makes, maybe you will come up with an economic way to coerce

02:41:39.480 --> 02:41:42.000
[Guest]: an adversary that you wouldn't have thought of, right?

02:41:42.000 --> 02:41:46.920
[Guest]: So you new knowledge generation will always happen at this intersection.

02:41:46.920 --> 02:41:53.440
[Guest]: So why be bothered about an academic department sort of mindset, right?

02:41:53.440 --> 02:41:58.000
[Guest]: So that is one sort of main idea that I think of.

02:41:58.000 --> 02:42:04.080
[Guest]: The second one is, and I think, Amit, you know it best, right to learn instead of reading

02:42:04.080 --> 02:42:05.120
[Guest]: to learn only.

02:42:05.120 --> 02:42:11.800
[Guest]: So the more we try to write and learn, we develop mental frames to look at variety of

02:42:11.800 --> 02:42:12.800
[Guest]: problems.

02:42:12.800 --> 02:42:19.800
[Guest]: And we think of things that we ourselves wouldn't have imagined a few years back, right?

02:42:19.800 --> 02:42:24.360
[Guest]: So that writing experience opens up those windows.

02:42:24.360 --> 02:42:26.440
[Guest]: So that is one thing.

02:42:26.440 --> 02:42:31.600
[Guest]: The third thing, and this is not mine, but Hal Varian has a very good idea about this.

02:42:31.600 --> 02:42:38.000
[Guest]: He has written a nice paper on how to build an economic model in your spare time, okay?

02:42:38.000 --> 02:42:42.600
[Guest]: And that has three really nice insights which I think apply here.

02:42:42.600 --> 02:42:46.240
[Guest]: First idea is, where do you get your ideas from, right?

02:42:46.240 --> 02:42:51.080
[Guest]: And a lot of people would say, read journal papers and you will get ideas.

02:42:51.080 --> 02:42:54.480
[Guest]: He says that's not the way to get good ideas.

02:42:54.480 --> 02:42:57.960
[Guest]: Only the way you get good ideas is by reading bad arguments.

02:42:57.960 --> 02:42:59.920
[Guest]: So that's why you should be on Twitter, right?

02:42:59.920 --> 02:43:05.840
[Guest]: So you will basically get, there's nothing which inspires you to write about something

02:43:05.840 --> 02:43:08.400
[Guest]: or investigate than a bad idea, right?

02:43:08.400 --> 02:43:12.480
[Guest]: So you will get these really flawed references in your mind.

02:43:12.480 --> 02:43:17.840
[Guest]: When you get those, it inspires you to, okay, that's not the way to think and that's why

02:43:17.840 --> 02:43:18.840
[Guest]: I'll write it.

02:43:18.840 --> 02:43:28.360
[Guest]: So getting ideas through TV or through forums or Twitter is a great way to start off.

02:43:28.360 --> 02:43:33.760
[Guest]: It will inspire you to see a frame which you absolutely disagree with.

02:43:33.760 --> 02:43:35.160
[Guest]: So that's one first point.

02:43:35.160 --> 02:43:37.520
[Guest]: The second one is postpone your literature review.

02:43:37.520 --> 02:43:41.600
[Guest]: And this is also something quite counterintuitive.

02:43:41.600 --> 02:43:47.520
[Guest]: Once you think of an idea, people will directly dive into what has been done in this field.

02:43:47.520 --> 02:43:53.520
[Guest]: And the problem with that is you will eventually come to thinking the way others have already

02:43:53.520 --> 02:43:56.040
[Guest]: done and you won't come up with anything new.

02:43:56.040 --> 02:44:02.040
[Guest]: So the way he says is postpone literature review, actually think of what you would imagine

02:44:02.040 --> 02:44:03.040
[Guest]: the solution to be.

02:44:03.040 --> 02:44:04.720
[Guest]: Can you have your own framework?

02:44:04.720 --> 02:44:07.720
[Guest]: Can you imagine the way forward?

02:44:07.720 --> 02:44:10.560
[Guest]: And once you've done that, then look at literature review.

02:44:10.560 --> 02:44:14.080
[Guest]: You will be able to poke holes in your own solution better as well.

02:44:14.080 --> 02:44:15.360
[Guest]: So that was the second one.

02:44:15.360 --> 02:44:19.040
[Guest]: And the third thing is just giving a seminar.

02:44:19.040 --> 02:44:21.520
[Guest]: Just basically discussing your ideas.

02:44:21.520 --> 02:44:25.320
[Guest]: And I always say public policy is anyways a team sport.

02:44:25.320 --> 02:44:27.360
[Guest]: One person cannot transform India.

02:44:27.360 --> 02:44:30.160
[Guest]: Even thousand people cannot transform governance in India.

02:44:30.160 --> 02:44:34.400
[Guest]: You need lots and lots of ideas, debates, discussions.

02:44:34.400 --> 02:44:39.320
[Guest]: So discussing your ideas, however unformed they might be, is valuable.

02:44:39.320 --> 02:44:43.800
[Guest]: You get a lot of feedback and then you are able to improve upon it.

02:44:43.800 --> 02:44:46.200
[Guest]: So I think these three things are really nice.

02:44:46.200 --> 02:44:50.840
[Guest]: Not mine, but I think a lot of people will benefit from this paper.

02:44:50.840 --> 02:44:54.800
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, you know, we link it from the show notes and these are really fascinating.

02:44:54.800 --> 02:44:58.360
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I did an episode with Krish Yashok at the end of last year and he spoke about

02:44:58.360 --> 02:45:02.920
[Amit Varma]: some pyramid of learning and which are the most intense ways of learning about something.

02:45:02.920 --> 02:45:06.680
[Amit Varma]: You know, at the bottom is you just read something or, you know, slightly higher might be when

02:45:06.680 --> 02:45:11.160
[Amit Varma]: you when someone tells you and you're listening, but the highest is you teach something because

02:45:11.160 --> 02:45:13.720
[Amit Varma]: when you teach it, you have to teach it in a systematic way.

02:45:13.720 --> 02:45:16.200
[Amit Varma]: So you're forced to learn it better yourself.

02:45:16.200 --> 02:45:20.040
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, one of the things I love about Takshashila is so many incredibly smart people

02:45:20.040 --> 02:45:25.000
[Amit Varma]: always iterating with each other and trying to teach each other and learning from that.

02:45:25.000 --> 02:45:29.400
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, you know, writing is also a great way to clarify your thinking on a subject

02:45:29.400 --> 02:45:33.480
[Amit Varma]: like Joan Didion once said, quote, I don't know what I think until I write it down, stop

02:45:33.480 --> 02:45:34.480
[Amit Varma]: quote.

02:45:34.480 --> 02:45:38.400
[Amit Varma]: And just writing can often, you know, sharpen your thinking because if you want to write

02:45:38.400 --> 02:45:43.680
[Amit Varma]: something in clear language devoid of obfuscatory jargon or vague abstract terms, then you're

02:45:43.680 --> 02:45:46.320
[Amit Varma]: forced to get really concrete.

02:45:46.320 --> 02:45:49.200
[Amit Varma]: And that whole intersection of subjects is also really interesting.

02:45:49.200 --> 02:45:54.880
[Amit Varma]: Like I had Gautam Menon on my show, the biologist, and he was talking about how it was so fascinating

02:45:54.880 --> 02:46:01.840
[Amit Varma]: for him to go deep into both biology and physics and how much insight there is at the intersection

02:46:01.840 --> 02:46:05.280
[Amit Varma]: of those two, which is just wonderful.

02:46:05.280 --> 02:46:07.960
[Amit Varma]: Let's quickly move on to Twitter questions.

02:46:07.960 --> 02:46:10.620
[Guest]: I'll just add one thing, Amit.

02:46:10.620 --> 02:46:16.720
[Guest]: On teaching, right, I absolutely agree, but teaching is when you teach interested students,

02:46:16.720 --> 02:46:25.680
[Guest]: if you're teaching for a class, which probably are hoping for a degree or credit, then teaching

02:46:25.680 --> 02:46:28.240
[Guest]: doesn't challenge you the way you would want to.

02:46:28.240 --> 02:46:33.360
[Guest]: So what if you have a bunch of self selected students who really want to know because they

02:46:33.360 --> 02:46:39.600
[Guest]: are interested in it, and it's not because they'll get some job, or they'll get credit,

02:46:39.600 --> 02:46:43.080
[Guest]: then teaching is the most powerful way, right?

02:46:43.080 --> 02:46:48.880
[Guest]: They challenge you and you will then be dumbfounded, then you will go back, learn, be a better

02:46:48.880 --> 02:46:49.880
[Guest]: teacher.

02:46:49.880 --> 02:46:51.560
[Amit Varma]: So yeah, I would just add that.

02:46:51.560 --> 02:46:52.560
[Amit Varma]: Wonderful.

02:46:52.560 --> 02:46:58.000
[Amit Varma]: Myopic Astronomer wants to know, is currency devaluation a credible option for India or

02:46:58.000 --> 02:46:59.000
[Amit Varma]: would that be demo 2.0?

02:46:59.000 --> 02:47:00.680
[Amit Varma]: Do you have any views on this?

02:47:00.680 --> 02:47:02.240
[Amit Varma]: Why is he asking you?

02:47:02.240 --> 02:47:04.640
[Guest]: Yeah, I became a macroeconomist.

02:47:04.640 --> 02:47:09.680
[Guest]: But there is a very interesting idea about devaluation written about it.

02:47:09.680 --> 02:47:14.800
[Guest]: Generally, you know, there was this frame that one rupee should be equal to one dollar,

02:47:14.800 --> 02:47:18.320
[Guest]: you know, I've seen WhatsApp messages and all that.

02:47:18.320 --> 02:47:21.600
[Guest]: And I was looking at the history of it, right?

02:47:21.600 --> 02:47:29.760
[Guest]: And this was obviously earlier, it was intentionally you had the Britishers sort of overvaluing

02:47:29.760 --> 02:47:31.120
[Guest]: the currency, right?

02:47:31.120 --> 02:47:36.120
[Guest]: And when you have an overvalued currency, it benefited the system where you exported

02:47:36.120 --> 02:47:40.960
[Guest]: raw materials and you had a lot of British goods, clothes, etc. coming into India.

02:47:40.960 --> 02:47:43.400
[Guest]: So overvaluation actually harmed us.

02:47:43.400 --> 02:47:47.760
[Guest]: It was one of the ways in which the colonial economy worked, one of the principal ways

02:47:47.760 --> 02:47:48.760
[Guest]: in which.

02:47:48.760 --> 02:47:54.240
[Guest]: But there is this notion that still we should have this one rupee equal to one dollar and

02:47:54.240 --> 02:47:55.480
[Guest]: it is completely flawed.

02:47:55.480 --> 02:48:00.440
[Guest]: And in fact, Manmohan Singh had a really great speech about this.

02:48:00.440 --> 02:48:05.520
[Guest]: It is very pervasive, you know, this idea was being discussed in parliament, etc.

02:48:05.520 --> 02:48:11.120
[Guest]: And Manmohan Singh very eloquently talks about why this shouldn't be the case.

02:48:11.120 --> 02:48:17.720
[Guest]: You know, there is nothing which is prestigious about an overvalued currency or an undervalued.

02:48:17.720 --> 02:48:22.920
[Guest]: So I think we can link to that, Manmohan Singh will explain this much better than I can.

02:48:22.920 --> 02:48:27.560
[Amit Varma]: Manmohan Singh will explain this and for fans of the current regime who are smoking at the

02:48:27.560 --> 02:48:31.040
[Amit Varma]: mention of Manmohan Singh, let's point out that when Manmohan Singh was PM, the rupee

02:48:31.040 --> 02:48:34.680
[Amit Varma]: was far closer to being one dollar than it is today.

02:48:34.680 --> 02:48:39.200
[Amit Varma]: And I agree that there's not necessarily any one right level for it.

02:48:39.200 --> 02:48:41.120
[Amit Varma]: But that's a macroeconomic discussion.

02:48:41.120 --> 02:48:44.160
[Amit Varma]: I think I'd asked Ila Patnaik this also in my episode with her.

02:48:44.160 --> 02:48:46.560
[Amit Varma]: But anyway, that's a different subject.

02:48:46.560 --> 02:48:51.280
[Amit Varma]: Shantanu wants to know, quote, I wish to know whether his favorite foreign policy philosophy,

02:48:51.280 --> 02:48:55.560
[Amit Varma]: Matsyana, really can answer happenings across the globe.

02:48:55.560 --> 02:48:57.600
[Amit Varma]: Top quote and apologies for mispronunciations.

02:48:57.600 --> 02:48:59.800
[Guest]: Yeah, Matsyana, right.

02:48:59.800 --> 02:49:01.520
[Guest]: So it is law of the fishes.

02:49:01.520 --> 02:49:05.240
[Guest]: Yeah, that basically is realism at play, right.

02:49:05.240 --> 02:49:13.200
[Guest]: So the fact that big fish eats small fish and Matsyana is a quotidian Arthashastra concept.

02:49:13.200 --> 02:49:17.160
[Guest]: But so thinking of whether it applies to the real world.

02:49:17.160 --> 02:49:18.160
[Guest]: Yes, it does.

02:49:18.160 --> 02:49:22.840
[Guest]: You know, we can explain a lot of things that happen in international relations through

02:49:22.840 --> 02:49:23.840
[Guest]: this frame.

02:49:23.840 --> 02:49:29.520
[Guest]: Like there are three traditions in foreign policy broadly, which is realism, there is

02:49:29.520 --> 02:49:32.400
[Guest]: liberalism and there is constructivism.

02:49:32.400 --> 02:49:34.880
[Guest]: And we've discussed this in our last episode.

02:49:34.880 --> 02:49:37.080
[Guest]: So I'm not going into more detail.

02:49:37.080 --> 02:49:43.320
[Guest]: But yes, Matsyana and realism explain a lot of what happens in the international sphere,

02:49:43.320 --> 02:49:48.880
[Guest]: just like how see what US could do in Iraq and Afghanistan, right?

02:49:48.880 --> 02:49:50.600
[Guest]: Who could question it, right?

02:49:50.600 --> 02:49:56.080
[Guest]: That was also an example of the fact that because they had the power, they could exert

02:49:56.080 --> 02:49:57.080
[Guest]: it.

02:49:57.080 --> 02:50:00.840
[Guest]: There is, yes, something called UNSC and United Nations.

02:50:00.840 --> 02:50:01.840
[Guest]: What could they do?

02:50:01.840 --> 02:50:02.840
[Guest]: Nothing.

02:50:02.840 --> 02:50:03.920
[Guest]: You see that playing even now, right?

02:50:03.920 --> 02:50:10.840
[Guest]: Is the fact that you are not even able to investigate whether, where did the coronavirus

02:50:10.840 --> 02:50:12.760
[Guest]: pandemic start from, right?

02:50:12.760 --> 02:50:18.080
[Guest]: And this just illustrates that power has a big role to play in international relations.

02:50:18.080 --> 02:50:24.480
[Guest]: And the one point I would add is, sadly, people apply Matsyana to domestic sphere as well.

02:50:24.480 --> 02:50:28.000
[Guest]: And they think everything is Matsyana and it is justified.

02:50:28.000 --> 02:50:30.160
[Guest]: That's exactly not the case, right?

02:50:30.160 --> 02:50:34.080
[Guest]: When we talk about Matsyana, we are talking about international relations, a different

02:50:34.080 --> 02:50:35.080
[Guest]: system.

02:50:35.080 --> 02:50:38.840
[Guest]: But in a domestic realm, I mean, we should not want Matsyana to prevail, right?

02:50:38.840 --> 02:50:44.720
[Guest]: We would want a republic which ensures our rights irrespective of the power that we have.

02:50:44.720 --> 02:50:47.240
[Guest]: And that is why you have the state in the first place.

02:50:47.240 --> 02:50:53.680
[Guest]: So the existence of Matsyana in domestic relations would mean that the state has failed.

02:50:53.680 --> 02:51:01.120
[Amit Varma]: I guess Matsyana, whatever you call it, is a good descriptive frame to look at international

02:51:01.120 --> 02:51:05.840
[Amit Varma]: affairs, which can often be zero sum, but would be a terrible prescriptive frame to

02:51:05.840 --> 02:51:11.040
[Amit Varma]: look at domestic affairs where we want to protect everyone's rights and avoid coercion

02:51:11.040 --> 02:51:13.040
[Amit Varma]: as far as possible.

02:51:13.040 --> 02:51:14.840
[Amit Varma]: Big fish eat little fish instead.

02:51:14.840 --> 02:51:16.840
[Amit Varma]: Anirudh Menon has two questions.

02:51:16.840 --> 02:51:19.000
[Amit Varma]: First of them is about semiconductors.

02:51:19.000 --> 02:51:20.000
[Amit Varma]: What is this?

02:51:20.000 --> 02:51:23.560
[Amit Varma]: And the second one is, what fiction are you reading?

02:51:23.560 --> 02:51:29.200
[Guest]: Yeah, so actually, as I said, I don't read a lot of fiction.

02:51:29.200 --> 02:51:33.720
[Guest]: So first, one of the first tasks that was assigned to me when I joined Takshashila was

02:51:33.720 --> 02:51:37.520
[Guest]: to read all Harry Potter books.

02:51:37.520 --> 02:51:41.880
[Guest]: And that was like a new learning for me.

02:51:41.880 --> 02:51:45.240
[Guest]: And that's where I learned the defense of the dark arts and all that.

02:51:45.240 --> 02:51:48.800
[Guest]: So but yeah, I don't read a lot of fiction.

02:51:48.800 --> 02:51:56.480
[Guest]: I really love the nonfiction segment itself, just the way the fact is more fun than fiction,

02:51:56.480 --> 02:52:01.200
[Guest]: I would say not even the fact that fact is more stranger than fiction.

02:52:01.200 --> 02:52:05.860
[Guest]: I don't know how strange fiction is, but I like the fun element of it.

02:52:05.860 --> 02:52:12.520
[Guest]: So I read a lot of travelogues kind of thing, city biographies, that is a genre I like but

02:52:12.520 --> 02:52:13.520
[Amit Varma]: not so much fiction.

02:52:13.520 --> 02:52:16.080
[Amit Varma]: Have you read the Power Broker by Robert Caro?

02:52:16.080 --> 02:52:17.080
[Amit Varma]: No.

02:52:17.080 --> 02:52:18.080
[Amit Varma]: Are you kidding me?

02:52:18.080 --> 02:52:19.080
[Amit Varma]: Okay.

02:52:19.080 --> 02:52:23.320
[Amit Varma]: Recommendation to you and all my listeners, and old timer listeners would have heard it

02:52:23.320 --> 02:52:24.320
[Amit Varma]: before.

02:52:24.320 --> 02:52:27.040
[Amit Varma]: The Power Broker by Robert Caro is this masterpiece.

02:52:27.040 --> 02:52:30.920
[Amit Varma]: It must be a million words or half one and a half million or whatever.

02:52:30.920 --> 02:52:35.680
[Amit Varma]: Massive book on it's actually around 800,000 now I remember and I'll tell you why I remember.

02:52:35.680 --> 02:52:38.940
[Amit Varma]: It is actually three books in one in a sense.

02:52:38.940 --> 02:52:43.200
[Amit Varma]: At one level, it is a biography of this guy called Robert Moses, who designed most of

02:52:43.200 --> 02:52:45.120
[Amit Varma]: modern New York and all of that.

02:52:45.120 --> 02:52:50.320
[Amit Varma]: At another level, it's a biography of New York, the city over several decades.

02:52:50.320 --> 02:52:56.780
[Amit Varma]: And at a third level, it is a study of power, of how power shapes the world and the reason

02:52:56.780 --> 02:53:02.840
[Amit Varma]: I remember to say 800,000 was it was originally a million, and he had to cut it down to 800,000.

02:53:02.840 --> 02:53:07.240
[Amit Varma]: And out of the 200,000 or so words that he cut out was a book length portion on Jane

02:53:07.240 --> 02:53:08.880
[Amit Varma]: Jacobs.

02:53:08.880 --> 02:53:11.160
[Amit Varma]: And Jane Jacobs, of course, is one of my heroes.

02:53:11.160 --> 02:53:14.000
[Amit Varma]: She wrote the great book, The Death and Life of American Cities.

02:53:14.000 --> 02:53:15.120
[Amit Varma]: It's a masterpiece.

02:53:15.120 --> 02:53:20.760
[Amit Varma]: And she was constantly in opposition to Moses, because Moses was this top down central planner

02:53:20.760 --> 02:53:21.760
[Amit Varma]: kind of person.

02:53:21.760 --> 02:53:28.240
[Amit Varma]: And Jane Jacobs was much more about how are the people actually living, what is organically

02:53:28.240 --> 02:53:30.760
[Amit Varma]: emerging from there, you got to respect that.

02:53:30.760 --> 02:53:34.520
[Amit Varma]: The remarkable figure Jacobs and these are both these books are masterpieces, but you

02:53:34.520 --> 02:53:40.520
[Amit Varma]: mentioned biographies of cities and the Power Broker is just kind of on top of my list over

02:53:40.520 --> 02:53:41.520
[Amit Varma]: there.

02:53:41.520 --> 02:53:42.520
[Amit Varma]: But I'm sorry, continue.

02:53:42.520 --> 02:53:44.720
[Guest]: Yeah, no, that that's it.

02:53:44.720 --> 02:53:49.400
[Guest]: I think that kind of books I like but fiction, no.

02:53:49.400 --> 02:53:53.440
[Amit Varma]: And I would just say that, you know, nobody should ever pass value judgment on someone

02:53:53.440 --> 02:53:57.060
[Amit Varma]: who reads only nonfiction and not fiction or vice versa.

02:53:57.060 --> 02:54:02.000
[Amit Varma]: Because the point is that opportunity cost life, you know, time is limited, life is short,

02:54:02.000 --> 02:54:03.080
[Amit Varma]: we will all die.

02:54:03.080 --> 02:54:06.760
[Amit Varma]: So while we are alive, you want to read things you enjoy reading, you don't want to force

02:54:06.760 --> 02:54:12.520
[Amit Varma]: yourself to read because reading diversity or so and so friend has said this is a great

02:54:12.520 --> 02:54:13.520
[Amit Varma]: book.

02:54:13.520 --> 02:54:14.520
[Amit Varma]: It's part of the canon.

02:54:14.520 --> 02:54:17.240
[Amit Varma]: Read what you enjoy reading and feel no guilt whatsoever.

02:54:17.240 --> 02:54:19.280
[Amit Varma]: Like I keep saying any reading is good.

02:54:19.280 --> 02:54:23.800
[Amit Varma]: You read Chanda Mama also old copies that is good reading is good period.

02:54:23.800 --> 02:54:29.320
[Guest]: Yeah, but a lot of people have told me Amit that you must read fiction because it opens

02:54:29.320 --> 02:54:32.520
[Guest]: you to newer ways of thinking.

02:54:32.520 --> 02:54:34.400
[Guest]: Yeah, so maybe that's true.

02:54:34.400 --> 02:54:37.160
[Guest]: I'm probably missing out on that.

02:54:37.160 --> 02:54:41.080
[Amit Varma]: So yeah, I think great fiction is a very good way of zooming in.

02:54:41.080 --> 02:54:45.160
[Amit Varma]: Like a lot of my writing students, I'll find that they'll zoom out very well, where they

02:54:45.160 --> 02:54:50.440
[Amit Varma]: discuss things at a broader level, you know, but it's a zooming in which makes fiction

02:54:50.440 --> 02:54:53.320
[Amit Varma]: special because, you know, we only live one life.

02:54:53.320 --> 02:54:57.920
[Amit Varma]: But when we read fiction, we can live the lives of others, if the fiction is good enough,

02:54:57.920 --> 02:55:01.200
[Amit Varma]: and you can only do that, you know, through fiction, really.

02:55:01.200 --> 02:55:05.360
[Amit Varma]: And that is valuable, but I still would not pass a value judgment because life is limited.

02:55:05.360 --> 02:55:09.280
[Amit Varma]: And if as long as people are reading, I won't pass judgment on what they are reading because

02:55:09.280 --> 02:55:11.960
[Amit Varma]: most people are not reading and that's that's a problem.

