02:56:19.000 --> 02:56:23.600
[Amit Varma]: Molly at Abhinav Molly asks an interesting question, quote, let's get an economist to

02:56:23.600 --> 02:56:26.320
[Amit Varma]: answer Reddit's favorite AMA question.

02:56:26.320 --> 02:56:32.600
[Amit Varma]: Would it be better to fight one horse-sized duck or 100 duck-sized horses?

02:56:32.600 --> 02:56:35.760
[Unknown]: Yeah, I have.

02:56:35.760 --> 02:56:40.160
[Guest]: I'm just thinking about this.

02:56:40.160 --> 02:56:46.000
[Guest]: What lens would you apply to this comparative advantage?

02:56:46.000 --> 02:56:47.000
[Guest]: I don't know.

02:56:47.000 --> 02:56:48.000
[Amit Varma]: I really don't.

02:56:48.000 --> 02:56:49.720
[Amit Varma]: I'll give my answer and then you can give yours.

02:56:49.720 --> 02:56:51.880
[Amit Varma]: The first time I've seen this question, it's a lovely question.

02:56:51.880 --> 02:56:54.720
[Amit Varma]: One horse-sized duck or 100 duck-sized horses.

02:56:54.720 --> 02:56:59.840
[Amit Varma]: I would rather fight one horse-sized duck for the simple reason that I would assume

02:56:59.840 --> 02:57:02.960
[Amit Varma]: that these creatures have me overpowered anyway.

02:57:02.960 --> 02:57:09.760
[Amit Varma]: But the only way I can get away is if my opponent makes a mental mistake or if I can outthink

02:57:09.760 --> 02:57:10.760
[Amit Varma]: the opponent.

02:57:10.760 --> 02:57:15.960
[Amit Varma]: And it is more likely for me to outthink one opponent than to outthink a hundred opponents.

02:57:15.960 --> 02:57:22.560
[Amit Varma]: So I would opt to fight the one horse-sized duck rather than a hundred duck-sized horses,

02:57:22.560 --> 02:57:27.360
[Amit Varma]: assuming they are all equally hostile to me, which I don't see why it would be the case

02:57:27.360 --> 02:57:33.560
[Amit Varma]: because I have a very convivial relationship with both ducks and horses in the past and

02:57:33.560 --> 02:57:37.000
[Amit Varma]: have not tried to ride either.

02:57:37.000 --> 02:57:38.840
[Guest]: Do you have any kind of answer now?

02:57:38.840 --> 02:57:39.840
[Guest]: No.

02:57:39.840 --> 02:57:44.780
[Guest]: I mean, after you put it this way, maybe, yeah, it's similar.

02:57:44.780 --> 02:57:49.040
[Guest]: But it depends, no, we need to know what are the assumptions made.

02:57:49.040 --> 02:57:52.920
[Guest]: So the hundred things might actually fight amongst themselves.

02:57:52.920 --> 02:57:56.840
[Guest]: So they might not be concentrated on you as an adversary.

02:57:56.840 --> 02:58:01.160
[Guest]: So there are so many other variables that you need to take into account.

02:58:01.160 --> 02:58:02.160
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:58:02.160 --> 02:58:05.440
[Amit Varma]: So, yeah, good question for both of us to think about.

02:58:05.440 --> 02:58:09.320
[Amit Varma]: Thaul asks a question about Matsyana, we've already done that.

02:58:09.320 --> 02:58:11.120
[Amit Varma]: Bharatan asks, what does Kutasana mean?

02:58:11.120 --> 02:58:12.120
[Amit Varma]: We've done that.

02:58:12.120 --> 02:58:16.400
[Amit Varma]: Kautilya Subramaniam asks, what are his main sources for IR news?

02:58:16.400 --> 02:58:20.280
[Amit Varma]: What does he read on a daily basis, religiously, if any?

02:58:20.280 --> 02:58:21.280
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:58:21.280 --> 02:58:28.960
[Guest]: So one thing I realized, Amit, I think one is just creating good Twitter lists helps.

02:58:28.960 --> 02:58:32.200
[Guest]: So I have lists for my subject area.

02:58:32.200 --> 02:58:37.620
[Guest]: So more than the feed, I just go to TweetDeck and look at the list.

02:58:37.620 --> 02:58:38.620
[Guest]: That helps me.

02:58:38.620 --> 02:58:44.040
[Guest]: The second thing is just using the good old RSS reader.

02:58:44.040 --> 02:58:49.440
[Guest]: So subscribe to a lot of things on that and just go and read that.

02:58:49.440 --> 02:58:56.320
[Guest]: So maybe you will have Foreign Affairs, that magazine, Economist, Economist is really great

02:58:56.320 --> 02:58:59.400
[Guest]: for someone who's interested in a bunch of things.

02:58:59.400 --> 02:59:10.000
[Guest]: So I have like around 600-700 sources in that OPML file and just follow that is my idea.

02:59:10.000 --> 02:59:17.120
[Guest]: Because otherwise you end up reading so broadly that you might miss out the important things.

02:59:17.120 --> 02:59:23.120
[Guest]: So just using the RSS reader helps me focus on the things that I want to.

02:59:23.120 --> 02:59:24.120
[Guest]: I don't know.

02:59:24.120 --> 02:59:25.120
[Amit Varma]: What do you do?

02:59:25.120 --> 02:59:26.320
[Amit Varma]: Reading broadly and in a dispersed way.

02:59:26.320 --> 02:59:30.200
[Amit Varma]: No, I found your answer very curious and I'll ask a follow up question.

02:59:30.200 --> 02:59:34.160
[Amit Varma]: Because not curious, I don't mean that in I mean, I found it interesting.

02:59:34.160 --> 02:59:38.160
[Amit Varma]: I am curious about learning more, because it strikes me that a lot of my reading is

02:59:38.160 --> 02:59:39.920
[Amit Varma]: too broad and too dispersed.

02:59:39.920 --> 02:59:44.280
[Amit Varma]: And I wish I could, you know, build some kind of system which it seems to me that you have

02:59:44.280 --> 02:59:45.280
[Amit Varma]: done.

02:59:45.280 --> 02:59:50.720
[Amit Varma]: So apart from having the system where you have sort of curated lists or feeds or whatever,

02:59:50.720 --> 02:59:54.620
[Amit Varma]: are there also specific times of the day you give to reading and I have to change this

02:59:54.620 --> 02:59:59.240
[Amit Varma]: habit where I'll just be on Twitter or I'll be wherever and I'll just hit links at random

02:59:59.240 --> 03:00:04.560
[Amit Varma]: and I'll forget about them a minute later and I'll have 800 tabs open and until my computer

03:00:04.560 --> 03:00:06.180
[Amit Varma]: just gives up.

03:00:06.180 --> 03:00:09.440
[Amit Varma]: So do you have a system of reading and taking in knowledge?

03:00:09.440 --> 03:00:13.760
[Guest]: Yeah, so I, to be frank, I don't have a great system either.

03:00:13.760 --> 03:00:19.720
[Guest]: But what I do is, for example, if there's a PDF, I will always read it not on the browser,

03:00:19.720 --> 03:00:24.720
[Guest]: but I will download it on a software like Mendeley and use that to read.

03:00:24.720 --> 03:00:28.560
[Guest]: So all my PDFs will be in one place that I read later.

03:00:28.560 --> 03:00:32.920
[Guest]: Yeah, other articles, yeah, I'll just read the way you do.

03:00:32.920 --> 03:00:39.720
[Guest]: But just the idea that instead of reading in the tabs, you read on your RSS reader makes

03:00:39.720 --> 03:00:45.920
[Guest]: you go towards the things you really want to write and I keep changing those RSS feeds.

03:00:45.920 --> 03:00:52.320
[Guest]: So sometimes if I'm interested in, say, semiconductors, I will just put some Google alerts in that

03:00:52.320 --> 03:00:53.320
[Guest]: RSS feed.

03:00:53.320 --> 03:00:59.720
[Guest]: So I read news, but through the RSS feeds, which will help me focus on a particular area

03:00:59.720 --> 03:01:04.880
[Guest]: instead of going to news.google.co.in where you might read about Tapsee Pannu's review

03:01:04.880 --> 03:01:08.880
[Guest]: of a particular movie, I will then read about semiconductors.

03:01:08.880 --> 03:01:11.280
[Guest]: So that sort of helps sometimes.

03:01:11.280 --> 03:01:14.600
[Guest]: I don't have a definite time of the day for reading.

03:01:14.600 --> 03:01:17.080
[Guest]: I have a definite time of the day for writing.

03:01:17.080 --> 03:01:21.400
[Guest]: So that helps me in sort of trying to collect.

03:01:21.400 --> 03:01:22.760
[Guest]: Which is which is what?

03:01:22.760 --> 03:01:27.360
[Guest]: So newsletters, for example, I always write on Saturday nights.

03:01:27.360 --> 03:01:35.200
[Guest]: So it's, yeah, 8, 8.30pm to whatever 1pm, 1am, 2am, whatever time it may take.

03:01:35.200 --> 03:01:40.400
[Guest]: So through the week, I'm trying to collate thoughts, I have made a list of topics that

03:01:40.400 --> 03:01:46.720
[Guest]: I come across when I read the newspaper or on Twitter or wherever bad ideas, good ideas.

03:01:46.720 --> 03:01:53.680
[Guest]: And I'm constantly jotting them down, thinking through them through the week and noting them

03:01:53.680 --> 03:01:54.840
[Guest]: down on Obsidian.

03:01:54.840 --> 03:02:01.600
[Guest]: So taking notes whenever they strike, and then do focus writing during the weekend.

03:02:01.600 --> 03:02:07.600
[Guest]: Otherwise, if it is op-eds, etc, then it is again in the evenings, generally, just the

03:02:07.600 --> 03:02:12.760
[Guest]: same time after dinner, and don't sleep until you've finished.

03:02:12.760 --> 03:02:14.080
[Amit Varma]: And I love your newsletter.

03:02:14.080 --> 03:02:18.920
[Amit Varma]: And of course, also done an episode with Raghu Sanjay Lal Jaitley, your co-writer, who calls

03:02:18.920 --> 03:02:23.560
[Amit Varma]: himself RLJ these days, and keeps reminding me of the Rock Street Journal, which used

03:02:23.560 --> 03:02:27.000
[Amit Varma]: to be this music magazine, indie music magazine in India in the 1990s.

03:02:27.000 --> 03:02:31.760
[Amit Varma]: I am, by the way, the only person in the world who has had his byline in both Rock Street

03:02:31.760 --> 03:02:34.240
[Amit Varma]: Journal and Wall Street Journal.

03:02:34.240 --> 03:02:38.440
[Amit Varma]: So no one else has that unique honor.

03:02:38.440 --> 03:02:39.960
[Amit Varma]: So how is it like writing with him?

03:02:39.960 --> 03:02:43.320
[Amit Varma]: Like one thing I've noticed is that always the first piece in the newsletter will be

03:02:43.320 --> 03:02:44.720
[Amit Varma]: by RLJ.

03:02:44.720 --> 03:02:48.920
[Amit Varma]: So is this out of modesty that like, do you put it together and you just put his on top

03:02:48.920 --> 03:02:51.200
[Amit Varma]: because he's such a nice guy?

03:02:51.200 --> 03:02:52.200
[Amit Varma]: What's the deal?

03:02:52.200 --> 03:02:53.200
[Amit Varma]: And do you play off each other?

03:02:53.200 --> 03:02:56.600
[Amit Varma]: Do you sometimes during the week, do you discuss that I'm writing about this?

03:02:56.600 --> 03:02:57.600
[Amit Varma]: What are you writing about?

03:02:57.600 --> 03:02:58.600
[Guest]: How does it work?

03:02:58.600 --> 03:03:02.080
[Guest]: Okay, I have met RLJ only once in my life.

03:03:02.080 --> 03:03:03.080
[Guest]: Okay.

03:03:03.080 --> 03:03:09.600
[Guest]: So it's always been communication through either WhatsApp or on the phone very rarely.

03:03:09.600 --> 03:03:12.680
[Guest]: So both of us work very independently on this.

03:03:12.680 --> 03:03:18.440
[Guest]: So he writes his stuff, and I write on topics that I want to.

03:03:18.440 --> 03:03:24.680
[Guest]: Sometimes there have been editions where I had a comment or a rebuttal to what he wrote

03:03:24.680 --> 03:03:25.680
[Guest]: and things like that.

03:03:25.680 --> 03:03:27.000
[Guest]: So that's the way it is.

03:03:27.000 --> 03:03:33.080
[Guest]: And the reason why his writing was upfront is because he finishes always before than

03:03:33.080 --> 03:03:34.080
[Guest]: I do.

03:03:34.080 --> 03:03:38.560
[Guest]: So I am always the person who's sending the things towards the end.

03:03:38.560 --> 03:03:42.680
[Guest]: So that's why it was and RLJ is a much better writer than I am.

03:03:42.680 --> 03:03:49.440
[Guest]: So I always put his writing up front so that maybe people would then read mine as well.

03:03:49.440 --> 03:03:50.440
[Amit Varma]: That's incredibly modest.

03:03:50.440 --> 03:03:53.120
[Amit Varma]: I don't know what to say because I love both of your writings.

03:03:53.120 --> 03:03:56.560
[Amit Varma]: And you both write in different ways, but you are two of my favorite thinkers.

03:03:56.560 --> 03:04:00.800
[Amit Varma]: So honestly, just seeing you writing one newsletter is like mind blowing.

03:04:00.800 --> 03:04:07.760
[Amit Varma]: And if anybody hasn't subscribed to Anticipating the Unintended, please do so.

03:04:07.760 --> 03:04:08.760
[Amit Varma]: It's at publicpolicy.substack.com.

03:04:08.760 --> 03:04:14.360
[Amit Varma]: We'll also be linked from the show notes, obviously, two of our finest thinkers and

03:04:14.360 --> 03:04:16.960
[Amit Varma]: also most modest thinkers like what is this even?

03:04:16.960 --> 03:04:17.960
[Amit Varma]: Okay.

03:04:17.960 --> 03:04:24.040
[Amit Varma]: So let us move on to next Twitter question, Devashish Patel, Aditya Vajha and someone

03:04:24.040 --> 03:04:28.160
[Amit Varma]: called Naren who just put a plus one to Aditya's question, all have the same question about

03:04:28.160 --> 03:04:33.800
[Amit Varma]: how do you move into a public policy career from an IT career?

03:04:33.800 --> 03:04:40.680
[Guest]: Yeah, I think that was the transition I also made so I can relate to it.

03:04:40.680 --> 03:04:46.760
[Guest]: But the idea is now the options are much, much more than they were back then, you know,

