03:04:54.400 --> 03:04:55.520
[Guest]: So that has opened.

03:04:55.520 --> 03:05:00.960
[Guest]: So my way of thinking about this was, again, minimize opportunity cost, right.

03:05:00.960 --> 03:05:06.240
[Guest]: So idea was, I am working in a particular area, I have, I know nothing about public

03:05:06.240 --> 03:05:07.240
[Guest]: policy.

03:05:07.240 --> 03:05:09.960
[Guest]: So can I take a course while I'm working?

03:05:09.960 --> 03:05:13.960
[Guest]: And that's the great thing that Takshashila offers, right, the GCP because it is meant

03:05:13.960 --> 03:05:19.800
[Guest]: for working professionals, people who don't know about this topic, but want to explore

03:05:19.800 --> 03:05:20.800
[Guest]: it, right.

03:05:20.800 --> 03:05:24.160
[Guest]: So it's a sachet course for someone wanting to know.

03:05:24.160 --> 03:05:31.360
[Guest]: So that's how I started and I will also probably recommend it to people who want to get into

03:05:31.360 --> 03:05:38.080
[Guest]: this area that try it out first, you will know something and if it really, you know,

03:05:38.080 --> 03:05:42.120
[Guest]: it lights a bulb in your head, and you want to actually explore this further, then there

03:05:42.120 --> 03:05:47.800
[Guest]: are various opportunities, you know, now, companies have public policy departments,

03:05:47.800 --> 03:05:54.640
[Guest]: they recruit people, then there are, of course, governments also have opened up, you know,

03:05:54.640 --> 03:05:58.040
[Guest]: on contract positions where hiring happens.

03:05:58.040 --> 03:06:01.400
[Guest]: So there are many, many more avenues now.

03:06:01.400 --> 03:06:03.480
[Guest]: So maybe start small first.

03:06:03.480 --> 03:06:09.840
[Guest]: And then if you're interested, either do a master's, PhD, or directly jump into public

03:06:09.840 --> 03:06:11.640
[Guest]: policy careers itself.

03:06:11.640 --> 03:06:18.040
[Guest]: What I will say is people looking to recruit in this area need two or three things, one

03:06:18.040 --> 03:06:22.880
[Guest]: writing skills, so they always focus on really good writing skills, they can do my writing

03:06:22.880 --> 03:06:26.960
[Amit Varma]: course for that and the rest they can learn from Takshashila.

03:06:26.960 --> 03:06:28.640
[Guest]: And second one is economic reasoning.

03:06:28.640 --> 03:06:35.920
[Guest]: So if these two are really sort of fundamentals that you built on, then you can directly jump

03:06:35.920 --> 03:06:40.040
[Guest]: into a career, try a few things and explore it.

03:06:40.040 --> 03:06:43.160
[Guest]: So what I would say is there are lots of options.

03:06:43.160 --> 03:06:48.600
[Guest]: And this is a career where we need a lot of people from different disciplines to come

03:06:48.600 --> 03:06:50.320
[Guest]: and contribute.

03:06:50.320 --> 03:06:53.680
[Guest]: And our public discourse will be richer and better if that happens.

03:06:53.680 --> 03:06:59.800
[Guest]: So please do if you are in an IT career, consider thinking public policy is fascinating.

03:06:59.800 --> 03:07:04.600
[Amit Varma]: So before we move on with the questions, tell me more about this upcoming Takshashila course.

03:07:04.600 --> 03:07:09.540
[Amit Varma]: And you know, why people study public policy, what kind of things do you teach, what they

03:07:09.540 --> 03:07:10.540
[Amit Varma]: can expect?

03:07:10.540 --> 03:07:11.660
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit more about that.

03:07:11.660 --> 03:07:17.160
[Amit Varma]: Because I you know, I've for your postgraduate course, I taught this thing on how to write

03:07:17.160 --> 03:07:20.960
[Amit Varma]: an op-ed for a brief file, which was where I first two, three years ago got the idea

03:07:20.960 --> 03:07:22.640
[Amit Varma]: for the writing course I do now.

03:07:22.640 --> 03:07:23.800
[Amit Varma]: So I'm very grateful for that.

03:07:23.800 --> 03:07:27.100
[Amit Varma]: And I was given access to the all the other lectures.

03:07:27.100 --> 03:07:30.200
[Amit Varma]: So while I haven't done the course, I have a fair idea of the content.

03:07:30.200 --> 03:07:31.200
[Amit Varma]: And it is mind blowing.

03:07:31.200 --> 03:07:36.120
[Amit Varma]: Like I wish I had sort of done this course when I was in my 20s, because it would just

03:07:36.120 --> 03:07:42.360
[Amit Varma]: have made the way I look at the world so much clearer and so much better and just an incredible

03:07:42.360 --> 03:07:47.320
[Amit Varma]: bunch of teachers also, you know, people like you and Nitin and Manoj and so on.

03:07:47.320 --> 03:07:52.280
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit, tell us, tell my listeners a little bit more about this course.

03:07:52.280 --> 03:07:53.720
[Amit Varma]: When does it start?

03:07:53.720 --> 03:07:54.720
[Amit Varma]: What's the process?

03:07:54.720 --> 03:07:56.520
[Amit Varma]: Why should they learn?

03:07:56.520 --> 03:07:58.080
[Amit Varma]: And how will you go about it?

03:07:58.080 --> 03:08:02.300
[Guest]: Yeah, so I'll start with the why and then come to the course earlier.

03:08:02.300 --> 03:08:07.160
[Guest]: So the idea is, again, it's about thinking of the demand side and the supply side, right?

03:08:07.160 --> 03:08:10.280
[Guest]: So we are trying to address the demand side here.

03:08:10.280 --> 03:08:15.760
[Guest]: The idea is that if our discourse is better, if we are asking the right things of the government

03:08:15.760 --> 03:08:19.000
[Guest]: and the right questions, maybe we might get the right answers, right?

03:08:19.000 --> 03:08:24.040
[Guest]: So it's trying to address that demand side of the question.

03:08:24.040 --> 03:08:29.840
[Guest]: And that's why there are a lot of think tanks, you know, think tanks in US have are much

03:08:29.840 --> 03:08:35.960
[Guest]: older than the Indian Republic itself, you know, Brookings completed 100 years in 2016.

03:08:35.960 --> 03:08:36.960
[Guest]: Can you imagine?

03:08:36.960 --> 03:08:39.520
[Guest]: So think tanks do exist.

03:08:39.520 --> 03:08:44.760
[Guest]: But the idea is, a lot of think tanks are either in capitals, thinking about changing

03:08:44.760 --> 03:08:47.560
[Guest]: policy with the policymakers, right?

03:08:47.560 --> 03:08:51.640
[Guest]: But our thinking was that you need the other side as well, right?

03:08:51.640 --> 03:08:56.600
[Guest]: Address the demand side as well, improve the level of public discourse, then change will

03:08:56.600 --> 03:08:59.080
[Guest]: happen regardless of who is at the helm.

03:08:59.080 --> 03:09:04.400
[Guest]: So that's why this course exists, and it is trying to address the demand side.

03:09:04.400 --> 03:09:09.160
[Guest]: Now what we are seeing is it also probably addresses the supply side, you know, because

03:09:09.160 --> 03:09:15.160
[Guest]: in one sense, we also found out gaps, like the fact that most of the technology companies

03:09:15.160 --> 03:09:19.120
[Guest]: which now exist, are often operating in gray areas, right?

03:09:19.120 --> 03:09:24.200
[Guest]: Not because they are shady, but the fact that our government laws are such, right?

03:09:24.200 --> 03:09:26.360
[Guest]: You need laws which are old style.

03:09:26.360 --> 03:09:31.520
[Guest]: And then, for example, I'll just give you an example, one of our alumni operates this

03:09:31.520 --> 03:09:33.640
[Guest]: scooter rental startup.

03:09:33.640 --> 03:09:38.960
[Guest]: And the idea was, there was no law for that, you know, and the law prohibited many things

03:09:38.960 --> 03:09:40.360
[Guest]: that they wanted to do.

03:09:40.360 --> 03:09:46.360
[Guest]: So you need public policy to come in and work with the government, tell them that why certain

03:09:46.360 --> 03:09:50.120
[Guest]: things are better, why it will help the ecosystem as a whole.

03:09:50.120 --> 03:09:55.880
[Guest]: It's not just lobbying for your company, but it's about explaining why certain things when

03:09:55.880 --> 03:09:59.680
[Guest]: banned can result in certain other consequences.

03:09:59.680 --> 03:10:04.000
[Guest]: And when you allow it, what are the economic benefits you can unlock, right?

03:10:04.000 --> 03:10:07.800
[Guest]: So it's a really interesting thing to look at.

03:10:07.800 --> 03:10:13.200
[Guest]: The second thing from the supply side also is, for example, people within the government

03:10:13.200 --> 03:10:19.960
[Guest]: also, maybe armed forces officers or others, might be looking at a thing from the lens

03:10:19.960 --> 03:10:21.360
[Guest]: that they are used to, right?

03:10:21.360 --> 03:10:26.640
[Guest]: So for example, armed forces officials will know everything about the tactical side of

03:10:26.640 --> 03:10:27.960
[Guest]: things, right?

03:10:27.960 --> 03:10:31.320
[Guest]: But how does that relate to India's economic goals?

03:10:31.320 --> 03:10:37.080
[Guest]: How does, you know, India not having good relations with the US impact India's defense,

03:10:37.080 --> 03:10:43.280
[Guest]: for example, right, or China, for that matter, these things, the bigger connections, the

03:10:43.280 --> 03:10:47.280
[Guest]: course is able to make, you know, and that is useful for people who are within the government

03:10:47.280 --> 03:10:48.280
[Guest]: as well.

03:10:48.280 --> 03:10:52.720
[Guest]: The third one, yeah, a lot of people are aspirants of UPSC, etc.

03:10:52.720 --> 03:10:56.200
[Guest]: They are also the type of people who join the course.

03:10:56.200 --> 03:11:00.080
[Guest]: And what we tell them is this course will not help you crack the UPSC.

03:11:00.080 --> 03:11:01.080
[Guest]: Definitely not.

03:11:01.080 --> 03:11:02.960
[Guest]: That's a clear thing, which is upfront.

03:11:02.960 --> 03:11:08.400
[Guest]: But it might help you once you get into the government, the way you will think about price

03:11:08.400 --> 03:11:13.360
[Guest]: caps, the way you will think about incentives, the way you think about government itself

03:11:13.360 --> 03:11:19.520
[Guest]: as a complex of principles and agents will be definitely different, you know, so that

03:11:19.520 --> 03:11:24.640
[Guest]: is how I would say why public policy sort of learning it is important.

03:11:24.640 --> 03:11:28.640
[Guest]: It is important, even if you just want to be a more engaged citizen.

03:11:28.640 --> 03:11:32.880
[Guest]: And it is also important if you want to actually go into the government.

03:11:32.880 --> 03:11:34.280
[Guest]: Now coming to the course.

03:11:34.280 --> 03:11:36.360
[Guest]: So the course is called GCPP.

03:11:36.360 --> 03:11:42.680
[Guest]: And it started way back in 2012, Nitin and co-founders of Takshashila got that together.

03:11:42.680 --> 03:11:50.360
[Guest]: And the background of this was actually the citizens against corruption, that entire movement

03:11:50.360 --> 03:11:52.080
[Guest]: that had happened, right.

03:11:52.080 --> 03:11:56.440
[Guest]: And a lot of people asked that, you know, if that's not the right way to go.

03:11:56.440 --> 03:12:00.920
[Guest]: And I think Nitin had written a column on why that's not the right way to go.

03:12:00.920 --> 03:12:01.920
[Guest]: Yeah.

03:12:01.920 --> 03:12:06.840
[Guest]: So the idea was, what is the way out then if protests were not the way to go?

03:12:06.840 --> 03:12:11.920
[Guest]: And that was the reason why the course started that, you know, we actually didn't have good

03:12:11.920 --> 03:12:14.320
[Guest]: answers, if people have this question.

03:12:14.320 --> 03:12:20.720
[Guest]: And the idea was that, then can we get smart people together, and at least discuss some

03:12:20.720 --> 03:12:21.720
[Guest]: of these concepts.

03:12:21.720 --> 03:12:26.280
[Guest]: It's not so much teaching, but just bringing people from different disciplines together,

03:12:26.280 --> 03:12:30.240
[Guest]: and exposing them to certain ideas that they wouldn't have come across.

03:12:30.240 --> 03:12:32.960
[Guest]: So that's the origin of the GCPP.

03:12:32.960 --> 03:12:38.200
[Guest]: And it's sort of in its 30th cohort, it's a 12 week course.

03:12:38.200 --> 03:12:41.880
[Guest]: And it is meant for people who are working again, keep opportunity costs low.

03:12:41.880 --> 03:12:46.880
[Guest]: So people who want to learn about this, start learning it, even while you're working.

03:12:46.880 --> 03:12:49.760
[Guest]: And there are three main streams.

03:12:49.760 --> 03:12:54.400
[Guest]: One is the fundamentals of public policy, where we discuss these ideas, which we talked

03:12:54.400 --> 03:12:55.560
[Guest]: about today.

03:12:55.560 --> 03:13:00.680
[Guest]: The second one is economic reasoning, really getting people to know the fundamentals of

03:13:00.680 --> 03:13:02.240
[Guest]: microeconomics.

03:13:02.240 --> 03:13:04.880
[Guest]: And the third one is about public communication.

03:13:04.880 --> 03:13:09.680
[Guest]: So we talk a lot about writing, the importance of narratives, the importance of stakeholder

03:13:09.680 --> 03:13:11.320
[Guest]: management, etc.

03:13:11.320 --> 03:13:13.520
[Guest]: So these are the three components.

03:13:13.520 --> 03:13:20.280
[Guest]: And by the end of the course, people are equipped enough to write a policy proposal by themselves.

03:13:20.280 --> 03:13:27.080
[Guest]: So think through an entire policy question in a systematic manner and write a proposal

03:13:27.080 --> 03:13:28.440
[Guest]: down.

03:13:28.440 --> 03:13:32.320
[Guest]: And that sort of is really pathbreaking for a lot of people.

03:13:32.320 --> 03:13:37.900
[Guest]: It was for me definitely when I did this in 2013, because it gave me the confidence that

03:13:37.900 --> 03:13:43.040
[Guest]: I can systematically think of a problem and bring out a solution, even though I've never

03:13:43.040 --> 03:13:44.440
[Guest]: worked in the government, right.

03:13:44.440 --> 03:13:48.680
[Guest]: So just that act sort of gives in a lot of confidence.

03:13:48.680 --> 03:13:54.840
[Guest]: And what it did to me personally, was it changed the way I parse news, just add a completely

03:13:54.840 --> 03:13:59.240
[Guest]: new frame of reference to look at the happenings in the world.

03:13:59.240 --> 03:14:04.440
[Guest]: Otherwise, it's very easy to get dejected by what happens in the world, and just think

03:14:04.440 --> 03:14:05.920
[Guest]: that everything's going wrong.

03:14:05.920 --> 03:14:12.040
[Guest]: But that helped me put some frame of reference to why things happen the way they do.

03:14:12.040 --> 03:14:15.520
[Guest]: And that was like a big learning point for me.

03:14:15.520 --> 03:14:18.680
[Amit Varma]: You know, a note for my listeners, one thing I sometimes do is at the end of every year,

03:14:18.680 --> 03:14:22.280
[Amit Varma]: I kind of like to look back and say that how has this year changed me?

03:14:22.280 --> 03:14:23.680
[Amit Varma]: How have I grown in this year?

03:14:23.680 --> 03:14:25.120
[Amit Varma]: What have I done in this year?

03:14:25.120 --> 03:14:28.400
[Amit Varma]: And the answer is usually disappointing, and I could have done so much more.

03:14:28.400 --> 03:14:32.880
[Amit Varma]: And you know, Jan 1, I am lying there depressing, shit, I wasted another year.

03:14:32.880 --> 03:14:37.200
[Amit Varma]: But I would say that, one, it's a good practice, and two, this course is like 12 weeks, like

03:14:37.200 --> 03:14:42.320
[Amit Varma]: it's 12 weekends, right, basically Saturdays, you spend a few hours, you know, just do it.

03:14:42.320 --> 03:14:46.880
[Amit Varma]: If you if you have any interest in this subject, which I assume you do, because you've heard

03:14:46.880 --> 03:14:50.600
[Amit Varma]: more than three hours of Pranay chatting with me about just these subjects.

03:14:50.600 --> 03:14:53.640
[Amit Varma]: So you know, why not could be could be life changing.

03:14:53.640 --> 03:14:57.920
[Amit Varma]: And even if it isn't life changing, at least you have another frame, you have a more refined

03:14:57.920 --> 03:14:59.840
[Amit Varma]: frame perhaps to look at the world.

03:14:59.840 --> 03:15:00.880
[Amit Varma]: And that's a good thing.

03:15:00.880 --> 03:15:05.280
[Amit Varma]: Let's get back to our Twitter questions, we asked questions.

03:15:05.280 --> 03:15:11.120
[Guest]: I would add to the summit, by the way, the course is not for the faint hearted in the

03:15:11.120 --> 03:15:16.080
[Guest]: sense that beyond the Saturdays, there are assignments and all to do.

03:15:16.080 --> 03:15:22.400
[Guest]: But what I can guarantee is, you will enjoy it, it's, we have a lot of games, etc.

03:15:22.400 --> 03:15:25.160
[Guest]: And the idea is, it's, it's a lot of fun.

03:15:25.160 --> 03:15:29.160
[Guest]: You don't want to have a course which people are taking out of their own volition to be

03:15:29.160 --> 03:15:30.160
[Guest]: boring, right.

03:15:30.160 --> 03:15:32.760
[Guest]: So that's one thing we are very conscious about.

03:15:32.760 --> 03:15:37.160
[Guest]: And making it more fun is the whole aim, but it is rigorous.

03:15:37.160 --> 03:15:42.800
[Guest]: So a lot of people need to put in at least I would say, eight to 10 hours a week for

03:15:42.800 --> 03:15:43.800
[Guest]: this course.

03:15:43.800 --> 03:15:47.280
[Guest]: So that will give you the results that you want.

03:15:47.280 --> 03:15:49.080
[Amit Varma]: Excellent, highly recommended.

03:15:49.080 --> 03:15:54.520
[Amit Varma]: Meanwhile, we better get back to Twitter, otherwise people will go crazy, we asked questions

03:15:54.520 --> 03:15:56.000
[Amit Varma]: and we were ignored.

03:15:56.000 --> 03:15:57.000
[Amit Varma]: Not a good thing.

03:15:57.000 --> 03:16:01.400
[Amit Varma]: Asad wants to know, how does he fight procrastination in daily life?

03:16:01.400 --> 03:16:04.680
[Amit Varma]: And then stuff about your economic student journey, which you've covered, but how do

03:16:04.680 --> 03:16:05.680
[Amit Varma]: you fight procrastination?

03:16:05.680 --> 03:16:07.520
[Guest]: That's a good question.

03:16:07.520 --> 03:16:15.080
[Guest]: I think just having those habits help, you know, so I used to procrastinate a lot on

03:16:15.080 --> 03:16:20.560
[Guest]: again writing as well as a bunch of things that I have to write, but they never translate

03:16:20.560 --> 03:16:25.400
[Guest]: into so their idea is there, but it's never you don't write it.

03:16:25.400 --> 03:16:32.480
[Guest]: But things like having a newsletter, etc helped me a lot, because I know that you have to

03:16:32.480 --> 03:16:37.200
[Guest]: get something out by that time, you know, so there's no room for procrastination after

03:16:37.200 --> 03:16:41.200
[Guest]: that, if you have promised your reader that you're going to get something out, you have

03:16:41.200 --> 03:16:42.200
[Guest]: to do it.

03:16:42.200 --> 03:16:46.360
[Guest]: So I think that is what you put yourself in these situations.

03:16:46.360 --> 03:16:47.360
[Guest]: That sort of helps.

03:16:47.360 --> 03:16:50.800
[Guest]: Otherwise, I mean, for example, if you have a column, it helps, right?

03:16:50.800 --> 03:16:54.400
[Guest]: You wouldn't have that issue if you have a column, because you know, you have a deadline.

03:16:54.400 --> 03:16:55.840
[Guest]: But I haven't had a column.

03:16:55.840 --> 03:17:01.440
[Guest]: So it's used to write an op-ed, then the editors will sit for it for two weeks.

03:17:01.440 --> 03:17:05.540
[Guest]: By that time, you will anyways be dejected about that topic, right?

03:17:05.540 --> 03:17:10.600
[Guest]: So that didn't give me that sense of writing regularly.

03:17:10.600 --> 03:17:16.720
[Guest]: But when you have something like, say a newsletter, or you have promised yourself that I'm going

03:17:16.720 --> 03:17:21.760
[Guest]: to get something out a particular week or a particular day, then I think things fall

03:17:21.760 --> 03:17:23.720
[Guest]: into place, you just make it work.

03:17:23.720 --> 03:17:26.640
[Guest]: So it's promising yourself rather than anything else.

03:17:26.640 --> 03:17:29.880
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, this is I think, what psychologists call a commitment device.

03:17:29.880 --> 03:17:32.920
[Amit Varma]: And I started a newsletter for the same reason.

03:17:32.920 --> 03:17:37.040
[Amit Varma]: But then a lot of shit happened, personal shit happened in April, and I just got swamped.

03:17:37.040 --> 03:17:39.160
[Amit Varma]: And I didn't write it for the longest time.

03:17:39.160 --> 03:17:42.320
[Amit Varma]: So I need to revive one of these days, because I thought I'll do two or three a week.

03:17:42.320 --> 03:17:45.920
[Amit Varma]: And I'm just, I haven't done it for months, but I'm going to get back to it.

03:17:45.920 --> 03:17:50.120
[Amit Varma]: And commitment devices are useful, like, you know, I would like thank God my power, you

03:17:50.120 --> 03:17:54.240
[Amit Varma]: know, the scene in the unseen is a weekly podcast, and because now it has a listenership

03:17:54.240 --> 03:17:58.440
[Amit Varma]: that it does, that I have to come out with it, no matter what happens, like recent weeks,

03:17:58.440 --> 03:18:01.400
[Amit Varma]: I felt very burnt out things haven't always been going well.

03:18:01.400 --> 03:18:05.420
[Amit Varma]: But I have to come out with it every week, because there are just too many people who

03:18:05.420 --> 03:18:08.120
[Amit Varma]: listen to it and will be disappointed if I don't.

03:18:08.120 --> 03:18:09.120
[Amit Varma]: And that's great.

03:18:09.120 --> 03:18:10.640
[Amit Varma]: And maybe the newsletter had just started.

03:18:10.640 --> 03:18:16.080
[Amit Varma]: So it hadn't reached that sort of cultic level, where I have to worry about those things.

03:18:16.080 --> 03:18:19.240
[Amit Varma]: So commitment devices are useful, do set them for yourself.

03:18:19.240 --> 03:18:23.600
[Amit Varma]: Be like Pranay, don't be like me when it comes to things like newsletters.

03:18:23.600 --> 03:18:29.480
[Guest]: But Amit, I would just add, I'm so amazed that you've done this podcast alone for week

03:18:29.480 --> 03:18:33.560
[Guest]: on week, 200 and what 30 odd times.

03:18:33.560 --> 03:18:39.000
[Guest]: One commitment device that works for me is always work with someone else.

03:18:39.000 --> 03:18:44.360
[Guest]: Most of the things I do, and it also comes from this frame that public policy in general

03:18:44.360 --> 03:18:47.240
[Guest]: is a team sport, you will be wrong.

03:18:47.240 --> 03:18:51.240
[Guest]: So you it's better to have someone else so that you can refine your idea.

03:18:51.240 --> 03:18:55.040
[Guest]: So I try to work with people.

03:18:55.040 --> 03:18:59.480
[Guest]: And that helps, you know, then both people can inspire each other, right.

03:18:59.480 --> 03:19:04.240
[Guest]: And sometimes when you are not in a mood to write, you see RSJ has already written his

03:19:04.240 --> 03:19:09.000
[Guest]: edition, then you will be under pressure and say, Okay, now I have to write there's no

03:19:09.000 --> 03:19:12.940
[Guest]: way that I can ditch what someone else has already written.

03:19:12.940 --> 03:19:19.280
[Guest]: So that similarly with Puliyabazi, because Saurabh is there, I am inspired to keep doing

03:19:19.280 --> 03:19:20.760
[Guest]: things week on week.

03:19:20.760 --> 03:19:21.960
[Guest]: So I guess that also helps.

03:19:21.960 --> 03:19:27.320
[Guest]: So I'm really amazed how you've done this alone over 232 weeks, how have you done that?

03:19:27.320 --> 03:19:28.560
[Amit Varma]: I have somehow done it.

03:19:28.560 --> 03:19:30.200
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I've somehow done it.

03:19:30.200 --> 03:19:31.640
[Amit Varma]: So it I mean, it is what it is.

