03:20:10.160 --> 03:20:15.360
[Amit Varma]: So Durga asks, why is it so difficult to bridge theoretical knowledge and policy implementation

03:20:15.360 --> 03:20:16.440
[Amit Varma]: in India?

03:20:16.440 --> 03:20:18.920
[Amit Varma]: Why do we fail to see the unintended?

03:20:18.920 --> 03:20:22.120
[Amit Varma]: What would a roadmap to fix this look like?

03:20:22.120 --> 03:20:27.680
[Guest]: Yeah, I think the road to this is just understanding things better, right.

03:20:27.680 --> 03:20:32.920
[Guest]: And that's why being equipped with public policy knowledge from wherever you get it,

03:20:32.920 --> 03:20:38.960
[Guest]: you do a course or you read up things by yourself is really important.

03:20:38.960 --> 03:20:45.720
[Guest]: Because again, like public policy, we already come up with so much baggage to it that we

03:20:45.720 --> 03:20:48.080
[Guest]: already have solutions, right.

03:20:48.080 --> 03:20:53.360
[Guest]: And Land Pritchett has a great video, I mean, again, we can share it about selling solutions

03:20:53.360 --> 03:20:55.320
[Guest]: versus defining problems.

03:20:55.320 --> 03:21:00.640
[Guest]: So even people who think they are rational, will actually frame a policy problem as a

03:21:00.640 --> 03:21:03.060
[Guest]: lack of their favorite solution.

03:21:03.060 --> 03:21:07.500
[Guest]: So they will say, okay, what's the problem with education, there are not enough teachers.

03:21:07.500 --> 03:21:10.200
[Guest]: So the only solution to that is have more teachers, right.

03:21:10.200 --> 03:21:16.880
[Guest]: So you've already thought of a solution and you're framing a problem as an absence of

03:21:16.880 --> 03:21:20.000
[Guest]: it, you know, so it's a solution masquerading as a problem.

03:21:20.000 --> 03:21:27.560
[Guest]: But the idea would be, can you think so the hack that he gives us a problem is not a problem

03:21:27.560 --> 03:21:32.440
[Guest]: until and unless you can have three mutually exclusive solutions for solving that same

03:21:32.440 --> 03:21:33.480
[Guest]: problem, right.

03:21:33.480 --> 03:21:39.240
[Guest]: So if you look at it from that frame of reference, maybe you will be able to define problems

03:21:39.240 --> 03:21:41.760
[Guest]: better before even coming to solutions, right.

03:21:41.760 --> 03:21:44.040
[Guest]: So such things are needed.

03:21:44.040 --> 03:21:49.320
[Guest]: And second thing is, again, just being open to the fact that you don't know the world,

03:21:49.320 --> 03:21:55.480
[Guest]: you know, use of knowledge in society, the essay that Hayek wrote, those kinds of things

03:21:55.480 --> 03:21:57.560
[Guest]: illustrate that we don't know enough.

03:21:57.560 --> 03:22:04.000
[Guest]: So if we are open to our priors being updated through public policy, then we'll be able

03:22:04.000 --> 03:22:05.760
[Guest]: to anticipate the unintended.

03:22:05.760 --> 03:22:11.480
[Guest]: Most of the times I often feel that people will already have solutions, they've already

03:22:11.480 --> 03:22:15.880
[Guest]: figured out that this is the way it works, then there is no learning to be had, right.

03:22:15.880 --> 03:22:23.560
[Guest]: Then there's no point of reading or taking a course just to reaffirm your existing biases,

03:22:23.560 --> 03:22:25.520
[Guest]: then what's the point?

03:22:25.520 --> 03:22:31.440
[Guest]: So that's why I think we fall into this idea that we already know things.

03:22:31.440 --> 03:22:34.960
[Guest]: So public policy, what do we need to learn about it?

03:22:34.960 --> 03:22:37.560
[Guest]: What's there to be learned from economic reasoning?

03:22:37.560 --> 03:22:44.280
[Guest]: But if we go back a step and try to think of these disciplines in a systematic manner,

03:22:44.280 --> 03:22:48.480
[Guest]: then maybe we'll be able to anticipate the unintended much better.

03:22:48.480 --> 03:22:49.480
