03:25:24.640 --> 03:25:26.880
[Amit Varma]: yourself that and that makes a difference.

03:25:26.880 --> 03:25:30.360
[Amit Varma]: So is that like a fair summation of the tradeoffs as it were?

03:25:30.360 --> 03:25:37.040
[Guest]: Yeah, I would say the systematic learning is absolutely necessary in public policy,

03:25:37.040 --> 03:25:43.280
[Guest]: especially because you need a network of people to correct you, because as we said, we'll

03:25:43.280 --> 03:25:46.080
[Guest]: have biases, we'll never learn from them.

03:25:46.080 --> 03:25:51.360
[Guest]: So and having a systematic way of thinking is absolutely necessary.

03:25:51.360 --> 03:25:56.920
[Guest]: I would just say it's not necessary that you have a particular degree which says that you

03:25:56.920 --> 03:25:57.920
[Guest]: know this, you know.

03:25:57.920 --> 03:26:04.400
[Guest]: So yeah, maybe you take a bachelor's course, a level course in a college which is teaching

03:26:04.400 --> 03:26:09.560
[Guest]: you this or you might just take an elective in a college which teaches is that is also

03:26:09.560 --> 03:26:10.560
[Guest]: fine.

03:26:10.560 --> 03:26:14.760
[Guest]: But I was just referring to the question that you need a master's in a particular thing.

03:26:14.760 --> 03:26:21.000
[Guest]: But I definitely think more than systematic thinking, it's just being with other people,

03:26:21.000 --> 03:26:27.000
[Guest]: other smart people learning from them, learning their frames of reference, to see what you

03:26:27.000 --> 03:26:32.640
