03:28:29.520 --> 03:28:35.320
[Guest]: Yeah, the great example is about the economic growth, right?

03:28:35.320 --> 03:28:39.760
[Guest]: This idea in 1991, whatever changed, the change happened at the margin.

03:28:39.760 --> 03:28:47.080
[Guest]: Now you can argue that people who were the most disadvantaged in India didn't face any

03:28:47.080 --> 03:28:49.920
[Guest]: benefits of this, there is still poverty, etc.

03:28:49.920 --> 03:28:57.000
[Guest]: But at the margin, people who had say some benefit of education before or had some skill

03:28:57.000 --> 03:29:01.560
[Guest]: before, benefited immensely from whatever has happened since 1991.

03:29:01.560 --> 03:29:02.560
[Guest]: Right.

03:29:02.560 --> 03:29:07.360
[Guest]: So that is what it means that change happens at the margin, change might not always happen

03:29:07.360 --> 03:29:10.560
[Guest]: to the most disadvantaged section.

03:29:10.560 --> 03:29:17.600
[Guest]: But that doesn't mean that, that government should focus only on the most disadvantaged

03:29:17.600 --> 03:29:18.600
[Guest]: section, right?

03:29:18.600 --> 03:29:23.040
[Guest]: If it can make changes at the margin, a lot of good things happen.

03:29:23.040 --> 03:29:26.080
[Amit Varma]: A lot of good things happen to the most disadvantaged also.

03:29:26.080 --> 03:29:27.080
[Amit Varma]: Yes.

03:29:27.080 --> 03:29:31.360
[Amit Varma]: Like I think you'll agree with me about Mahatma Gandhi's metric for public policy.

03:29:31.360 --> 03:29:36.280
[Amit Varma]: He didn't use these exact words, but his metric was that for every action, the one thing I

03:29:36.280 --> 03:29:40.280
[Amit Varma]: ask myself is, what will be the impact of this on the poorest of the poor?

03:29:40.280 --> 03:29:43.760
[Amit Varma]: And I think for all of us in India, this is a good metric to have.

03:29:43.760 --> 03:29:49.480
[Amit Varma]: And all my arguments for, you know, more individual freedom, respecting individual autonomy, economic

03:29:49.480 --> 03:29:55.440
[Amit Varma]: freedom, especially, all come down from this, that the impact on the poor is the only thing

03:29:55.440 --> 03:29:56.440
[Amit Varma]: that I look at.

03:29:56.440 --> 03:29:58.560
[Amit Varma]: And that is why I support all of these things in.

03:29:58.560 --> 03:30:05.080
[Guest]: Yeah, but there's a nuance here, Amit, like, for example, if you have limited resources,

03:30:05.080 --> 03:30:08.840
[Guest]: and you want to bring change, which will be in the case of the government, where would

03:30:08.840 --> 03:30:10.800
[Guest]: the government put its money on?

03:30:10.800 --> 03:30:11.800
[Guest]: Right?

03:30:11.800 --> 03:30:12.800
[Guest]: That is a challenge.

03:30:12.800 --> 03:30:18.480
[Guest]: So for example, you want to bring out economic growth, you want to bring make everyone prosperous,

03:30:18.480 --> 03:30:24.360
[Guest]: maybe the effort that you would require to do this in a far flung village will require

03:30:24.360 --> 03:30:30.760
[Guest]: more effort, more resources, whereas maybe you can impact a lot more number of people

03:30:30.760 --> 03:30:36.640
[Guest]: who are at the margin and require some barriers that government has artificially put to be

03:30:36.640 --> 03:30:37.640
[Guest]: brought down.

03:30:37.640 --> 03:30:38.640
[Guest]: Right?

03:30:38.640 --> 03:30:43.480
[Guest]: So the ideas both are important, but it shouldn't happen that the government says, I will stop,

03:30:43.480 --> 03:30:48.280
[Guest]: I will only do things when I can influence the poorest of the poor.

03:30:48.280 --> 03:30:56.000
[Guest]: That never happens, and that will just lead to us expending humongous amount of resources

03:30:56.000 --> 03:31:00.480
